{ Beginning your journey with these seven model games is a good place to start. This first game discusses the relative nature of having a space advantage. It shows that the space advantage is a means to an end, which receives its value from its concrete effectiveness.   This game serves as an example for a tolerable kind of space advantage. In the comments, I will compare it with White's space advantage in the Bayonet Attack and explain why it isn't tolerable. The other games are only lightly annotated, as they don't show us what we have to do, but what scenarios we would like to avoid. In any case, the games will increase your appreciation for the fantastic system you are about to learn.  The annotations before move 17 are given for readers who are interested in the Hedgehog. Everyone, who wants to study this game in the more narrow context of the Bayonet Attack may directly jump to move 17. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ The Kveinys Variation had its time in the sun, but is now considered as dubious. Its basic idea is to reach a Hedgehog/Scheveningen/Kan type of position where White's knight is passively placed on b3. }
5. Nb3
{ White moves the knight to a secure location, as  5.Nc3  Bc5  gives Black good chances for equality.   Unfortunately, for Sicilian players like me, the line  5.Be3  Bc5  6.Na3!  leads to a distinct advantage. }
5... Qc7
{ After doing its job  @@StartBracket@@dislocating the knight@@EndBracket@@, the queen moves to the real destination, where it isn't exposed to Be3 or a2-a4-a5. }
6. Bd3 a6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Qe2
{ Apparently, White wanted to stay flexible and keep all the options open, i.e. to go for a Hedgehog position with c2-c4 or to quickly develop with Nc3. However, a Hedgehog position is best realized by playing 8.c4 without delay.   8.c4  d6  9.Nc3  Nbd7  10.f4  g6?  That was possible in the game, but is now refuted.  11.e5!  White is already winning.  11...dxe5?!  12.fxe5  Qxe5  13.Bf4  Qh5  14.Be2  Qh4  15.Qd2+-  . }
8... d6 9. c4
{ Now, it's too late.  9.f4  or  9.a4  would have given White chances for a slight advantage. }
9... Nbd7
{ A subtle move, leaving White the choice between committing himself to  10.f4  or abandoning the bishop pair. }
10. f4 { 10.Nc3  Ne5!  11.Be3  Be7= } 10... g6
{ This move was made possible by 9...Nd7, not only through leaving the bishop on f8 for the time being but also by provoking f2-f4. If you don't understand what I am talking about, don't worry. This is higher Hedgehog mathematics, but no rocket science yet. So let me explain.  White has two basic strategies against the Sicilian Hedgehog. He can play a@@EndBracket@@ on the queenside or b@@EndBracket@@ on the kingside.   In case of strategy a@@EndBracket@@, Black's bishop is needed on e7. Against strategy b@@EndBracket@@ however, Black's king feels much safer with the bishop on g7 and with the pawn on g6, neutralizing the bishop on d3. For this reason, we see the maneuvers ...Re8, ...Bf8, ...g6, and ...Bg7 often happening in this position type, also in the Scheveningen. Obviously, Black is saving 3 precious tempi when developing the bishop to g7 directly. But before doing this, he had to wait until White was committed to f2-f4.  This commitment disabled White from pursuing the queenside strategy, as with both pawns @@StartBracket@@e4 and f4@@EndBracket@@ and adjacent squares being weak, rolling out a queenside expansion would lead to fatal overextension. Consequently, White is now caught in a setup, which is rendered ineffective right from the start. With a black bishop on g7, there simply is no attack. }
11. Nc3
{ Evidently, the Hedgehog is most vulnerable in the early phase of the opening, before Black has finished his development. Hence, any kind of fast play by White has to be carefully checked.   Before opting for 10...g6, I had to calculate the consequences of 11.e5, which, however, was no big deal.  11.e5?  dxe5  12.fxe5  Qxe5  13.Qxe5?  Nxe5  14.Rxf6  Nxd3-+  . }
11... Bg7 12. Be3 b6 { Finally, all the spines of the beast are erected. } 13.
Nd4 { Reviving the knight and unblocking the b-pawn. } 13... O-O 14. Rac1 Bb7
15. b4 { This is more of a defensive move, as ...Nc5 had to be prevented. }
15... Rac8 16. Nf3
{ Black would soon be ready for ...e6-e5, so the knight had to leave the center. }
16... Qb8
{ The queen withdraws from the line of fire and we see rook and bishop nicely converging on the square c3. Obviously, this didn't happen unnoticed by White, who decided to overprotect the knight. }
17. Bd2 Rfe8
{ The rook on e8 doesn't only prevent f4-f5, it also supports the pawn-breaks ...e6-e5 and ...d6-d5. As both parties have finished the mobilization of their troops, it is a good time to take stock and also discuss the topic of space advantage. As in the Bayonet Attack, White's space advantage is obvious, but there are a lot of differences:   1@@EndBracket@@ Black had no problems developing his pieces within his territory, despite being confined to three ranks.   2@@EndBracket@@ Black's pieces are better centralized than White's. White's bishops don't point towards the center.   3@@EndBracket@@ Black's major pieces have an open file to play on.   4@@EndBracket@@ Black has more pawn breaks at his disposal. There is ...b6-b5, ...d6-d5, ...e6-e5 and ...f7-f5 @@StartBracket@@after ...Nh5@@EndBracket@@.   5@@EndBracket@@ Black only has two potential weaknesses, the pawns on d6 and b6. However, both aren't de facto weaknesses, as they can't be easily attacked.   6@@EndBracket@@ Actually, it is White who has to deal with his many exposed pawns and squares.   7@@EndBracket@@ Black has the better king, as White's king misses his f-pawn. Although the position is roughly equal, I prefer Black, as his position is easier to play. White has to permanently watch out for Black's many pawn breaks. }
18. Kh1 Nh5
{ That's an important motif in the g6-structure of the Hedgehog. Now, the dark-squared bishop becomes alive and the knight presses against the f-pawn, in cooperation with the queen. More concretely, many pawn advances are in the air, such as ...e6-e5 and ...f7-f5, but first and foremost ...d6-d5. }
19. g4
{ White falls for the provocation. Five pawns on the fourth rank are normally a sign, that something went wrong on White's side of the Hedgehog. It is true, 19... d5 was a threat, but there were better ways to cope with it.   A@@EndBracket@@  19.a3?  I am using this as a zero move, in order to demonstrate Black's idea.  19...d5!  20.e5   20.cxd5?  Nxf4-+   20.Ng5?  dxc4  21.Bxc4  h6  22.Nh3   22.Nxf7  Rxc4  23.Qxc4  Kxf7∓  Black's minor pieces are stronger than White's rook and pawn.  22...Qa8  Once f2-f4 has been played in the Hedgehog/Sicilian, the pressure on the long diagonal might become an issue for White.  23.Bd3  Red8  24.Rfe1  f5  25.Bb1  b5  26.Ba2  Nf8∓  There is a lot of weakness Black can try to exploit.  20...dxc4  21.Be4   21.Bxc4?  Bh6  22.Ne4  b5  23.Bb3  Bxf4∓  f5  22.Bxb7  Qxb7  23.b5  Bf8⩱   B@@EndBracket@@  19.Qf2!  Removing the queen from the influence of Black's rook and at the same time exerting latent pressure against the f-pawn.  Now,  19...f5=  ,  19...Qa8=  ,  19...Rc7=  , but after  19...d5?!  20.cxd5  Nxf4  21.Ne1  g5  22.Ne2↑  , White has the initiative. }
19... Nhf6 20. h3 Qa8 21. Kh2
{ The king will be tactically exposed on that diagonal.   21.Kg1  d5!  22.cxd5   22.e5  dxc4  23.Bxc4  Bxf3  24.Qxf3  Rxc4-+  Nxe4!  Here, we see the power of the rook on e8.  23.Bxe4   23.dxe6?  Ng3-+  exd5  24.Nxd5  Bxd5  25.Bxd5  Qxd5  26.Rxc8  Rxc8∓  White's position is full of weaknesses. }
21... d5
{ That's not the first time in the history of the Hedgehog, that the appearance of the second black pawn on the fifth rank announces a winning position. }
22. e5
{ White immediately admits failure and tries to confine the damage.   22.cxd5  exd5  23.e5  Ne4  24.Nb1   24.g5  Unfortunately for White, preventing 24...f6 doesn't do the job.  24...Nxd2  25.Qxd2   25.Nxd2  Nxe5-+  d4!  26.Nxd4  Nxe5!  Here you see, that h2 is not the safest of squares for the king.  27.fxe5  Bxe5+  28.Rf4  Red8  29.Nde2  Qb8  30.Rcf1  Qd6-+   24.Bxe4  dxe4  25.Ng5  Nxe5!  Again, it's White vulnerable king, that turns the balance.  26.fxe5  Bxe5+  27.Kg1  f6  28.Ngxe4  b5  ,  with White's king and queen being that exposed, Black can take his time.  29.Rfe1  f5  30.gxf5  gxf5  31.Bf4  fxe4-+   24.Rfe1  Nxc3  25.Rxc3   25.Bxc3?  d4  26.Nxd4  Nxe5-+  Rxc3  26.Bxc3  d4!  Deflecting the knight from covering e5.  27.Nxd4  Nxe5  28.Kg3  Rc8  29.Bb2  Nxd3  30.Qxd3  h6-+  White's king has no protection against the upcoming assault.  h6  Black will undermine White's pawn shield one way or the other.  25.Rxc8   25.h4  f6-+  Qxc8  26.Rc1  Qb8  27.Kg2  b5-+ }
22... dxc4 23. Bb1
{ 23.Bxc4?  Bxf3  24.Rxf3  Rxc4-+  White's queen is overloaded. } 23... Nd5 24.
Nxd5 { 24.Ne4  c3!  25.Nxc3  Nxb4-+ } 24... Bxd5
{ I won the opening battle, but when time trouble struck, I finally lost against my tactically resourceful opponent. }
25. Ng5 b5 26. Bc3 Qb8 27. Rce1 Nb6 28. Qf2 Na4 29. Bd4 c3 30. Bc2 Rc4 31. a3
Rd8 32. Ba7 Qb7 33. Nxh7 Kxh7 34. Qh4+ Bh6 35. Be3 Rh8 36. f5 exf5 37. Rxf5 Be4
38. Rd1 Qc7 39. Rxf7+ Qxf7 40. Qxh6+ *

