1. d4 d6 2. c4 e5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nc3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Be2 Nh6 7. O-O O-O 8. d5
Ne7 9. e4 f5 10. Ne1 f4 11. Rb1 g5 12. f3 Kh8 13. b4 Neg8 14. c5 Nf6
{ We have reached this basic structure via an unusual variation. White's slow play allowed Black to equalize without any problems. }
15. Nd3 { 15...g4 had to be prevented, while  15.g4=  leads to equality. }
15... g4 16. a4
{ 16...g3 had to be prevented.  16.fxg4  would be met by  16...Nhxg4∓  . }
16... g3
{ White lacks space for a successful defense and his counterplay is much too slow. }
17. hxg3
{ 17.h3  doesn't solve the problem, as White won't be able to prevent a successful bishop sacrifice on h3. See model games below. }
17... Nh5
{ Transferring the knight to g3, in order to play ...Qd8-h4-h1 mate is a standard motif. Imagine the whole King's Indian attacking architecture as a collection of different patterns. The only question is what motif to use in which situation.   17...fxg3?  18.Bg5  Qe8  19.Bh4  Qg6  leaves Black only with some initiative, but nothing tangible. }
18. g4
{ 18.gxf4  exf4  19.Bb2  Rg8  20.Nf2   20.e5  Nf5-+  Be5  with a winning attack. }
18... Ng3
{ White's king is caught in a cage, as  19.Kf2  Qh4  ,  threatening 20...Nxe4+ would force the king back to g1. }
19. a5
{ White surely doesn't defend in the best possible way, but in our context it makes no sense to come up with proposals, how he could have postponed defeat most effectively. }
19... Qh4 20. Nf2 Nf7 21. Nb5
{ 21.Nh3  Bf6  22.Bd2  Ng5  23.Kh2  h5-+  No fortress. } 21... Ng5 22. Re1 Rf6
23. Bf1 Rh6 { 23...h5! } 24. Nh3 Nxh3+ 25. gxh3 Nxf1 { 25...Bxg4! } 26. Kxf1
Qxh3+ { 26...Qg3! } 27. Ke2 Bxg4 28. fxg4 Qg3 29. Qb3
{ White resigned in view of  29...Rh2+  30.Kd1  Qxg4+  with mate in  2. } *

