1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. Be3 f5 11. f3 f4 12. Bf2 g5 13. b4 Nf6 14. c5 Ng6 15. cxd6
cxd6 16. Rc1 Rf7 17. a4 Bf8 18. a5 Bd7 19. Nb5 g4 20. Nxa7 g3 21. Bb6 Qe7 22.
Nb5 { 22.Bb5  could possibly lead to a slight advantage for White. } 22... Nh5
23. Kh1
{ In contrast to the last game, taking on g3 is completely out of the question. White embarks on another well-known strategy, which is to defend the dark squares on the kingside with the bishop.   23.h3?  Qh4-+ }
23... Qh4 24. Bg1 Rf6 25. Nc7
{ This leads to a beautiful finish and displays an important attacking mechanism. In order to understand the following annotations, you have to first play through the game and then you know what the alternatives try to prevent.   A@@EndBracket@@  25.Bd3?  gxh2  26.Bf2  Qg5  27.Nc3  Nh4  28.Bxh4  Qxh4  29.Ne2  Rg6∓  Black has dangerous threats.   B@@EndBracket@@  25.Qd2!  The key to salvation is the protection of both, f2 @@StartBracket@@see the game@@EndBracket@@ and g2 @@StartBracket@@see 26.Nd3@@EndBracket@@.  25...Bxb5   25...Ne7?  26.Bd3±  As the f2-square is protected, Black is running into a dead end.  26.Bxb5  gxh2  27.Bf2  Ng3+  28.Bxg3  fxg3  29.Rc7  Rf7  30.Rxf7  Kxf7  31.Qc3  Bh6∞  . }
25... Ne7 { Clearing the 6th rank for the rook. } 26. Nxa8
{ A@@EndBracket@@  26.Nd3  White is covering the important square f2 @@StartBracket@@see the game continuation@@EndBracket@@, but by doing so, the square g2 is being neglected.  26...Bh3!  27.Ne1  The knight has to return. Now, Black simply resumes the h-file routine.   27.gxh3  g2+  28.Kxg2  Rg6+  29.Kh1  Qxh3  30.Rf2  Ng3  27...Rh6  28.Bb5  gxh2  29.Bxh2   29.Bf2  Qxf2-+  see the game  Bc8  30.Kg1  Rb8-+   B@@EndBracket@@  26.Bb5  gxh2  27.Bxh2  Bxb5  28.Nxb5  Rh6  29.Kg1  Qxh2+!  That's similar to the main line, but here f1 will be the square.  30.Kxh2   30.Kf2  Qh4+  31.Ke2  Ng3+-+  is winning material.  Ng3+  31.Kg1  Rh1+  32.Kf2  Rxf1 }
26... gxh2 27. Bf2
{ 27.Bxh2  Ng3+  28.Kg1  Rh6  29.Nd3   29.Bc4  Nh1!  with mate in 2. That's another important motif.  Ng6!  Funny, that the now dormant dark-squared bishop is supposed to deal the lethal blow.   29...Nh1  also works, but White can still continue with  30.Rf2  30.Nb6  Be7-+  Threatening  31.--  Nxe2+  32.Qxe2  Qxh2+  33.Kf2  Bh4  mate. }
27... Qxf2
{ That's why protecting the f2-square with more pieces than the rook was mandatory @@StartBracket@@see respective sidelines@@EndBracket@@. Now, the mating square will be h1. }
