{ This game is interesting in terms of risk management. White is losing against an opponent who is 200 ELO points lower than himself. Usually, this can only happen in sharp, coinflip-like positions. The good thing about the Bayonet Attack is, that in general, our opponent can only see our king by using a pair of binoculars. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. Be3 f5 11. f3 f4 12. Bf2 g5 13. a4 Ng6 14. a5 Nf6 15. c5 Kh8
16. cxd6 cxd6 17. Nb5 g4 18. Bxa7 { 18.fxg4  Nxe4  19.Bxa7  Bd7  20.Bb6⩲ }
18... g3 19. Bb6 Qe7 20. h3 { 20.Qc2∞ } 20... Bxh3
{ Kawumm! That might look amazing, but in reality it's pretty much 101 for the King's Indian player. }
21. gxh3 Qd7 22. Bd3 { 22.Kg2  Nh4+-+ } 22... Qxh3
{ Again, White lacks space to defend the kingside. } 23. Qd2 Nh4 24. Nxd6 Nd7
{ Coming with a double threat. } 25. Rc1 { 25.Nf5  Nxf5  26.exf5  Nxb6-+ }
25... Nxb6 26. Rc7
{ 26.axb6  Rf6  27.Nf5  Rxf5  28.exf5  Bf6  That's an instructive position. White is up an entire rook, but yet completely helpless. He simply cannot get the square g2 under control, as h2 is also weak.  29.Be4  Rg8  There is no defense against  30.--  g2  . }
26... Rxa5
{ With material equality restored, White's position looks very grim. One of Black's ideas is to play ...Ra5-a1xe1, followed by ...g2. }
27. Nf5 Rxf5 { Black is in a sacrificial mood.  27...Nxf5  is also fine. } 28.
exf5 Rxd5 29. Qc2
{ 29.f6  Bxf6  30.Rxh7+  Kg8  31.Qg2  Qxg2+  32.Nxg2  Rxd3-+ } 29... Bf6 30.
Be4 Rd1 31. Qe2 Nd5 32. Bxd5 Rxd5 33. Rf7 Rd6 34. Nd3
{ This accelerates defeat in a hopeless position.   34.b3  Nxf5  35.Nd3  Nd4  36.Qg2  Qh5  37.Rxb7  e4  38.Nxf4  Nxf3+  39.Rxf3  Rd1+  40.Rf1  Bd4+-+ }
34... g2 35. Rf8+ Kg7 36. Rf7+ Kxf7 37. Nxe5+ Kg7 *

