[Black "Ftacnik, Lubomir vs. Cvitan, Ognjen"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game highlights the coin flip nature of the kings indian pawnstorm. White went from winning to losing in just one move. It also presents a rare motif, where the sacrifice on the square h3 happens without the presence of a pawn. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. Nd2 Ne8 10. b4 f5 11. c5 Nf6 12. f3 f4 13. Nc4 g5 14. a4 Ng6 15. Ba3 Rf7
16. b5 dxc5 17. Bxc5 h5 18. a5 g4 19. b6 g3 20. Kh1 Nh7 { 20...Bf8∞ } 21. d6
Qh4 22. Bg1 Bh3
{ Sacrifices on empty squares are called passive sacrifices. They are generally beautiful and easy to overlook. In this specific case, however, this sacrifice is bad. But sometimes, bad moves lead to good results. Correct would have been to play 22...Ng5 in order to perform the passive sacrifice with the knight in an appropriate moment.   22...Ng5!  This position is extremely complicated. I will just give a few lines, which could form the basis for your own analysis.  23.Ra2   23.dxc7  Bf8  24.Nd6  Nh3!  25.gxh3  Bxh3  26.Rf2  gxf2  27.Nxf7  Kxf7∞   23.bxc7?  Nh3!  24.gxh3  Bxh3  25.Rf2  gxf2  26.Bxf2  Qxf2-+  axb6  24.dxc7  Kh7∞ }
23. bxc7
{ White had the chance to stop Black's attack with an exchange sacrifice. I am sure that this is what he would have played with ease, if he only had seen what was about to happen, now.   23.gxh3  Qxh3  24.Rf2  gxf2  25.Bxf2  This position illustrates the general idea of a defensive sacrifice and even touches the essence of chess. Black's attack depended on the collaboration of all his pieces. Remove one piece and the whole mechanism breaks down. After all, chess is a holistic phenomenon, where the whole is more than the sum of its parts.  25...cxb6  26.axb6  a6  27.Bf1  Qd7  28.Na4+-  . }
23... Bxg2+ 24. Kxg2 Qh3+
{ White cannot be blamed for overlooking this beautiful queen sacrifice. This could have happened to any of us. }
25. Kxh3 Ng5+ 26. Kg2 Nh4+ *

