[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... f5 11. a4
{ Quickly expanding the space advantage on the queenside is the core element of White's strategy in the Bayonet Attack. At the same time, the knight is left on f3, in contrast to other lines, where it is moved to e1 or d2, as the option to play Nf3-g5-e6 is very valuable for White. }
11... Nf6
{ That's much better than  11...Nf4?  .  From f6, the knight really contributes to the position by fighting for the key square e4. }
12. a5
{ As Black's last move didn't contain a threat, White simply claims more space. Amongst others, the advance a5-a6 is now to be reckoned with, undermining the square c6 and consequently establishing an outpost for the knight on b5. There is also a prophylactic aspect to a5, as it prevents Black from playing the move himself. Thus, White has secured his control over the key square c5. }
12... Nxe4
{ This is clearly the most frequent continuation. Black creates space for the activation of his pieces.  12...fxe4  13.Ng5  leads to the same structure. }
13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Ng5 e3
{ This desperado is necessary, in order to activate the King's Indian bishop.  14...Bf5?  15.Bg4!  is won for White, thanks to the weak  square e6, amongst others.   Another alternative is  14...Nf5  15.Nxe4  Bh6  16.Bb2!  @@StartBracket@@White doesn't allow Black to exchange his problem-piece, which is cutting a lot of thin air from its current position.@@EndBracket@@  16...Nd4  There is no alternative way to activate the pieces.  17.Bxd4  exd4  18.Bg4  Bg7  19.h3  Black managed to upgrade his  dark-squared bishop, but he has to worry about the d-pawn and the square e6. }
15. Bxe3 Nf5 16. Bd2 Bh6
{ Now, White has to be careful not to play  17.Ne4?  Bxd2  18.Qxd2  Nd4  , letting Black exchange his bad bishop and establish a strong knight in the center. }
17. Qc1
{ As White doesn't want to exchange bishops, supporting the knight on its influential outpost is the right thing to do. Alternatively, White could think about the liquidation  17.Ne6  Bxe6  18.Bxh6  Nxh6  19.dxe6  Qe7  20.c5  , which is interesting, but more chaotic. }
17... Nd4 18. Bd1
{ White had to cover the square b3, so dropping the bishop back to f1 was not an option. At first glance it may appear artificial to place the bishop on d1, as it interferes with the coordination of the major pieces. This however, is an illusion, as the natural square for the queen's rook is a3. On d1 the bishop radiates towards both wings and has a lot of options, once Black's knight has disappeared. }
18... Qe7 19. Ra3 Bd7 20. a6 { 20.c5  Rae8  21.Rc3  is a good alternative. }
20... b6 21. Rd3 Rf5
{ The rook is too exposed on that square. Also after  21...Qg7  the situation doesn't look rosy for Black, but perhaps he can achieve a draw with best play:  22.b5  Rae8  23.g4!  After stabilizing the queenside, White can fully concentrate on his kingside ambitions.  The next two moves could be Rg3 and Be3. At a given moment, the h-pawn will be set in motion. }
22. h4 Qg7 23. Be3 Rff8 { 23...Raf8?  24.Qd2  R5f6  25.Ne4  Bxe3  26.fxe3+- }
24. f4 Rae8 25. fxe5 dxe5 26. c5
{ White is winning, as he has more space, the more active pieces and the better king. The knight on g5 is difficult to tolerate. But if it is taken, Black's king will be even more exposed. }
*

