1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... f5 11. a4
{ Quickly expanding the space advantage on the queenside is the core element of White's strategy in the Bayonet Attack. At the same time, the knight is left on f3, in contrast to other lines, where it is moves to e1 or d2, as the option to play Nf3-g5-e6 is very valuable for White. }
11... Nf6
{ That's much better than  11...Nf4?  .  From f6, the knight really contributes to the position by fighting for the key square e4. }
12. a5
{ As Black's last move didn't contain a threat, White simply claims more space. Amongst others, the advance a5-a6 is now to be reckoned with, undermining the square c6 and consequently establishing an outpost for the knight on b5. There is also a prophylactic aspect to a5, as it prevents Black from playing the move himself. Thus, White has secured his control over the key square c5. }
12... h6
{ Instead of conceding the square e4 to White, Black prefers to maintain the tension. Preventing Ng5 is not only a defensive measure against the idea Ng5-e6, it also threatens to play ...fxe4 after which White would lose some of his advantage. }
13. Nd2 { White stabilizes the center, before proceeding on the queenside. }
13... Kh7
{ Black stays patient and opts for a prophylactic move. By removing the king from the a2-g8 diagonal, he more or less prevents c5. }
14. Ba3
{ White should be careful not to prematurely play  14.c5?  as the center gets unstable:  14...fxe4  15.cxd6  cxd6  16.Ndxe4  Nexd5  17.Nxd5  Nxe4  18.Bf3  Nf6  19.Ra3+=  . }
14... b6
{ Black continues to maintain the tension in the center and now tries to bring his queen's rook into play. The alternatives are  a@@EndBracket@@  14...f4?  15.c5  g5  16.b5+-  This a bad version of the pawn storm structure, where White is clearly winning the race.  b@@EndBracket@@  14...fxe4?!  15.Ncxe4  Nf5  16.Bb2  @@StartBracket@@We arrived in a position type, known from the lines  13..fxe4  and  13..Nxe4  . If Black insist in placing his knight on  d4  , White might swap it off in an appropriate moment.@@EndBracket@@  16...Nd4  17.Bd3  Nxe4  18.Nxe4  Bf5  19.a6  b6  20.Bxd4!  exd4  21.Ng3+/-, with good prospects on the light squares. }
15. h3
{ As Black cannot do much, White increases his control over g4, which has some benefits, such as slowing down a potential pawn storm. Apart from that, semi-waiting moves always provide the opponent with the opportunity to harm himself. }
15... Rb8
{ There also is a@@EndBracket@@  15...g5?  16.exf5  Bxf5  17.Nf1!  Qd7  18.Ng3  Bg6  19.Bd3+-  White will be able to exploit Black's weakened light square color complex.   b@@EndBracket@@  15...c6?  16.dxc6  Nxc6  17.Bf3!  Nd4  18.exf5  Nxf3  19.Nxf3  gxf5  20.b5  Bb7  21.a6  Bxf3  22.Qxf3+-  Black suffers from structural problems. }
16. Bd3 Rf7 { Again, Black can only wait for White to act. } 17. a6 Bxa6
{ Black cannot let this pawn live and has to surrender the a-file. } 18. Bb2
Bc8 { 18...Qc8  19.Qc2  Nh5  20.Ra2  with easy play for White. } 19. Rxa7 Bd7
20. Qa1 Rf8 21. Qa3
{ White is in control of the position and is waiting for a good opportunity to play c4-c5. }
