Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... f5 11. a4
{ Quickly expanding the space advantage on the queenside is the core element of White's strategy in the Bayonet Attack. At the same time, the knight is left on f3, in contrast to other lines, where it is moves to e1 or d2, as the option to play Nf3-g5-e6 is very valuable for White. }
11... Nf6
{ That's much better than  11...Nf4?  .  From f6, the knight really contributes to the position by fighting for the key square e4. }
12. a5
{ As Black's last move didn't contain a threat, White simply claims more space. Amongst others, the advance a5-a6 is now to be reckoned with, undermining the square c6 and consequently establishing an outpost for the knight on b5. There is also a prophylactic aspect to a5, as it prevents Black from playing the move himself. Thus, White has secured his control over the key square c5. }
