13. Nd2 { White stabilizes the center, before proceeding on the queenside. }
13... g5
{ It's enticing to let the pawns advance, after White did the same on the queenside. But often similar things are not equivalent. Abandoning the square e4 and the light squares is a positional sin in this structure. }
14. exf5 Bxf5 { 14...Nxf5  15.Nde4  Nd4  16.Bd3+- } 15. a6
{ Further weakening Black's position on the light squares and securing the square b5 for the knight. }
15... b6 16. Nf1
{ That's another key move. The knight will be very strongly placed on g3. As you will notice, my analysis will go on for quite a while. One reason is the obligation to prove my winning claim, the other reason is that I really enjoyed myself, as I found the ensuing structure quite intriguing. If your approach is very pragmatic, you might want to stop here and move on to the next sub-line. }
16... Bh7 17. Ra2
{ Prophylaxis, after  17.Ng3  Ng6  18.Bd3  Black can become active with  e4  on the following move, due to the exposed rook on  a1  . }
17... Nf5 18. Ng3 Qd7
{ 18...Nd4  19.Bd3  Exchanging Black's good bishop, leaving him with his bad one.  19...Qd7  20.Bxh7+  Kxh7  21.Be3  Kg8  22.Qd3  Obviously, this is a tasty diagonal for the queen.  22...Rae8  23.Qg6  White is winning, as Black cannot even exchange the queen with good conscience.  23...Qf7?!  24.Qxf7  Kxf7  25.Rd1  Kg6  26.Bxd4  exd4  27.Nb5+-  . }
19. Nxf5 Bxf5 20. Nb5
{ This knight is nothing but a plague for the black player. } 20... Bg6 21. Be3
Kh8 { Waiting is all Black can do. } 22. Bd3
{ Now, each of the following choices has its specific downside. } 22... Be8
{ Avoiding the exchange of the important light-squared bishop, but leaving the diagonal b1-h7 to White. Alternative options are  22...e4  23.Bb1+-  and @@StartFEN@@r4r1k/p1pq2b1/Pp1p1nbp/1N1Pp1p1/1PP5/3BB3/R4PPP/3QR1K1 b - - 5 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Bxd3  23.Qxd3  Kg8  24.Rc1+-  .   The weak queenside pawns together with Black's bad bishop decide the outcome. White's prime idea is c4-c5, but he is not forced to rush in. He might also consider placing his queen on g6 or opening the kingside with h4. }
23. Nc3
{ The knight would soon be under attack by the bishop. Hence, it moves to a square, from where it can reach both e4 and b5, as well as enable the advance c4-c5 by supporting the d-pawn. }
23... Nh5 24. c5 Nf4 25. Be4
{ Also the bishop makes a 'bella figura' on this square. } 25... Qf7 26. c6
{ This is a remarkable way of dealing with the position. Instead of trying to play against the weak d-pawn or to penetrate on the 7th rank, White closes the queenside, the wing where he is supposed to win the game. As a matter of fact, White indeed is winning the game on the queenside, but indirectly.  With his last move, the knight is allowed to return to b5, where it will exert decisive influence, by binding the rook to the defense of the a-pawn and the queen to the defense of the c-pawn. When the position will finally open up on the kingside, the rook cannot participate and the queen's participation is severely restricted @@StartBracket@@the exchange of queen's wont be possible, for instance@@EndBracket@@. That's an enormous energy drain! }
