[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... f5 11. a4
{ Quickly expanding the space advantage on the queenside is the core element of White's strategy in the Bayonet Attack. At the same time, the knight is left on f3, in contrast to other lines, where it is moves to e1 or d2, as the option to play Nf3-g5-e6 is very valuable for White. }
11... Nf6
{ That's much better than  11...Nf4?  .  From f6, the knight really contributes to the position by fighting for the key square e4. }
12. a5
{ As Black's last move didn't contain a threat, White simply claims more space. Amongst others, the advance a5-a6 is now to be reckoned with, undermining the square c6 and consequently establishing an outpost for the knight on b5. There is also a prophylactic aspect to a5, as it prevents Black from playing the move himself. Thus, White has secured his control over the key square c5. }
12... c6
{ Instead of relieving or maintaining the tension, Black increases it even further. The idea is to prevent White from playing c4-c5 or, more aggressively, to win the d-pawn, which is already undermined. This all sounds good in theory, but can be considered refuted thanks to a very direct and brutal approach. }
13. dxc6
{ This is more ambitious than the quieter  13.Nd2  , which is good enough for a clear advantage. If your intention is to play this line on a Quickstarter level, I recommend to be modest and play  13.Nd2  . To get a full grasp of  13.dxc6  , you will have to get acquainted with the main section. }
13... Nxc6
{ 13...bxc6  14.c5!  promises White a winning advantage, but there are still some complications ahead. One line would be  14...d5  15.exd5  cxd5  16.Qb3! }
14. Bg5
{ This evaluation is not visible yet for the naked eye. Nevertheless, it already exists as underlying information, waiting to be brought to light by analytical effort. Black suffers from a bad pawn structure and a vulnerable king. In order to score the full point, White has to play in dynamic fashion and mustn't shy away from temporarily sacrificing material. }
14... h6
{ After  14...Be6  15.a6  b6  16.Qa4  Rc8  17.Rad1+-  , the pressure against  d6  is very annoying for Black.   14...Nxb4  is strongly met by  15.c5!  , when one line is  15...dxc5  16.Bc4  Kh8  17.Qxd8  Rxd8  18.Nxe5+-  . }
15. Bxf6 Rxf6
{ After  15...Bxf6  16.a6!  White's supremacy on the light squares and his better structure give him a winning advantage. }
16. b5
{ If you don't like to sacrifice material, you can resort to  16.Qa4  Nd4  17.Rad1  . }
16... Nxa5
{ For his bad position, Black at least has a pawn on his account. Now, the knight is placed on the edge of the board and is also exposed to the rook, temporarily withdrawing energy from Black's queen. The alternative  16...Nd4  17.exf5  Nxf5  18.Bd3+-  gives White a winning advantage without a fight. }
17. Nh4 Kh7 { The pawn needed protection in view of the threat Nd5. } 18. exf5
gxf5 19. g3
{ A good example for information warfare. As the knight has to be protected anyways, once the rook moves from f6, White does it outright. Now Black has to show his hand and White can react accordingly. White's idea is to play against Black's king by attacking the f5-pawn with moves such as Qc2, and Bd3. As the position is already won, I can leave you here with good conscience and refer to the main part for all the details. }
