20. Rc4
{ Yet another position for my 'camouflaged +- collection'. To be honest, I wouldn't have guessed that this one is already won for White before performing the analysis. So, how can this possibly be the case? Let me sum up the ingredients:   1@@EndBracket@@ The black king is lacking good pawn protection.   2@@EndBracket@@ The Bishop on g7 is passive; playing e4 would weaken the e-pawn.   3@@EndBracket@@ The bishop on f5 is susceptible to being expelled by g2-g4.  4@@EndBracket@@ Black's queenside is threatened by an invasion on c7.  5@@EndBracket@@ Black will be forced to concede the square b6 to the bishop, once his a-pawn is under attack by Be3 or even earlier. Obviously, this will facilitate the invasion on c7.  6@@EndBracket@@ Black's queenside pawns can easily become a target for White's bishops, once they are fixed.   7@@EndBracket@@ Let's not forget Black's permanent weakness on d6. }
