Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... f5 11. a4
{ Quickly expanding the space advantage on the queenside is the core element of White's strategy in the Bayonet Attack. At the same time, the knight is left on f3, in contrast to other lines, where it is moves to e1 or d2, as the option to play Nf3-g5-e6 is very valuable for White. }
11... a5 { Black wants to weaken White's control of the square c5. } 12. bxa5
Rxa5 13. Ng5 Nf6 14. exf5 gxf5
{ The alternative  14...Nxf5  is more solid but also easier to play against. After  15.Bd3  ,  White might follow up with Bd2, Ra3, and Nb5, preparing activities such as a4-a5 and Ne6. In this structure after the text move play generally becomes rather dynamic, as White will jump with his knight to e6 in most cases. }
15. Nb5
{ Exerting pressure against the c-pawn is a good prelude for the Ne6 idea, as it indirectly protects the ensuing passed pawn on e6 from being attacked by the queen. }
15... h6
{ Black forces a change of the structure, in order to reduce White's options and to clarify the situation for himself. After  15...Ra8  , anticipating  Bd2  , White would continue with  16.Ra3  , intending to move it all the way to h3.   After  15...Ne8  , White can already sacrifice a pawn with  16.c5!  dxc5  17.Ra3  Nd6  18.Ne6  , when his active piece play gives him a clear advantage. }
16. Ne6 Bxe6 17. dxe6
{ That's a good example for a binary situation, as the pawn is either weak or strong. In the context of this repertoire @@StartBracket@@opposed to less convincing lines with this structure, e.g. after 9.Nd2@@EndBracket@@, it will be strong every single time, though. }
17... Qc8
{ The queen is targeting our pawn, but giving up the c-pawn is not really an option, as Black's structure would fall apart. }
18. Ra3
{ This position is all about piece play and it's the white pieces, which have a lot of space. The rook wants to shift to the kingside. }
18... Ne4
{ Black looks for ways and means to destroy the intruder. Another way of doing that would be  18...Ne8  , liberating the queen from the defense of the c-pawn. White, however, can simply continue with  19.Bh5!  Qxe6?  20.Bxe8  Rxe8  21.Nxc7+-  . }
19. Be3 { Preventing  19...Nc5  . } 19... Rf6
{ 19...Ng5  20.Bxg5  hxg5  21.Qd2+-  , with a double attack. } 20. Bf3
{ We now see a relatively forcing sequence. } 20... Rxe6 21. Bxe4 fxe4 22. Qg4
Ra8 23. Na7 { 23.Nxc7  Rg6  is only clearly better for White. } 23... h5
{ 23...Qd7  24.Bxh6+- } 24. Qh3 Qd7 25. Nb5 Rd8 26. Qxh5 Rg6 27. Nc3 Qf5 28.
Qxf5 Nxf5 29. Nxe4
{ After a long journey, the knight is finally netting a healthy extra pawn. } *

