Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... f5 11. a4
{ Quickly expanding the space advantage on the queenside is the core element of White's strategy in the Bayonet Attack. At the same time, the knight is left on f3, in contrast to other lines, where it is moves to e1 or d2, as the option to play Nf3-g5-e6 is very valuable for White. }
11... a5 { Black wants to weaken White's control of the square c5. } 12. bxa5
Rxa5 13. Ng5 Nf4 14. Bf1
{ This position resembles the one after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.b4  Nh5  10.Re1  Nf4  11.Bf1  a5  12.bxa5  Rxa5  13.a4  f5  . There, I recommended the strong move  14.Bd2  , which was followed up by  a subsequent a4-a5 with a grip on the queenside. }
14... h6
{ Now, the knight is forced to retreat to a modest location and cannot be installed on e4. }
15. Nf3 g5
{ This advance is double-edged, as it weakens the light squares. Preferable is  15...fxe4  16.Nxe4  b6  17.Ra3  .  White will chase Black's knight away with h3, Nh2 and g3, when ....Nxh3+ / Bxh3 Bxh3 / g4 would lose a piece. The next step would be to push the a-pawn. }
16. Nd2 c5
{ Black managed to stabilize the queenside for the time being, but he is now sitting on two long-term weaknesses. This is more than he can bear, as his kingside is weak, as well. White will win by combining activities on both wings. Black had to seek active piece play, even though, there is no really pleasant line:   A@@EndBracket@@  16...b6  17.Nb3  Ra8  18.g3  Nfg6  19.a5  bxa5  20.Nxa5  Qd7  21.c5  .   B@@EndBracket@@  16...g4  Black doesn't want to see his knight driven to  g6  and provides it with a potential outpost on h3.  17.Nb5!  As there is no black piece pressure against e4, the knight can be placed on this fine outpost.  17...Ra8  Black had to watch out for c5, followed by Nc4 or Nb3.  18.Ba3  b6  19.Bb4  Kh8  20.a5  White pursues his standard queenside play. }
17. Nb5 Ra6 18. g3
{ It's logical to drive Black's knight to the joyless square g6 as soon as possible, exploiting the move ...g5. }
18... Nfg6 19. exf5 Nxf5 20. Qh5
{ Obviously, this option is another consequence of Black's ambitious pawn advance on move 15. }
20... Nge7 21. Ne4
{ White combines the pressure against the d-pawn with his control of the light squares. Black's queen cannot easily oppose the white queen, as it is occupied with guarding the points d6 and c7. The knight on b5 is really doing a formidable job. White's long-term plan is to improve his pieces and then pry open the kingside with h2-h4. }
21... Bd7 22. Bd2 Be8 23. Qg4 Bg6
{ Black is unable to get rid of the queen, as  23...Bd7  is answered by  24.Bh3!+-  ,  threatening Nbd6. }
24. a5
{ Dismissing the rook from its service and preparing Rab1. White is winning, because Black has three weaknesses: the b-pawn, the d-pawn, and the kingside structure, which can be broken by h2-h4 in a suitable moment. Look for more details in the main section. }
