1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... f5 11. a4
{ Quickly expanding the space advantage on the queenside is the core element of White's strategy in the Bayonet Attack. At the same time, the knight is left on f3, in contrast to other lines, where it is moves to e1 or d2, as the option to play Nf3-g5-e6 is very valuable for White. }
11... Nf4
{ Let's start with the positive aspect. We are dealing here with an improved version of the line @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.b4  Nh5  10.Re1  Nf4  11.Bf1  f5  .  As the bishop is still on e2, White cannot answer with  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1n1bp/3p2p1/3Ppp2/PPP1Pn2/2N2N2/4BPPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bxf4  exf4  13.e5  . However, this doesn't wipe away the  fact, that the knight is misplaced on f4, as shown by the following analysis. }
12. Bf1 fxe4
{ Aspiring active play on the f-file is what gives this line its independent meaning, but it turns out to be a flawed concept.   After  12...a5  13.bxa5  Rxa5  14.Bd2!  , we see a transposition to the 10...Nf4 move order. }
13. Nxe4 Bg4
{ If Black could move another time, he would play ...Nh3+ with equality. } 14.
Ra3
{ Now, that the soft spot is protected, Black is deprived of any real activity. Soon, both pseudo-active minor pieces will be expelled, after which Black has to worry about a white knight landing on e6. Preventing this with ...h6 will further weaken Black's kingside, which is already pretty drafty, as it is now. White will pursue his general plan of creating a weakness on d6 by pushing the c-pawn, possibly followed by an invasion down the c-file. }
14... a5
{ This weakens White's control over c5, but won't be able to prevent the advance c4-c5 in the long run. Let's have a look at the alternatives:   A@@EndBracket@@  14...Qd7?  15.h3  Bf5  That's not a good place, as the connection between rook and knight is interrupted.  16.Neg5  Rae8  17.Bxf4  exf4  18.Nd4  One of White's knights will enjoy their outpost on e6.   B@@EndBracket@@  14...Nf5  15.g3!  Nh3+  16.Bxh3  Bxh3  17.Nfg5  . }
15. bxa5 Rxa5 16. h3 Bf5
{ This is the most active move, but it comes with drawbacks. The best continuation is actually  16...Bc8  , but at the same time this would be a confession that something went wrong. Play may continue  17.Bd2  Ra8  18.c5  dxc5  19.Bc4  Nfxd5  20.Nxc5  , when White's position is won in the long run.   After  16...Bd7  White can push his c-pawn by means of small tactics:  17.c5!  dxc5?  18.Bd2  Ra8  19.Nxc5  b6  20.Nxd7  Qxd7  21.Bb4+-  and the e-pawn will fall. }
17. Bd2 Ra8 18. a5
{ Pinning down the b-pawn. If Black doesn't react, White's following moves could be Bxf4 and Neg5. }
18... h6
{ After  18...b6  19.Bxf4  exf4  20.a6  White's passed pawn is very annoying. }
19. Nh4 { Exploiting the newly created weakness. } 19... Bc8 20. g3 g5
{ After  20...Nxh3+  21.Bxh3  Bxh3  22.g4  g5  23.Nxh3  gxh4  24.g5+-  White has a winning attack and   20...Nh5  runs into  21.Nxg6+-  . }
21. gxf4 gxh4 22. fxe5 dxe5 23. Bb4
{ White has the more active pieces plus a de facto extra pawn. } *

