{ Black wants to stop the advance c4-c5 once and for all. } 14. Ra3 Ra6
{ The rook is keeping an eye on d-pawn and on the weak b6-square. } 15. Nb5 h6
{ The position is very difficult for Black, as there is not really anything to do. The majority of players opted for the faulty g5-plan, which I made the mainline for that reason. Let's think about the alternatives. Playing ...f5 outright doesn't work:   15...f5?  16.Bxf4  exf4  17.e5+-  .  Black could retreat with the knight to h5 and play ...f5 afterwards, but this also fails:   15...Nh5  16.Bd2  f5?  17.exf5  Bxf5   17...gxf5?  18.Nxe5  18.Ng5  followed by Ne6.   I came to the following conclusion. Black's best bet is, as a matter of fact, to return all the way home with the knight and play ...Nf4-h5-f6-e8 and afterwards bide his time. There is absolutely nothing active he can do. But even if he follows this recommendation, his position is most likely lost, as I try to prove in the line @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.b4  Nh5  10.Re1  a5  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.a4  c5  . }
16. Bd2 g5
{ Better is  16...Nh5  17.a5  , but now  17...f5?  fails due to  18.exf5  Bxf5  19.Nh4  . On  19...Bc8  there follows the tactical blow  20.Nxg6  . }
17. h4 g4
{ 17...f6  18.hxg5  fxg5   18...hxg5  19.g3  19.g3  Nfg6   19...Nh3+  20.Bxh3  Bxh3  21.Nxg5!  hxg5  22.g4  20.Nh2+-  Black is defeated on both wings and would probably resign within the next 20 moves. }
18. Nh2 Qd7
{ After  18...h5  19.g3  Nfg6  20.f3  Black will lose a pawn.   Not much better is  18...f5  19.h5  Nxh5  20.exf5  Nxf5  21.Nxg4+-  , when Black's kingside cannot be defended in the long run. }
19. g3 Nh5
{ Black plays conservatively and tries to establish a fortress. No improvement is  19...Nh3+  20.Bxh3  gxh3  21.Qh5  . }
20. Bd3
{ In the first step, White frustrates Black's only active plan, namely ...f7-f5. }
20... Nf6 21. Bc2 Kh8 22. Nf1 h5 23. Ne3 Bh6 24. Qe2
{ After the minor pieces have been improved, the idle king's rook is brought into position. }
24... Qd8 25. Rb1 Kh7 26. Nc3 { The start of a key maneuver. } 26... Ne8 27.
Ncd1 Ng8 28. a5 Ng7 29. Rab3 f6 30. Rb6 Ra8
{ After  30...Rxb6  31.Rxb6+-  , it's not so easy to stop the knight from reaching  a7  , followed by the exchange of the important light-squared bishop. }
31. Nb2 Ra7 32. Na4 Rf7 33. R6b3 Kh8 34. Nb6
{ After capturing the bishop, White is prepared to open the position on the kingside with f2-f3. }
