1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... Nf4
{ Consistent play, but bad. On f4 the knight is more liability than asset. }
11. Bf1 a5
{ Weakening White's control over c5 is clearly Black's best approach in this position. However, it would be wiser to apply this method already on move 9 or 10. }
12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. a4 c5
{ Black wants to stop the advance c4-c5 once and for all. } 14. Ra3 h6
{ Similar to the line 13…h6, Black wants to fortify the knight on f4 with g5, in order to prepare ...f7-f5. }
15. Nb5 g5
{ As we will see, this idea turns out to be flawed on different levels.  15...Ra6  16.Bd2!  leads to the main line. }
16. g3 Nfg6
{ 16...Nh3?  17.Bxh3  Bxh3  18.Bxg5!  Bg4   18...hxg5  19.Nxg5+-  with the double threat of Nxh3 and Qh5.  19.Bxe7  Qxe7  20.h3!  Returning the pawn for a crushing positional advantage.  20...Bxh3  21.Nh4  Rfa8  22.Nf5  Bxf5  23.exf5 }
17. Nd2
{ Black is already lost, as he handed over the light squares by playing g5. If he now stays put, White will occupy the light squares by Be2-g4 and Nf1-e3. When this is done, the position is ripe for the pawn break h2-h4. }
17... f5
{ Black doesn't want to go under without a fight. However, donating the square e4 to White's knight can hardly be advisable. }
18. exf5 Nxf5
{ 18...Bxf5  19.Ne4  Nc8  20.Qh5  Nge7  21.Bh3!  Removing the guardian of the light squares.  21...Qd7  22.Bxf5  Nxf5  23.h4! }
19. Ne4 Ra6 20. Qh5 Nge7 21. h4
{ All you have to do is learn the standard patterns. } 21... gxh4 22. g4 Nd4
23. Bxh6 Nf3+ 24. Rxf3 Rxf3 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. g5
{ With the double threat of Qxf3 and Qh6+. } *

