1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... Nf4
{ Consistent play, but bad. On f4 the knight is more liability than asset. }
11. Bf1 a5
{ Weakening White's control over c5 is clearly Black's best approach in this position. However, it would be wiser to apply this method already on move 9 or 10. }
12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. a4 f5 14. Bd2
{ The idea to breakthrough in the center by  14.Bxf4  exf4  15.e5  doesn't work this time, due to  15...dxe5  16.Nxe5  Qd6  17.Qe2  Nc6!=  .  In many openings, d2 is a poor place for the queen's bishop. Here, however, things are different. The bishop radiates in two directions, overprotects the knight, and will support the a-pawn. Furthermore, it doesn't obstruct the queen's rook, which will soon appear on the third rank. }
14... fxe4
{ Taking on e4 looks feeble, but if Black doesn't, there are other kinds of problems. }
15. Nxe4 Ra8 16. a5
{ Pinning down the b-pawn means turning it into a weakness and at the same time securing the control over the key square c5. }
16... Bg4 17. Ra3
{ With the rook on the third rank, the potentially soft spot f3 is well-protected. Don't fall for  17.h3??  Nxh3  . }
17... h6 { 17...b6  18.a6 } 18. h3 Bc8
{ The Bishop has to return to it's original square as the b-pawn needs it's protection. }
19. Nh2 { We are witnessing a standard motif for getting rid of the intruder. }
19... Kh7 20. g3
{ The ambitious black knight is being confronted with reality. } 20... Nh5
{ 20...Nxh3??  21.Bxh3  Bxh3  22.g4 } 21. Ng4
{ The maneuver Nf3-h2-g4 is worth remembering, as the knight now occupies an influential position. }
21... Nf5
{ 21...Nf6  Generally, it's a good idea to recycle the stranded knight. Here, however it allows a powerful motif  22.Ngxf6  Bxf6  23.g4!  Black's minor pieces are dominated. }
22. Bg2 Ra6 23. Qb1 Rf7
{ 23...b6  Black exchanges a weakness, but allows his position to be penetrated.  24.Qa2  Nd4  25.axb6  Rxb6  26.Ra7 }
24. c5
{ This break was to come sooner or later. Now, the c-file gets opened and the Black d-pawn is turned into a weakness. }
24... b6 25. cxb6 cxb6 26. Rc1 Bb7
{ 26...bxa5?  allows the direct invasion through  27.Qb8  . } 27. Rb3
{ That's a strong exchange sacrifice. } 27... Nd4 28. Rb2 Ne2+ 29. Kh2 Nxc1 30.
Qxc1
{ The threat is to take on h6 and then further on g7, in order to penetrate on h6 with the queen. }
30... Rc7 31. Qb1 Bc8
{ 31...Bxd5  is tactically refuted:  32.axb6  Rb7  33.Qd3  . } 32. Rxb6 Rxb6
33. Qxb6 Rd7 34. Qb4
{ The combination of Black's passive pieces, his weak d-pawn, unsafe king and, most importantly, White's passed a-pawn, makes this position an easy win for White. }
