11. Bf1 a5
{ Weakening White's control over c5 is clearly Black's best approach in this position. However, it would be wiser to apply this method already on move 9 or 10. }
12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. a4 b6
{ Obviously, Black wants to strengthen his control over the key square c5. White's answer is straight-forward. He will eliminate the b-pawn by pushing his own pawn to a5. That way, the weakness on c7 will become accessible. }
14. Bd2 f5
{ Black creates tension, in order to prevent Nb5. This, however, gives White the opportunity to strike on the kingside.   After  14...Bd7  15.Nb5  Ra8  16.a5  White's position is already positionally won. }
