1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Black prepares both, ...f7-f5 and ...Nf4.   I made this the main line of the Quickstarter, simply because it is the most common move with 9793 games. The second most frequent move  9...a5  only carries 3972 games. }
10. Re1
{ White anticipates ...Nf4 by creating an escape square for the bishop on f1. }
10... Nf4
{ Consistent play, but bad. On f4 the knight is more liability than asset. }
11. Bf1 h6
{ Some players used this move as preparation for 12...f5 by preventing the Ng5-e6-maneuver. But they underestimated the Bxf4 idea, which we have seen in the line 11...f5?. The majority intended 12...g5, with the idea to support the knight on f4 before playing ...f5, thus ruling out Bxf4. }
12. c5 g5
{ Black is now prepared to play ...f5, as Bxf4 no longer has to be feared. Additionally, the square g6 is cleared for the knights and the advance ...g5-g4 is an option. In spite of all the goodies, the position is positionally lost, due to White's automatic attack on the queenside and the weakness of the light-squared color complex in Black's camp after ...f7-f5. }
13. Nd2 f5
{ Black's position looks reasonably active, but there is not much potential for improvement, as the pawn storm ...f5-f4, followed by ...g5-g4-g3 is not possible with the knight on f4. The downside of Black's setup will soon become visible. Four of White's pieces are very happy right now. The knights just received a fantastic outpost on e4 and the queen and bishop will find a good occupation on the light squares. }
14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Nc4
{ Now Black has to deal with two monsters: the one that might appear on e4 and the one that has already arrived on its ideal square c4. }
15... g4
{ This is the most frequent move. Black deals with the imminent threat of g3, after which his super-ambitious knight would be otherwise condemned to accept a cheerless existence on g6. The downside of this idea, however, is the exposure of the g-pawn and the re-emerging menace of White playing Bxf4, followed by e5. }
16. b5
{ As Black is still far away from establishing threats on the kingside, White proceeds with his agenda. Obviously, the queen's bishop would now have clear sight on the target from a3. }
16... h5
{ Stabilizing the g-pawn and introducing the option to attack with ...h5-h4. }
17. b6 a6
{ Trying to keep the position closed. After  17...axb6  18.a4  ,  the pawns on b6 and d6 can be attacked in numerous ways, e.g.  18...fxe4  19.Nxe4  Nf5  20.Ba3  . }
18. g3 Nfg6 { 18...Nh3+  would lose a pawn after  19.Bxh3  gxh3  20.Qxh5  . }
19. Ba3 Rf6 20. exf5 Bxf5 21. Nd2
{ Not only establishing a knight on e4, but also clearing the c-file for the rook. }
21... Nh8 22. Nce4 Rg6 23. Rc1 Rc8
{ After  23...Qxb6  24.Nc4  Black would lose his d-pawn, which is, more often than not, equivalent with the collapse of his entire position. }
24. Rxc8 Nxc8 25. Bxa6 Qxb6 { 25...bxa6  26.b7 } 26. Bd3 Nf7 27. Nc4 Qa7 28.
Qc2
{ Black won't be able to withstand for very much longer with his pieces placed so passively. }
*

