{ The rook is in a position, now, to enter the battle once Black opens the game with ...f7-f5. }
13... Nf6
{ The knight was exposed on  h5  and returns to safety. Another plan is  13...Kh8  14.Nb5  Ng8  , preparing ...Bh6. White's best reaction is  15.Bd2!  Ra6  16.Qc1!  , thwarting Black's intentions.  As mentioned many times in the main section, moving the knight to f4 is generally a flawed concept.   One typical line could be:  13...Nf4?  14.Bf1  f5?  15.Bxf4  fxe4  16.Nxe4!  exf4  17.Neg5  , when White's knight is ready for the jump. }
14. Bd2 { That's the best place for the bishop in so many lines. } 14... Ra6
15. Qc2 Ne8 16. Nb5
{ We now have to distinguish between two general plans: Black plays ...f5 at some stage, or stays completely passive. }
16... Kh8
{ This line is more important than the lines with ...f5, as it became clear that White's pieces could profit more from the open kingside than Black's. The really interesting question is: What does White do, if Black is simply biding his time? Advancing pawns on the kingside is possible, but not trivial. A move like f2-f4 needs good preparation, as it would activate the King's Indian bishop. Luckily, there is a more elegant plan. White is able to systematically make progress on the queenside. }
17. a5 Kg8 18. Rb1 Kh8 19. h3
{ As the plan is to transfer the light-squared bishop, we don't want to be molested by a possible ...Bg4, later on. }
19... Kg8 20. Qc1 Kh8 21. Bd1 Kg8 22. Bc2
{ That's the perfect interim setup. The king's rook performed a 'castling' with the queen and can now rule the b-file. The light-squared bishop radiates in two directions and leaves the queen's rook free sight on the 3rd rank. The queen and the dark-squared bishop control an interesting diagonal. Once more, we have maximized harmony. }
22... Kh8 23. Nc3 { Now the second part of the plan begins: penetration. }
23... Nf6
{ The knight hurries to neutralize his white counterpart. After  23...Rxa5  24.Rxa5  Qxa5  25.Na4  Qc7  26.Nb6  Black cannot save his b-pawn, as its defender is about to be exchanged.  26...Nf6  27.Qb2  Kg8  28.Nxc8  Rxc8  29.Qxb7  White enjoys more space, the two bishops, play against the weak d-pawn and has penetrated Black's territory. }
24. Na4 Nd7 25. Rab3 Kg8 26. Nb6
{ The square b6 has to be cleared for the rook. } 26... Nxb6 27. Rxb6 Rxb6
{ After  27...Ra7  28.Qb2  h6  29.a6!  An important motif!  29...bxa6  30.Ba5!  Bd7  31.Qa3  Black cannot hold on to his d-pawn. }
28. Rxb6 Kh8 29. Bg5 Qc7 30. Qb1 h6 31. Bd2 Kg8
{ Did you spot the ideal square for White's knight? } 32. Ne1
{ It might be a7, after all. That's why exchanging Black's rook was that strong. Now, Black cannot sit tight anymore. }
32... f5 33. Bd3 fxe4 34. Bxe4 Nf5 35. Nc2 Qd8 36. Na3 Rf7 37. Nb5 Bf8 38. Na7
{ There it is! } 38... h5 39. Bc3 Kh7 40. Qd3
{ Black suffers from 3 weaknesses and has to reckon with g2-g4. } *

