Qe7 19. Bd3 Bh6
{ A@@EndBracket@@ After  19...h6  20.Ne4   20.Ne6  Bxe6  21.dxe6  Qxe6  22.Be4  is also interesting.  20...b6  21.Qb1  Ra8  22.Bc2  White's position has reached maximum harmony and can be considered won due to the weaknesses on b7, d6 and g6.   B@@EndBracket@@ The change of structure after  19...Nd4  20.Nxd4  cxd4  is very favorable for White. He will activate his rook by playing a5, followed by Rb3. After Black withdrew his rook from a6, due to the threat of c4-c5, White will place his rook on b6 and play c4-c5 nevertheless. }
20. Qc1 b6 21. h3 { 21.Bc2  Nd4  22.Nxd4  cxd4  23.Rg3  is also good. } 21...
Neg7 22. Bxf5 Nxf5
{ After  22...gxf5  23.h4  , Black's vulnerable king makes his position indefensible. One line would be  23...Bd7  24.Ne6!  Bxd2  25.Qxd2  Nxe6  26.dxe6  Bxe6  27.Nxd6  Qf6  28.Qb2  e4  29.Qb5  White is winning, as Black's kingside stands wide open. }
23. Ne4 Bxd2 24. Qxd2 Bd7
{ Black managed to exchange two pairs of minor pieces, but to what avail? The weak d6-pawn will be enough for him to lose the game. }
25. Rea1 Ra5 { Blocking the a-pawn and preparing ...Rfa8. } 26. Qb2 Bxb5
{ The threat was g4, with an attack on the d6-pawn. } 27. axb5 Rxa3 28. Rxa3
{ Black is unable to take care of that many weaknesses. He has two weak pawns and an insecure king. }
