{ Obviously, Black wants to play ...f5 without being molested by Ng5. Apart from this, the move has waiting move qualities, as Black can adapt his play according to White's chosen setup. }
11. Nd2
{ If White plays the c4-c5 advance too early, Black will get a playable position by applying pressure on White's center pawns:  11.c5?  f5  12.Nd2  Nf6  13.a4  Kh7  14.Bc4  .  The d5-pawn needed protection. Now, Black switches to his standard attacking plan with  14...f4  ,  as White's knight cannot directly access the square c4. I don't say that this position is fantastic for Black, but at least he has something to play for. }
11... Nf4
{ As the knight on d2 blocks the bishop, this plunge is less risky, now. No Bxf4 to be feared. }
12. Bf1 f5
{ 12...a5  13.bxa5  Rxa5  14.a4!   That's better than  14.Nb3  , which has been played far more often.  14...Ra8  15.a5  b6  16.Nb3  bxa5  17.Rxa5  Rxa5  18.Nxa5  White enjoys the usual queenside initiative and will target Black's pawn structure. }
13. c5 fxe4
{ This provides White's knight with a splendid outpost, but Black's pieces were in dire need of space. After  13...dxc5  White has the intermediate move  14.Bc4  available. }
14. Ndxe4 Nf5
{ If Black recaptures with his bishop, he will get problems with the d6-pawn:  14...Bf5  15.b5  Kh8  16.cxd6  cxd6  17.a4  ,  followed by Ba3. }
15. g3 Nh5 16. Bg2
{ By covering the square f3, forking the knights with g4 is now a threat.   16.g4?  would have been very bad because of  16...Nd4  17.gxh5  Nf3+  18.Kh1  Qh4  , winning. }
16... Nd4
{ This is what Black gets from this position, but not more. White can tolerate this knight, as it cannot cause too much damage all by itself. After  16...Nf6  17.Nxf6  Qxf6  18.Ne4  White's position is close to winning. }
17. Be3 { It's good to know that the knight can be removed, if necessary. }
17... Nf6 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 19. Ne4 Qd8 20. Rc1 Nf5
{ 20...Bf5  looks more natural, but White has the means to make progress.  21.h3  a6  22.a4  Rf7  23.Nd2!  Kh7  24.Nb3  Exchanging Black's only active piece.  24...Qf8  25.Rc4!  Nxb3  26.Qxb3  White's space advantage on the queenside is already decisive. }
21. h3
{ There is no need to remove the bishop. On the contrary, we wouldn't mind forcing this exchange, as the knight is Black's most active piece and also protects the d-pawn. }
21... Bd7 22. g4 Nxe3 23. Rxe3
{ Black owns the square f4, but he has no use for it. } 23... Be8 24. cxd6 cxd6
25. Rec3 { The invasion cannot be prevented anymore. } *

