[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ By challenging White's b-pawn, Black diminishes White's control of the key c5-square. We can also see this motif in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played more than twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8  . In our variations,  the knight will appear on d7, which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the c5-square. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one.   However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming in the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as  11...Ne8  would do. }
12. Ba3 Ra8 13. Bb4 { White prepares to gain more space by playing a4-a5. }
13... Bh6
{ By covering the g5-square, Black wants to avoid the problems he faces after  13...f5  14.Ng5  .  The bishop appears to be more active on the h6-square, but in reality, it doesn't manage to influence White's further development much. Its absence from g7 will reduce Black's dynamic options in the center, once tension is established there. }
14. a5
{ We have seen this move many times before. By suppressing Black's b-pawn, White not only fixes it as a weakness, he also improves his chances in the fight for the key square c5. }
14... f5 15. Bd3
{ The bishop fortifies the point e4 and at the same time exerts pressure on Black's f-pawn. }
15... Nf6
{ This allows White to follow his queenside agenda without delay. Black has a dilemma. If he is sitting tight, White will slowly improve his position and can systematically prepare the c4-c5 pawn break. On  15...Kh8  , the best way for White to proceed would be  16.Re1  , when Black has the problem to find a constructive move. }
16. c5 fxe4 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 { 17...Nf5  18.Re1 } 18. Bxe4 Bf5
{ Other attempts are inferior:   A@@EndBracket@@  18...Kh8?!  19.Re1  Ng8  20.cxd6  cxd6  21.Nd2  Nf6  22.Nc4  .  Thanks to the overprotection of the bishop on move 19, White is now able to force Black's knight to e8.   B@@EndBracket@@  18...Nf5  19.Re1  Qf6  20.Qc2  Bg7  21.Ra3  Rf7  22.c6  White applies a standard motif to create a very effective passed pawn. }
19. Re1 Bxe4
{ After  19...Qd7  White plays  20.Qb3  , when  20...Bxe4  would transpose to the main line. }
20. Rxe4 Qd7
{ In some games  20...Rf4?  happened, but exchanging an important defender is not a good idea.  21.Rxf4  Bxf4  22.Qb3  . }
21. Qb3 Bg7
{ After  21...Nf5?  White clears the b-file  and the square b4 for the rook with  22.Bc3  and @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1ppqn2p/3p2pb/P1PPp3/1B2R3/1Q3N2/5PPP/R5K1 b - - 2 21@@EndFEN@@  21...Kh8  is also answered by  22.Bc3  with the intention to finish the game in style, for instance,  22...Ra7  is met with  23.Rxe5!  dxe5  24.Nxe5  Qxd5  25.Nf7+  Kg8  26.Nxh6  . }
22. Rb1 Nf5 23. h3 dxc5 24. Bxc5 Nd6 25. Ra4 Qf5 26. Rf1
{ By overprotecting f2, White would be ready to install a monster e4-knight. A decent alternative is  26.Be3  with the threat of Ng5.  Black has to react with  26...Bf6  and after  27.Re1  Qd7  28.Bc5  White is clearly better. }
