Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ By challenging White's b-pawn, Black diminishes White's control of the key c5-square. We can also see this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played more than double as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8  .  In our variations, the knight will appear on d7, which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the c5-square. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one.   However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as  11...Ne8  would do. }
12. Ba3 Ra8 13. Bb4 { White prepares to gain more space by playing a4-a5. }
13... f5 14. Ng5
{ That's one of the reasons why we like to leave the knight on f3. Black's weak spot e6 is easily accessible. }
14... Nc5
{ This will lead to a disrupted structure, but it is still better than allowing White to open the position as after  14...Nf6  15.c5  . Play may continue  15...fxe4   15...Nxe4  16.Ncxe4  fxe4  17.cxd6  cxd6  18.Ne6  16.cxd6  cxd6  17.Ncxe4  Nxe4  18.Nxe4  Nf5  19.Rb1  Rf7  20.h3  Bf8  21.Bc3  Black has too many weaknesses.  He has to worry about Ng5-e6 and the siege of his d-pawn. White might place the pawn on a5, the rook on b6, and the bishop on b4. Finally, Black's knight could be questioned by g2-g4 or Bg4. }
15. Bxc5 dxc5
{ White gave up his bishop pair, but received many assets in return:   a@@EndBracket@@ Black's structure lost its flexibility.   b@@EndBracket@@ We see an isolated e-pawn and a slightly exposed pawn on c5.   c@@EndBracket@@ From a more dynamic perspective we observe the potential of the newly liberated d-pawn, which can either advance or turn into a passed pawn after the sequence Ne6 Bxe6 / dxe6. The opening of the d-file gives this option additional punch. }
16. a5
{ The rationale behind this move is to prevent a fortification of Black's structure by ...b6, giving support to the somewhat fragile pawn on c5 and also placing the b-pawn on a protected square. As the c5-pawn is now isolated from the b-pawn, it can be attacked by Na4 or the queen from various squares.  If Black defends the pawn with ...b6, we would see a further change of structure after axb6 cxb6. Now, White would attack the weak pawn on b6 or use the square b5 for his knight. Moreover, the d5-pawn would turn into a passed pawn. }
16... Bh6
{ 16...h6?  would be pushing the knight to where it wants to go anyways:  17.Ne6  Bxe6  18.dxe6  Qc8  19.Bf3  Bf6  20.Nd5  . After  20...Ra6  White would play  21.Qb3  , clearing the square  d1  for the rooks and exerting pressure on  b7  as a preparation for  Ne6  . }
17. Ne6 Bxe6 18. dxe6
{ The vanguard pawn opens the possibility for White to use the square d7 for the invasion. }
18... Bd2
{ Black exploits his superiority on the dark squares to win a pawn by a nice geometrical maneuver. But will he be happy with it? The alternatives are not better, anyways:  18...c6?!  19.Qb3  Qc7  20.Rad1  Rad8  21.Na4  and   18...Qc8?  19.Nd5  Bg5  20.Bf3  f4  21.Bg4  . }
19. Nd5 { 19.Qc2  Bxc3  20.Qxc3  Qd6  would allow Black to equalize. } 19...
Bxa5 { This bishop is offside now and will be missing on the kingside. } 20.
Ra3 c6
{ A beautiful line, where White exploits Black's exposed king is  20...Qd6?  21.Nxe7  Qxe7  22.exf5  gxf5  23.Qa1  b6  24.Bf3!  e4  25.Bh5  (Threatening Rg3+.)  25...Qf6  26.e7  . }
21. Nxe7+ Qxe7 22. Qa1 b6 23. exf5 Rxf5 24. Rd1 e4 25. Re3 Rff8
{ 25...Qxe6  26.Bg4  Qxc4  27.Bxf5  gxf5  28.Rg3 } 26. Qe5 Qf6
{ By exchanging queens Black solves the problem of his bad king safety, but the presence of White's e-pawn still causes him a headache. }
27. Qxf6 Rxf6 28. Rxe4 *

