Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ By challenging White's b-pawn, Black diminishes White's control of the key c5-square. We can also see this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played more than double as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8  .  In our variations, the knight will appear on d7, which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the c5-square. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one.   However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as  11...Ne8  would do. }
12. Ba3 Ra8 13. Bb4 { White prepares to gain more space by playing a4-a5. }
13... h6
{ Black wants to prevent the move Ng5, which would follow after Black played ...f5. }
14. a5 f5 15. Nd2
{ 15.Bd3  is a playable alternative,  but with the g5-square no longer accessible, it makes a lot of sense to direct the knight towards the key squares e4 and c5. }
15... Kh7
{ A typical semi-waiting move. Black wants White to show his hand and accomplishes useful tasks, such as removing the king from the potentially dangerous a2-g8 diagonal @@StartBracket@@in case White plays c4-c5@@EndBracket@@ and overprotecting the kingside pawns.   Premature would be  15...Nf6?  .  Black has to wait with this move until White's knight is committed to the b3-square.  16.c5  fxe4   16...Ne8  17.Nc4  17.cxd6  cxd6  18.Ndxe4  Ne8  19.Bb5  White goes directly after the pawn.  19...Nf5  20.Bxe8  Rxe8  21.Nb5  Bf8  22.Qd3  Kh7  23.Rfc1  Rb8  24.Qa3 }
16. Nb3
{ This move is logical, as White has to prepare c4-c5. However, once this is done, the knight will be misplaced on b3. It belongs to d2, from where it supports the control of the square e4 and can also move to c4. For that reason, Black played ...Kh7 and left the knight on d7 one more move. }
16... Nf6
{ If you compare this position with previous lines, you can consider it a small success for Black, that White has to react passively to this move and cannot just play c5.   After  16...fxe4  17.Nxe4  Nf6  White has to undo his 16th move by playing  18.Nbd2  , but obviously, Black had to pay for this by giving up the central tension. }
17. f3
{ After  17.exf5?  gxf5  18.c5  , there follows the strong reply  18...c6!  . This line works, because Black's king was brought to safety in wise foresight. }
17... fxe4
{ After  17...Nh5  18.c5  Nf4  19.cxd6  cxd6  20.Kh1!  Prophylaxis against trouble on the a7-g1 diagonal or a black queen appearing on the g5-square.  20...Ng8  21.Bc4  Nf6  22.Nd2  Rf7  .  Clearing the f8-square for the bishop.  23.Bb5  White has a winning position. }
18. fxe4 Ne8
{ Exchanging a pair of rooks alleviates the defensive tasks for Black. Apart from that, the knight is heading to the d6-square, which will be vacated soon. }
19. Rxf8 Bxf8 20. Qf1 Bg7 21. c5 dxc5
{ Black needs some space for his pieces.  21...Bd7?  22.Qf2  Ng8  23.Rb1  Ngf6  24.h3  would leave him in a very passive position. }
22. Bxc5 b6
{ Exchanging the second pair of rooks considerably improves Blacks drawing chances. }
23. axb6 Rxa1 24. Qxa1 cxb6 25. Be3 Bd7 26. Nd2
{ This is as good as it gets for Black. The position is objectively drawn, but the two weak pawns will give White good practical chances, nonetheless. }
