1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ By challenging White's b-pawn, Black diminishes White's control of the key c5-square. We can also see this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played more than double as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8  .  In our variations, the knight will appear on d7, which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the c5-square. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one.   However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as  11...Ne8  would do. }
12. Ba3 Ra8 13. Bb4 { White prepares to gain more space by playing a4-a5. }
13... b6
{ Black's intention is to exchange a pawn on the queenside, in order to get rid of one potential weakness. This idea is based on sound logic, but there is also a downside to it. The additional open file will give White more space for his pieces. }
14. a5 bxa5
{ This is the only reasonable move. The alternative  14...Nc5  would allow White to perform a strong liquidation:  15.axb6  Rxa1  16.Qxa1  cxb6  17.Bxc5  bxc5  18.Rb1  .  The weak d6-pawn makes Black's defense a difficult endeavor. }
15. Bxa5
{ I like this move a bit better than  15.Rxa5  , but both options are of approximately the same strength. }
15... Nc5
{ There is no genuine alternative. Let's have a look:   A@@EndBracket@@  15...f5?  16.Nb5  Nb6  17.c5  dxc5  18.d6  .   B@@EndBracket@@  15...Nb6?  16.Bxb6  Rxa1  17.Qxa1  cxb6  18.h3  . A subtle move, in order to prevent Black from facilitating his situation by exchanging his bishop.  18...Bd7  19.Qa7  Nc8  20.Qb7  Black's pieces can hardly move. Transferring the rook to  a8  seems to be a good idea. }
16. Bb4 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 Na6 { Bxc5 was the threat. } 18. Ba3
{ Obviously, Black has a weak pawn on c7. If White manages to enforce c4-c5, the point d6 will be targeted as well. }
18... f5
{ The principled alternative is to block White's c-pawn with  18...c5  .  This, however, would weaken the d6-pawn.  19.Rb1  f5  20.Qb2  Qa5  21.Ra1  Nc7  22.Ra2  Ne8  23.Nd2  Bh6  24.Qc2  Nf6  25.Bc1  Qb6  26.Bd3  White has disentangled his pieces on the queenside and is now ready to start the invasion. }
19. Rd1
{ This is not only a prophylactic move against the ...c7-c5 advance. White also stabilizes the d-pawn in view of a later c4-c5. }
19... Kh8
{ 19...h6  ,  defending against Ng5 comes with the price of weakening the g6-pawn.  20.Qa2  Kh7  21.Bd3  fxe4  22.Bxe4  Nf5  23.Qc2  Bd7  24.Nb5  .  White exerts the usual pressure against Black's weak spots c7, d6 and g6 and will wait for a good opportunity to push his c-pawn. }
20. Ng5 Ng8
{ Apparently, Black had to relieve the tension:  20...fxe4  21.Ngxe4  Nf5  22.Nb5  Qh4  23.Bd3  White can be very satisfied with the location of his knights and is close to winning. }
21. Ne6 Bxe6 22. dxe6
{ Here, the loose knight on a6 prevents Black from simply devouring the passed pawn. }
22... Qc8 23. Nb5 Qxe6
{ Refraining from taking this pawn is no satisfactory solution, either.  23...Re8  , for instance, runs into  24.Bxd6  . }
24. Bxd6 cxd6 25. Qxa6 fxe4 26. Nxd6 e3
{ Without this move, Black would be completely lost. Now, White's king doesn't have his comfortable 3-pawn-protection-shield anymore, which is one of the trademarks of the Bayonet. However, the extra pawn is an asset good enough to win this position. }
27. fxe3 Bh6 28. Qa3 Ne7 29. g4
{ This looks a bit ugly, but White won’t win, if he allows his strong knight to be exchanged. }
29... Ng8 30. Ne4 { Prophylaxis. } 30... Nf6 31. Nf2
{ Securing the king, conserving winning potential  @@StartBracket@@with an extra pawn we don't want to have reduced material with opposite colored bishops@@EndBracket@@ and leaving Black's knight without real function. }
31... Re8 32. h4 g5 33. h5
{ White commands a dangerous passed pawn and might manage to transfer his knight to f5. }
*

