1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ By challenging White's b-pawn, Black diminishes White's control of the key c5-square. We can also see this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played more than double as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8  .  In our variations, the knight will appear on d7, which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 c5
{ This structure has already been covered twice in the line 9.b4 Nh5, once with Black playing the knight to f4 and the other with the knight staying on h5. The present version can be considered slightly better for Black in comparison, as the knight tends to be misplaced on the axis h5-f4. My recommendation in those other chapters was to retreat with the knight to e8, all the way from f4, if necessary.  Now, the question is, whether the extra tempi Black enjoys in this very situation are of great value for him. Let me give the answer right at the beginning. I don't see many benefits for Black as the only active idea is to play ...f7-f5. This idea, however, is flawed as it opens up the position in a sector, where the white player has considerably more firepower. }
12. Ra3 Ra6 13. Bd2 { That's the best square for the bishop. } 13... Ne8 14.
Nb5 h6
{ Black wants to play ...f7-f5 without allowing Nf3-g5.   After  14...f5  15.Ng5  it would be a mistake to play  15...fxe4  , due to the strong reply  16.g4!  , after which  the e7-knight would stay imprisoned. }
15. Qc1
{ It appears logical to force the king to h7, as it could be exposed on the b1-h7 diagonal after a potential ...f7-f5. }
15... Kh7 16. Bd3 f5
{ It's now or never. Everything else would give White the opportunity to further improve his position. }
17. exf5 gxf5 18. Nh4
{ This is the square for the knight in the ...gxf5 structure, once Black's pawn is on h6. }
18... Ng6
{ Black wants to exchange the annoying white knight. Alternatively, the game might continue  18...Rf7  19.Bc2  Increasing the firepower on the kingside by including the rook.  19...Bd7  20.Qb1  Qc8  21.Kh1  Kg8  22.g3  Qd8  Black can only wait and see how White further improves his position.  23.f3  White has a lot of pieces looking to the kingside and flexible pawns.  There is nothing to stop him from opening the position. Here is just one example:  23...Qc8  24.Nc3  Qd8  25.Rg1  Qc8  26.g4  fxg4  27.fxg4  Bxg4  28.Ne4  . White has no less than seven pieces pointing to the kingside! The next move might be Rg3. }
19. Nxg6 Kxg6
{ This looks suspicious, but White must play energetically to exploit the disharmony in Black's position. }
20. Bc2 Kf7
{ After  20...Kh7  21.Rh3  Qf6  22.f3  ,  followed by g4, White's attack will be irresistible. }
21. Rg3 { Less strong is  21.Bxh6  f4  . } 21... f4
{ After  21...Qh4  22.Qb1  Kg8  23.f3  Bd7  24.Rh3  Qf6  25.Kh1  , White is preparing to push the g-pawn. }
22. Bxf4 exf4 23. Qxf4+ { White has a winning attack. } 23... Kg8
{ After  23...Nf6  White will calmly continue with  24.Re1  ,  intending Bh7, followed by Re6, attacking the d-pawn. }
24. Qxh6 Bf5 25. Re1 Bxc2 { 25...Qd7  26.Qg5  Bxc2  27.Re7 } 26. Rxe8 Qd7 27.
Nc7 { Deflecting the queen from the square e6. } 27... Qxc7 28. Rxf8+ Kxf8 29.
Rf3+ Ke8 { 29...Kg8  30.Qe6+  Kh8  31.Rh3  Bh7  32.Qe8+ } 30. Qe6+
{ The point of Nc7! } 30... Qe7 31. Qc8+ Qd8 32. Qxb7 Qe7 33. Qc8+ Qd8 34. Qxa6
