12. Ra3 Kh8
{ The idea to play ...Nfg8 and ...Bh6 is a chance for Black to avoid getting trapped in endings with a bad King's Indian bishop. Then again, this bishop will often be a useful defender, be it for the king or for the weak d-pawn. As I am not one hundred percent sure what to think of this exchange, I would choose a pragmatic approach and stick to the rule: 'Never change a winning team!' Hence, I would simply prevent this exchange, in order to obtain a position, which I already know is good for me. }
13. Bd2 Nfg8 14. Nb5 Ra6 15. Qc1 { No ...Bh6 in the near future. } 15... f5 16.
exf5 gxf5
{ 16...Nxf5  17.Ng5  Nf6  18.Re1  is positionally lost if you take into account piece activity, king safety, and weaknesses. After  18...h6?  White would answer  19.Ne6  and probably exploit the weak pawns on h6 and g6. }
17. g3
{ The pawn is controlling two important squares and creates a hole for the light-squared bishop. }
17... Ng6
{ Black could try to create muddy waters by sacrificing a pawn with  17...f4  18.gxf4  Ng6  . However, after  19.fxe5  dxe5  20.Bg5  Qd7  21.Kh1  there is no real danger for White's king, as there are six 'defenders' nearby. }
18. Ng5 { The knight's jump to e6 will be a permanent concern for Black. }
