19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Be3
{ If you asked yourself, why White went to such great lengths, just to exchange the knight on e7, this is your answer: White wanted to place the bishop on its ideal square without being molested by ...Nf5. }
20... Nb6 { 20...Bf5?  21.g4  Bd7  22.Nxe4 } 21. Qb3 Nd7 22. c5 Kh8 23. c6
{ This pawn has a very restricting effect on Black's pieces and fixes the c-pawn as a target. }
23... Nf6
{ 23...Nc5  24.Qa2  h5  25.Rb1  Kh7  26.Qa7  Bf5  27.Rb7  .  Far advanced pawns, such as the one on c6 certainly enrich the tactical potential. }
24. Ra1 Bg4
{ After  24...Ng4  , Black would lose the c-pawn much quicker:  25.Bxg4  Bxg4  26.Ra7  . }
25. Bf1 Bf5 26. h3 Ne8 27. Ra7 Bf6 28. Nb5
{ Black won't be able to defend the c-pawn, as he lacks space. White will use both, the 7th and the 8th rank for the attack, as well as his dark-squared bishop on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "9... a5 (10. bxa5 Rxa5 11. a4 Ne8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ By challenging White's b-pawn, Black diminishes White's control of the key c5-square. We can also see this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played more than double as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8  .  In our variations, the knight will appear on d7, which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Ne8
{ If you compare this move with  11...Nd7  ,  you easily recognize its pros and cons. Obviously, the drawback of this move is that it doesn't influence the key c5-square. On the positive side we see the following aspects:   1@@EndBracket@@ The light-squared bishop is not hemmed in. Among other things, this affects the control of the square e6, which is relevant in positions, where White reacts to ...f7-f5 with the sortie Ng5-e6.  2@@EndBracket@@ The neuralgic points d6 and c7 are defended in case White plays c4-c5.  3@@EndBracket@@ The knight can be played to the strong d6-square with work. }
12. Be3
{ We haven't seen this move in any previous line at such an early stage. The reasons for this are manyfold, depending on the concrete position. One reason is that it doesn't help to push a4-a5, which is necessary after Black played ...b6. The other reason is exposure. On e3 it is in the sphere of Black's f-pawn @@StartBracket@@...f5-f4 would be lethal with a White knight on d2@@EndBracket@@ and the knights @@StartBracket@@...Nf6-g4, ...Ne7-f5@@EndBracket@@.   For me, this explains its novelty status. People simply don't take it into account. It's 'something you don't play in this position type'. But from a logical point of view, it does indeed make sense. In contrast to other lines, Black neglected the square c5 and this is, where our move places its focus on. }
12... f5
{ After  12...c5  I would recommend  13.Bd2  , as it appears to be the simplest solution.   The alternative  13.dxc6  bxc6  14.Nd2  Ra8  15.Nb3  looks promising, as well. }
13. c5 { The point of Be3 on move twelve is revealed! } 13... f4
{ Black is accepting the offered material, following the motto: 'If your position is bad, at least have a pawn for it.' Let's consider the alternatives:   A@@EndBracket@@  13...Kh8  A semi-waiting move. Black plans the typical King's Indian pawn storm but has to wait until the knight on f3 has disappeared.  14.Nd2  f4  15.Nb3  Ra8  16.Bc1  .  The square d2 is needed for the knight.  16...g5  17.cxd6  cxd6  18.Nd2  Ng6  19.Nc4  g4  20.g3  .  The disruptive f3 was a lethal threat. Now, the first wave of attack has been stopped.   B@@EndBracket@@  13...dxc5  14.Nd2  This works, as Black's rook is unprotected.  14...fxe4  15.Nc4  Ra8  16.Bxc5  . }
14. Bd2 dxc5
{ 14...Rxc5  would allow White to profit from the exposed rook.  15.a5  , closing the route for retreat and at the same time clearing the  square a4 for the knight.  15...Nf6  16.Bd3  c6  17.dxc6  Rxc6  18.Qb3+  Kh8  19.Rfd1  Black's extra pawn doesn't compensate for the structural problems. }
15. Nb5
{ 15.Qb3  Kh8  16.Nb1  followed by Bc3, intending Nbd2-c4 is an interesting alternative. }
15... Ra8 16. Qc2 Nd6 17. Bd3
{ By defending the e-pawn, White threatens to take on c5. } 17... b6 18. a5
{ White needs to create a second weakness, as simply attacking the e5-pawn doesn't suffice, e.g.  18.Bc3  c6! }
18... Bd7
{ 18...Bg4?  19.axb6  Rxa1  20.Rxa1  cxb6  21.Nxd6  Qxd6  22.Ra6  White has the more active pieces, the better king and weak pawns to play against. The pawn is a small price to pay for all these privileges. }
19. axb6
{ Introducing a strong exchange sacrifice. The ensuing position is full of pitfalls for the second player. }
19... Rxa1 20. bxc7 Rxf1+ 21. Bxf1 Qc8 22. Nxd6 Qxc7 23. Nc4
{ Right now, White is a full exchange down, but there is no way for Black to save his e-pawn. }
