[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "9... Ne8 (10. a4 f5 11. a5 Nf6) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Ne8
{ This is one of the most aggressive variations against the Bayonet Attack. Black plans to unroll the typical King's Indian pawn storm by playing ...f7-f5-f4, followed by ...g6-g5-g4.   In contrast to  9...Nh5  , Black won't have any problems with an exposed knight. The downside is, however, that the text move doesn't come with a threat and allows White to unfold his own agenda without delay. }
10. a4
{ I decided to recommend this move instead of the mainline  10.c5  . Our move is less sharp and doesn't involve so many sub-variations. Actually, it has only been played 281 times, opposed to the 1335 games. Instead of trying to directly attack Black's queenside and let him have his ways on the kingside, we neutralize his kingside play and bank on our structural advantage, which in the long-term will play itself. }
10... f5 11. a5
{ Gaining space on the queenside is the basic idea of the Bayonet and needs no further explanation. }
11... Nf6 12. Bg5
{ White is prepared to part with his queen's bishop for good reasons. First of all, the bishop is not needed anymore to make progress on the dark squares of the queenside, as White is already in charge no ...a7-a5 is possible anymore.   Now, the focus must be on suppressing Black's ambitions on the kingside, 'and it is exactly this, that the move is supposed to achieve. If White would continue with the more common  12.Nd2  , Black would be able to equalize after  12...f4  13.c5  g5  14.f3  Ng6  15.Nc4  Rf7  16.Ba3  Bf8  17.b5  dxc5! }
12... Nh5
{ Obviously, the knight is heading towards f4. At the same time, there is the threat of ...h6, as exchanging the bishop for the passive knight on e7 is no attractive prospect. }
13. Qd2
{ White prevents ...h6 and also clears the square d1 for the bishop.   13.Nd2  is an equivalent alternative. }
13... fxe4 { 13...Nf4  14.Bd1  most likely transposes. } 14. Nxe4 Nf4 15. Bd1
{ This reminds me of the move  18.Bd1  in the line @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.b4  Nh5  10.Re1  f5  11.a4  Nf6  12.a5  . Again, the bishop radiates in two directions. Right now,  it overprotects the knight on f3 and is ready to be transferred to c2, b3, or a4. }
15... h6 16. Bxf4
{ Finally, the queen's bishop has to leave the board, but it does so, by exchanging Black's most active piece, which was charged with no less than five tempi. }
16... Rxf4
{ 16...exf4  This way of recapturing liberates the bishop, but on the other hand, White receives good prospects on the e-file. Moreover, Black's f-pawn is exposed and if it is defended by g6-g5, more light squares will be weakened.  17.Rc1  Nf5  18.c5  b6  19.Re1  White's position is close to winning. }
17. Re1 Rf7
{ The rook was exposed on f4. After  17...Bf5  18.Qd3  White would be ready to play g3. }
18. Ra3 Bf5
{ Transferring his knight to d4 is no improvement for Black:   18...Nf5  19.h3!  A multi-purpose move. White is creating air for his king, waits for information, and prepares  a potential g2-g4.  19...Nd4  20.Nxd4  exd4  21.Bc2  Bd7  22.c5  . Black's position is full of weaknesses. }
19. a6
{ White is undermining the square c6 with the effect, that the square b5 turns into a fantastic outpost for the knight on e4. }
19... b6 20. Nh4
{ Black has to decide, whether he wants to part with his important bishop or to withdraw it to a passive square. }
20... Kh7
{ Withdrawing the bishop is not attractive for Black, as his minor pieces are going to be very restricted:   20...Bd7  21.g4!  The weakness of the square f4 is mitigated by the possibility to play Ng2.  21...Rf8  22.h3  Be8  23.Rg3  White has gathered all of his pieces on the kingside and is now ready to open the  position with g4-g5.  23...g5  24.Ng2  Ng6  25.Bc2  Nf4  26.Kh2  Rb8  27.Rf3  Rf7  28.Ng3  White has his opponent already dominated on the light-squares and will find a good moment to open the position with the pawn  breaks c4-c5 or h3-h4. }
21. Nxf5 gxf5
{ This strengthens the control of the light squares but further weakens the king's pawn shelter. After  21...Nxf5  22.Rh3  Kg8  23.c5  Qe7  24.cxb6  cxb6  25.Rc3  Black suffers from many weaknesses on the 6th rank.  The d-pawn could be targeted by Rc6 and Bg4. Apart from that, White could further soften up Black's structure by means of g3, followed by h4-h5. }
22. Bh5
{ As it turned out, the bishop didn't end up on c2 or b3, but was even deployed on the d1-h5 diagonal. That way, d1 proved to be an excellent pivot square, providing a lot of flexibility to the bishop. }
22... Rf8 23. Nc3 Qd7 24. Nb5
{ The knight has arrived on its favorite square, where it pressurizes three black pawns! Through the pressure on the d-pawn, Black won't be able to play ...c7-c6 so easily. As Black's heavy guns are tied to the defense of these weak pawns, their capability to fight on the kingside is severely restricted. }
