Ne7 9. b4 Ne8
{ This is one of the most aggressive variations against the Bayonet Attack. Black plans to unroll the typical King's Indian pawn storm by playing ...f7-f5-f4, followed by ...g6-g5-g4.   In contrast to  9...Nh5  , Black won't have any problems with an exposed knight. The downside is, however, that the text move doesn't come with a threat and allows White to unfold his own agenda without delay. }
10. a4
{ I decided to recommend this move instead of the mainline  10.c5  . Our move is less sharp and doesn't involve so many sub-variations. Actually, it has only been played 281 times, opposed to the 1335 games. Instead of trying to directly attack Black's queenside and let him have his ways on the kingside, we neutralize his kingside play and bank on our structural advantage, which in the long-term will play itself. }
10... f5 11. a5
{ Gaining space on the queenside is the basic idea of the Bayonet and needs no further explanation. }
11... Nf6 12. Bg5
{ White is prepared to part with his queen's bishop for good reasons. First of all, the bishop is not needed anymore to make progress on the dark squares of the queenside, as White is already in charge @@StartBracket@@no a7-a5 possible anymore@@EndBracket@@. Now, the focus must be on suppressing Black's ambitions on the kingside, and it is exactly this, what the move is supposed to achieve. If White would continued with the more common  12.Nd2  , Black would be able to equalize after  12...f4  13.c5  g5  14.f3  Ng6  15.Nc4  Rf7  16.Ba3  Bf8  17.b5  dxc5!  . }
12... h6
{ There are also other alternatives:   A@@EndBracket@@  12...f4?  13.c5  h6  14.Bxf6  Bxf6  15.h3  g5  16.Nh2  is won for White, as Black's kingside initiative came to a standstill.   B@@EndBracket@@  12...Nxe4  13.Nxe4  fxe4  14.Nd2  .  His space advantage on the queenside in combination with the outpost e4 promises White a very comfortable position.   C@@EndBracket@@  12...fxe4  13.Nd2  Nf5  14.Ndxe4  Nd4  15.Bd3  Bf5  16.Ne2  .  As the bishop on g5 supports the control of the square e4, the queen's knight can be used to challenge Black's most active piece. }
13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nd2 { 14.c5  is a decent alternative. } 14... c6
{ Black doesn't want to stay passive and anticipates the advance of White's c-pawn. }
15. c5 cxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 e4 18. Ra2
{ This position occurred in a couple of email games, which could all be drawn through engine power, as the drawing margin hasn't yet been overstepped. In a practical game, things are different, as White enjoys a strong initiative by virtue of his pawn majority. }
