1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Ne8
{ This is one of the most aggressive variations against the Bayonet Attack. Black plans to unroll the typical King's Indian pawn storm by playing ...f7-f5-f4, followed by ...g6-g5-g4.   In contrast to  9...Nh5  , Black won't have any problems with an exposed knight. The downside is, however, that the text move doesn't come with a threat and allows White to unfold his own agenda without delay. }
10. a4
{ I decided to recommend this move instead of the mainline  10.c5  . Our move is less sharp and doesn't involve so many sub-variations. Actually, it has only been played 281 times, opposed to the 1335 games. Instead of trying to directly attack Black's queenside and let him have his ways on the kingside, we neutralize his kingside play and bank on our structural advantage, which in the long-term will play itself. }
10... f5 11. a5
{ Gaining space on the queenside is the basic idea of the Bayonet and needs no further explanation. }
11... h6
{ As after  11...Nf6  , the move  12.Bg5  proved to be very effective in terms of stifling Black's activities, preventing it is well-motivated.  Apart from that, the move prepares the standard pawn storm ... f5-f4, ...g6-g5-g4. }
12. Nd2
{ This move, the intention of which is to stabilize the e4 point and continue with c4-c5, can now be played with a good conscience, as neither knight nor bishop have access to the square g5 anymore. }
12... Nf6 13. c5 f4
{ That's the all-or-nothing move we know from the line 9. Ne1. Here, however, this approach is doomed, as White is much quicker on the queenside. That said, there is no better plan Black could resort to.   Capturing on e4 would provide White with a fantastic outpost, which leaves us with  13...Kh8  . The idea is to maintain the tension while preparing the pawn  storm by vacating the square g8 for the rook, which in turn would allow the bishop to move to f8 in typical fashion.  Now, White simply answers  14.f3  g5  15.Nc4  , probably with a winning advantage. }
14. Ba3 g5 15. b5
{ White is ready to undermine the d6-pawn, the backbone of Black's entire structure, by b5-b6. }
15... g4 16. Nc4 { Now, Black's structure is falling apart. } 16... dxc5
{ The sacrifice  16...f3  17.gxf3  gxf3  18.Bxf3  Bh3  19.Bg2+-  is not really dangerous for White and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1n1b1/3p1n1p/PPPPp3/2N1Ppp1/B1N5/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Ne8?  loses to  17.Bxg4  . }
17. Bxc5 Ng6
{ After  17...Kh7  , White will keep his structure intact by  18.g3  . } 18.
Bxf8 Bxf8 { If only Black could move his bishop to c5... } 19. d6 cxd6 20. Nd5
