1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nd7
{ This way of unblocking the f-pawn is less popular than the previous variation. My explanation for this is that it has no advantages compared to ...Ne8, but provides White with more good options. The idea to prevent c4-c5 is only effective for one move. }
10. a4 f5
{ 10...a5  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Ba3  transposes to the 9...a5 move order. } 11. a5
h6 { 11...Nf6  12.Bg5  transposes to the 9...Ne8 variation. } 12. Nd2 h5
{ Apparently, Black is engaging in the standard King's Indian pawn storm. His unusual move order derives from two assumptions. First of all, he believes that leaving the knight on d7 would deter White from playing c4-c5. Secondly, he appears to be afraid of f4 and Bg4. Before we continue with this line, let's have a look at the alternatives:   A@@EndBracket@@  12...f4?  13.c5  g5   13...dxc5  14.bxc5  Nxc5  15.Ba3  b6  16.Qc2  ,  followed by Rfd1 and Nb3. Black will quickly lose on the queenside.  14.Nc4  Nf6  15.Ba3  g4  16.b5  f3  A desperate attempt.  17.gxf3  gxf3  18.Bxf3  Ng6  19.Kh1  .   B@@EndBracket@@  12...fxe4  ,  inviting the knight to e4 is generally doubtful, but here the position was bad already.  13.Ndxe4  Nf5  14.c5  Nf6  15.Nxf6  Qxf6  16.Ne4  Qe7  17.Bb2  Nd4  18.Bc4  Bf5  19.Re1  , with the direct threat  of Bxd4 followed by Nxd6, as well as the immediate Ng3, challenging the bishop.   C@@EndBracket@@  12...Rf7  Maintaining the tension doesn't prevent White from pushing his c-pawn.  13.c5  dxc5  14.bxc5  Nxc5  15.Bc4  .   D@@EndBracket@@  12...Nf6  13.c5  would lead to the 9...Ne8 variation. }
13. c5 dxc5
{ 13...Nf6  14.f3  f4  15.Nc4  g5  16.Ba3  Ng6  17.b5  intending b6, White is already standing on the doorstep of Black's queenside, while Black's attack didn't get off the ground. }
14. Ba3
{ An interesting motif to remember. Black's knight doesn't receive the opportunity to take on c5 and further on e4. }
14... cxb4 15. Bxb4 Nf6 16. Qb3 Kh8 17. Rad1
{ Black's position will blow up in a not so distant future. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
