[Black "9... c6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 c6
{ This is a rather defensive approach. By establishing central tension, Black wants to prevent White from executing the standard c4-c5 advance. The game will most likely lead to a structure, which we already met in several sections and perceived as very favorable for White. }
10. a4
{ 10.dxc6  Personally, I don't like the idea of granting Black more space, when the alternative is to simply maintain the status quo, in which his pieces are well confined by our pawns.  10...Nxc6  11.Rb1  Bg4  12.Be3  Rc8  13.a4  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Nd4  15.Be2  a5  White has some advantage, but might be worried by the specter of the draw, manifested by Black's control of the dark squares. }
10... a5
{ 10...Bd7  11.Ra3  is a strong prophylactic move compared to the following:  11.a5  cxd5  12.cxd5  Rc8  13.Bd2  Black obtains the chance to perform a prison break by sacrificing the exchange:  13...Rxc3  14.Bxc3  Nxe4  15.Bb2  Nf6  .  This position is still favorable for White, but the increase of disorder has improved Black's practical chances. }
11. bxa5 Qxa5
{ 11...Rxa5  was played in a couple of games, but makes no difference.  12.Ra3  followed by Bd2 with a strong position. }
12. Bd2 c5
{ This is the most frequent continuation. Of course, Black can also try to keep the structure fluid:   A@@EndBracket@@  12...Nh5  13.Re1  Nf4  14.Bf1  .  The knight on f4 makes it nearly impossible for Black to continue with ...f7-f5 in view of the reply Bxf4 exf4 / e5.   B@@EndBracket@@  12...Qc7  13.Qb3  Nd7  14.Be3  Nc5  15.Bxc5  dxc5  .  The c5-pawn is a serious weakness.  16.Rfd1  Rd8  17.h3  , dominating Black's light-squared bishop.  17...Bf8  18.a5  f6  19.Qa2  White will be attacking the c-pawn.   C@@EndBracket@@  12...Ne8  13.Qb3  h6  14.Rfb1  Qd8  15.Qb6  Qxb6   15...Qd7  16.a5  followed by Na4.  16.Rxb6  . The black queen was an important defender of many vulnerable points,  such as the d6-square, c7-square, and b7-square.  16...f5  17.Be1  Nf6  18.Nd2  White will have a long-lasting initiative on the queenside.  If Black did nothing, the next two moves would be a5 and c5. }
13. Nb5 Qd8 14. Bd3 Nh5
{ Everybody who already studied the section on 9...Nh5 should not be intimidated by this move. }
15. Ra3
{ There is no need for  15.Re1  ,  as the bishop can simply drop back to c2 from where it stands. }
15... Ra6
{ 15...Nf4  16.Bc2  This is the ideal square for the light-squared bishop in this structure.  16...f5  That's not necessarily the best move, but what else could Black do?  17.Bxf4   17.Re1  followed by Qc1 is strong for White.  exf4  18.Ng5+-  White will continue with Re1 and Ne6. The light squares are on fire. }
16. Re1 f5
{ For the majority of chess players it is difficult to wait and do nothing. This is even more true for a King's Indian player, who is biased towards active play. Pushing the f-pawn is what he has learned, pushing the f-pawn is what he will normally do. }
17. exf5 Nxf5 { 17...gxf5  18.Nxe5+- } 18. Ng5 { Now, g4 is a threat. } 18...
Bf6
{ The alternatives are:   A@@EndBracket@@  18...Nf4  19.Bxf4  exf4  20.Ne6  Bxe6  21.dxe6  Once more, this pawn will be the final nail in the coffin.   B@@EndBracket@@  18...Nf6  19.Ne6  Bxe6  20.dxe6  Qe7  21.a5  Rc8  If Black doesn't manage to eliminate the intruder, his chances will be slim.   The immediate  21...Qxe6  runs into  22.Nc7  , though.  22.g4  The g-pawn is often the tool that makes Black's position tumble in the Bayonet.  22...Nd4  23.g5  Nh5  24.Nxd4  cxd4  25.Qb3  Qxe6  26.Be4  . }
19. Ne6
{ White engages in a long-term pawn sacrifice, which can be classified under the no-brainer category. }
19... Bxe6 20. dxe6 Nhg7 21. Be4 Qe7 22. Qb1 Nxe6 23. Nc3
{ I love this position. Black is a useless pawn up and very good at demonstrating that he is the rightful owner of the square d4. In terms of piece activity, however, he cannot compete. }
23... Nd8 24. Nd5 Qd7 { 24...Qf7  25.Rf3+- } 25. Qb5 Rc6
{ 25...Qxb5  26.cxb5  Ra7  27.a5+- } 26. Bxf5
{ White parts with his monster bishop, because harvest time has begun. } 26...
Qxf5 { 26...gxf5  27.Rg3+  Kh8  28.Bh6  Rf7  29.Nxf6+- } 27. Bh6 Rf7 28. Rf3
Qe6 29. Ree3 { Smells like zugzwang. } 29... Bg7 30. Rxf7 Qxf7 31. Bg5 Ne6 32.
Ne7+ *

[Event "?"]
