1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Kh8
{ This move looks a bit artificial. It can't be said that Black is really taking off with an attack. On the other hand, the closed position allows for slow maneuvering. Black's point is to clear the g8-square for the knight and dodge potential tricks on the a2-g8 diagonal. Apart from that, this waiting move is good for collecting information. }
10. a4 Neg8
{ Black follows through with his plan to improve his worst placed piece. Black still had the chance to transpose to the line 9.b4 a5 by playing ...a5.   10...Nfg8?!  11.c5  f5  12.Nd2  Bh6?  Exchanging the bad King's Indian bishop via h6 is a motif we have seen several times in the previous chapters. When doing so, Black really has to pick his spots. As was already mentioned, the bishop fulfills an important prophylactic task, by defending the king and by making the pawn-break f2-f4 unattractive for White.  13.Nc4  Bxc1  14.Rxc1  14...fxe4  .  For the sake of preventing the f-pawn thrust, Black invites the knight to e4, with bad consequences for the pawn on d6. The alternatives, however, are not enticing,  (either:)   a@@EndBracket@@  14...Nf6  15.f4  Black suffers from his exposed king.   b@@EndBracket@@  14...f4  This is what you normally want to play after the exchange. The problem is, that White is in a position to directly  attack the c7-d6 structure.  15.Nb5  Rf6  16.Nxc7  This is the most straightforward line.  16...Qxc7  17.cxd6  Rxd6  18.Nxe5  Qb8  19.Nf7  15.cxd6  cxd6  16.Nxe4  Nf5  17.Bg4  Ngh6  18.Bxf5  Nxf5  19.f4!  exf4  20.Rxf4  Qe7  21.g4+-  After the d-pawns is captured, Black's king will become the next target. }
11. c5 Nh5
{ 11...Bh6  12.Nd2Ν  There is no need to avoid the exchange of bishops by playing Ba3.  12...Ne8  13.Nc4  Bxc1  14.Rxc1  g5   14...f5  This doesn't work anymore without the King's Indian bishop.  15.f4  .  15.Bg4!  f5  16.Bxf5  Bxf5  17.exf5  Rxf5  18.Ne4+-  White's knights are very impressive. }
12. Re1
{ This flexible move is often seen in the course against the ...Nh5 idea. }
12... f5
{ 12...Nf4?  13.Bf1  f5  14.exf5Ν  Bxf5  15.Bxf4  exf4  16.Rc1+-  Black's position is full of soft spots @@StartBracket@@f4, e6 and c7@@EndBracket@@. The knight on c3 can reach e6 via b5-d4 or e4-g5. }
13. exf5 Bxf5
{ 13...gxf5  Black takes the square e4 under control, but weakens the royal pawn shield.  14.a5  Nhf6  15.a6  Undermining the square c6 and establishing an outpost for the knight on b5.  15...b6  16.cxd6  cxd6  17.Ng5  Ne8  18.Bb5  Nc7  19.Bc6  Rb8  20.Qh5+-  . }
14. a5
{ Once more, pushing the a-pawn is a useful tool. Black is in a dilemma and has to decide between the lesser of two evils. }
14... a6
{ This stops the positional threat of a6, but now, either the square b6 will become weak or the a-pawn itself. }
15. Ra3 Nf4
{ 15...Bh6  16.g3  Bxc1  17.Qxc1  Nhf6  18.Bc4  Kg7  19.Qb2+-  Exchanging the often bad King's Indian bishop is always a double-edged sword for Black. In this position, Black has to maintain the pawn on e5 by all means, which strongly reduces his options. White will continue with one of the following plans:    Ng5-e6;  Bf1-g2, Nd2-c4, b4-b5;  f2-f4 at some point. }
16. Bf1 Nf6 { 16...Bg4  17.Ne4  Nf6  18.Bxf4  Nxe4  19.Bc1  Nf6  20.h3+- } 17.
Rb3 { That's both, prophylaxis against ...dxc5 and preparation of b4-b5. }
17... Bg4 { 17...dxc5  doesn't work because of  18.Rxe5  . } 18. Bxf4 exf4
{ Obviously, the soft spot e6 is very exposed in this structure. } 19. h3 Bxf3
20. Qxf3 Nd7 21. Ne4 Qe7 22. Rbb1 Ne5
{ This might be a good example of an optical illusion. Apparently, Black has solved most of his problems, by liberating his bishop and installing his knight in the center. Now, guess how Stockfish evaluates the situation? It sees White more than 2.5 pawn units ahead. Black simply has too many weaknesses. }
23. Qa3 Rfd8 24. cxd6 { 24.b5  also wins. } 24... cxd6 25. b5 axb5 26. Rxb5 Rd7
27. Rb6 Rad8 28. Qb4 h6 29. Rb1
{ Black can stay in the game with  29...Ra8  ,  but he still is lost in the long run. White might put the rook from b1 to b5 or try to accomplish Nd2-b3-d4-e6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "9... h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 h6
{ This move looks slow, as did the previous variation. In reality, it is hardly worse than any other move and is likely to transpose to other lines. Black prevents Bg5 and especially Ng5 for good, which constitutes a problem after Black plays ...f7-f5. Additionally, he could now push his g-pawn, if necessary, or use the vacant square h7 for his king or knight. The biggest motivation to play this move might be a little trap. }
10. a4
{ 10.c5  This natural looking move is what Black is counting on.  10...c6  gets Black close to equality.   10.Nd2  is an equivalent alternative to our main line. }
10... Ne8
{ Black's best option appears to be  10...a5  , with transposition to the line 9.b4 a5.. }
11. c5 a5
{ This just helps White to bring his dark-squared bishop into play.   11...f5  12.a5  transposes to the variation with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.b4  Ne8  10.a4  f5  11.a5  h6  . }
12. Ba3 axb4
{ 12...f5?  13.bxa5Ν  fxe4  14.Nd2  Nf5  15.Ncxe4  Rxa5  16.Nc4  Ra8  17.Rb1+-  A nice picture, demonstrating how weak pawns lead to a devaluation of the pieces. }
13. Bxb4 f5
{ After  13...dxc5  14.Bxc5  Nd6  15.Nd2  f5  ,  White can play in dynamic fashion:  16.Nc4Ν  Nxe4  17.Nxe4  fxe4  18.d6  cxd6  19.Nxd6  with the threat to capture on c8.  19...Be6  20.Nxb7+-  . }
14. Nd2 fxe4
{ After the passive  14...Kh7  15.a5  Ng8  16.Nc4  Ngf6  17.exf5  Bxf5  18.Qb3  ,  White is winning and may continue with Rad1, followed by cxd6 and then Nb5. }
15. Ndxe4 Nf5 16. Bd3 Nd4 17. cxd6 Nxd6
{ 17...cxd6  18.a5  Bf5  19.Rb1  Kh7  20.f3  Rf7  21.Na4+-  Black's passive position makes the engine suggest the exchange sacrifice which will not be enough.  21...Rxa5  22.Bxa5  Qxa5  23.Nb6  followed by Nc4 will enhance the pressure on the d-pawn. }
18. Nxd6 cxd6 19. Ne4 Nf5 20. a5
{ The next step could be to transfer the rook to b6. Later the bishop might reappear on b4, while the queen could contribute from a3. }
