1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 b6 { This doesn't prevent the breakthrough, it encourages it! } 10.
c5 bxc5
{ White's pieces can make good use of every line that opens on the queenside. }
11. bxc5 c6
{ 11...dxc5  White will regain the pawn, when Black's structure lays in ruins:  12.Ba3  Nd7   12...Qd6  13.Nd2  Ba6  14.Na4+-  13.Na4Ν  Re8  14.Rc1+- }
12. Ba3 { The key to victory is the square d6. } 12... Qa5 13. Qb3 dxc5
{ 13...cxd5  14.cxd6  Nc6  15.d7+-  winning the exchange. } 14. d6 Be6 15. Qa4
Qxa4 16. Nxa4 Nc8 17. Nxc5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "9... a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a6
{ This is the best of the unpopular moves. Black combines some kind of accelerated prophylaxis against the push a2-a4-a5-a6 and against Nb5 ideas with a little trap. }
10. a4 { 10.c5  is rushing things as  10...c6  would get black near equality. }
10... Nh5
{ Funnily enough, after  10...a5  I know, nobody would play that  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Ba3   12.h3  White could make this counter-semi-waiting move, preparing a potential Be3.  b6  Black still has a playable position. The reason for this is, that the Ba3-b4 setup is especially strong with Black's knight on d7. So here White is a tempo up, but Black can put his knight on a better square. A trade-off, as it seems.   10...Nd7  11.a5Ν  f5  12.c5!  Sacrificing the c-pawn for the purpose of isolating Black's e-pawn and opening lines and diagonals for White's pieces is a permanent background motif.  12...dxc5  13.Bc4  Kh8  14.bxc5  Nxc5  15.Ba3  Nxe4  16.Nxe4  fxe4  17.Ng5±  White's pieces are extremely active. Future moves could be Qe2, Rfd1, Ne6, and Rb1. }
11. Re1 f5 12. c5 fxe4 { 12...Nf6  13.Nd2+- } 13. Nxe4 Nf4 14. Bf1 h6
{ 14...Bg4?  15.Ra3  overprotecting f3 and preparing 16.h3.  15...Nf5  16.g3  Nh3+  17.Bxh3  That's why earlier it was important to play Bf1 and not Bc4.  17...Bxh3  18.Nfg5±  . }
15. Bxf4 Rxf4 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. Nfd2
{ White, intends Nc4 and is close to winning. } *

