12. Bxf4 exf4 13. e5
{ Black's vulnerable king, together with White's better pawn structure and central dominance justify this strong statement. }
13... g5
{ As the knight on c3 is unprotected, there was no immediate threat of White playing e6. Consequently, Black is challenging White's e-pawn by planning g4. }
14. exd6
