{ White has three principal ideas:   1@@EndBracket@@ Occupying the square e6 with the knight.   2@@EndBracket@@ Pushing the c-pawn to c6.  3@@EndBracket@@ Playing c5 and Nb5, thus unblocking the d-pawn. }
15. Rc1 Ng6 16. c5 g4 17. Nd4 Be5
{ A logical move, both in a defensive and offensive sense. The problem is, however, that e5 cannot really be called a stable outpost. }
18. Ne6 { This move could be called a liberator. } 18... Bxe6 19. dxe6
{ Let's sum up, what has been liberated:   The a2-diagonal is available for White's pieces. Queen and knight have the square d5 available.  The queen is in contact with Black's d-pawn.  The blocked d-pawn has turned into a mobile e-pawn. }
19... g3 { 19...Kh8  20.Nd5+- } 20. fxg3 fxg3 21. Nd5 Qh4 22. h3 Rae8 23. e7
{ Black's position was ripe for a little tactical blow. } 23... Nxe7
{ 23...Rf7  24.cxd6  Bxd6  25.Bb5+- } 24. Nc7 Rc8 { 24...Rd8  25.Ne6+- } 25.
cxd6 Qd4+ 26. Qxd4 Bxd4+ 27. Kh1 Ng6 28. Bc4+ Kh8 29. Ne6 *

