[White "1) 9.b4 Nh5 10.Re1 Nf4 "]
[Black "12.c5 g5 13.Nd2 f5 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... Nf4
{ Consistent play, but bad. On f4 the knight is more liability than an asset. }
11. Bf1
{ I always loved the harmony of this particular rook-bishop constellation, which can be found in many different openings. Black can now choose between  11...f5?  ,  11...h6?  ,  11...a5  , and  11...Bg4  . }
11... h6
{ Some players used this move as preparation for  12.c5  f5  by preventing the Ng5-e6 maneuver. But they underestimated the Bxf4 idea, which we have seen in the previous chapter.   The majority intended  12.c5  g5  , with the idea to support the knight on f4 before playing ...f5, thus ruling out Bxf4. }
12. c5
{ After a small prophylactic intermezzo, White continues with what he started on move 9. Even though it may come to you as a surprise, it can already be stated that Black cannot prevent checkmate anymore. This might happen as late as 40 moves down the road, but it will eventually happen @@StartBracket@@I am talking about the analysis, not games@@EndBracket@@.   Compare Black's position with the Titanic after her encounter with the iceberg. There was a time of agony, but her fate was already sealed directly after the impact. In this position, Black simply suffers from too many deficiencies.   On top of what was described in the introduction, we see a misplaced knight on f4 and the last move didn't help either. Black's queenside is defenseless and will be overrun. The only means against this automatic development is counterplay on the kingside. In this position, however, there is no such thing as serious counterplay. }
12... g5
{ Black is now prepared to play ...f5, as Bxf4 no longer has to be feared. Additionally, the square g6 is cleared for the knights and the advance ...g5-g4 is an option.   In spite of all the goodies, the position is positionally lost, due to White's automatic attack on the queenside and the weakness of the light-squared color complex in Black's camp after ...f7-f5. }
13. Nd2 f5
{ Black's position looks reasonably active, but there is not much potential for improvement, as the pawn storm ...f5-f4, followed by ...g5-g4-g3 is not possible with the knight on f4.   The downside of Black's setup will soon become visible. Four of White's pieces are very happy right now. The knights just received a fantastic outpost on e4 and the queen and bishop will find a good occupation on the light squares. }
14. cxd6
{ White can also play  14.Nc4  , which introduces interesting opportunities such as Nc3-b5xc7.  For me as a presenter, however, it is more convenient not to bother you with the added complexity, caused by the constant possibility of Black playing dxc5.   Let's keep it simple and don't forget, that the position is already won. We don't have to squeeze out an additional 0.1 pawn units here. }
14... cxd6 15. Nc4
{ Now Black has to deal with two monsters: the one that might appear on e4 and the one that has already arrived on its ideal square c4. }
15... g4
{ This is the most frequent move. Black deals with the imminent threat of g3, after which his super-ambitious knight would be otherwise condemned to accept a cheerless existence on g6.   The downside of this idea, however, is the exposure of the g-pawn and the re-emerging menace of White playing Bxf4, followed by e5. }
16. b5
{ As Black still is far away from establishing threats on the kingside, White proceeds with his agenda. Obviously, the queen's bishop would now have clear sight on target from a3. }
16... Rf6
{ Understandably, Black wants to overprotect the d-pawn. Now, the rook could move further to g6, to get out of the bishop's way and to oppose the white king, for what it is worth. }
17. a4
{ The long-term idea is to push the pawn to b6, in order to create an entry square on c7 for the rook.   17.Qb3  was played by two grandmasters and is by no means bad.  However, it is even stronger to leave the queen influencing the d1-h5 diagonal. }
17... h5
{ Fortifying the g-pawn, but creating other weaknesses, instead. It is difficult to find decent alternatives, however.   17...Rg6?  Avoiding weaknesses, but depriving the knight on e7 of its last square.  18.Bxf4  exf4  19.e5  dxe5?!  20.d6+-   17...Neg6?  18.exf5  Bxf5  19.Ne3!  h5  The only move avoiding material loss.   19...Qd7  20.Nxf5  Qxf5  21.Ne4+-  20.Nxf5  Rxf5  21.Ne4+-  This is the ultimate 'knightmare' for the kings indian player. Not only is it protecting f2 and threatening the d-pawn. By blocking the e-pawn, it also makes some of Black's minor pieces look pretty stupid.   17...Nxg2!?  Actually, the engine slightly favors this move compared to others. Even though it is not to be feared, at least Black has something to play for, now.  18.Kxg2  f4  19.Kh1  Ng6  20.b6  a6  21.Ba3  Bf8   21...Nh4  22.Be2  f3  23.Bd3  h5  24.Rg1+-  22.a5  Rf7  23.Ne2  Qf6  24.Nd2  The knights are protecting the kingside, while at the same time clearing the c-file.  24...Qh4  25.Kg1  h5  26.Rc1  Qg5  27.Rc7+-  There is no way Black can break through, as you can check for yourself. I just give you one line as an example.   27.Rc7  h4  28.Kh1  g3  29.Rxf7  Kxf7  30.Ng1  gxf2  31.Ngf3  Qh5  32.Re2  Bg4  33.Rxf2+- }
18. g3 Nfg6 { 18...Nh3+  19.Bxh3  gxh3  20.Bg5  Rf7  21.Qxh5+- } 19. Bg5
{ Allowing this move is surely a drawback of ...h5 from move seventeen. } 19...
Rf8 20. exf5 { We don't want to let f4 happen. } 20... Bxf5 21. b6 a6
{ 21...axb6  22.Nb5+- } 22. Rc1 Rc8 23. a5
{ The b-pawn needs protection, so the c4-knight can move. } 23... Bf6 24. Qd2
{ Black's position resembles a Swiss cheese. I marked the weak pawns and the entrance square c7. But of course, Black's entire kingside stands wide open. The engine awards White's advantage with more than 6 pawn units. I will now prosaically show, how the game could typically unfold. }
24... Rc5 25. Bxf6 Rxf6 26. Ne3 Kg7 { 26...Rxa5  27.Ne4  Bxe4  28.Qxa5+- } 27.
Nxf5+ Nxf5 28. Ne4 Nd4 29. Re3 Rxc1 30. Qxc1 Rf7 31. Rc3 Rd7 32. Rc7
{ Black's position has finally been invaded.   32.Rc7  Re7  33.Rxe7+  The queenside structure makes the liquidation into a won ending the simplest solution.  33...Qxe7  34.Qc7  34...Nf5  35.Qxe7+  Ngxe7  36.Bxa6!  Nxd5  37.Bxb7  and so on. By playing b5-b6, White not only created an invasion square on c7, it also turned Black's queenside pawns into potential bishop fodder. It's always good to have such endgame patterns in the back of your mind. }
