{ The attempt to destroy White's vanguard will result in a strong white passed pawn on d6. }
14. cxd6 Qxd6 15. Nc4 Qd7
{ 15...Qf6?  16.d6  Neg6  17.d7+-  and also of note that @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2npb1/2pq3p/3Pp1p1/1PN1Pn2/2N5/P4PPP/R1BQRBK1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Qxb4  16.Bd2  cxd5  17.Nxd5+-  loses as well. }
16. d6 Neg6 17. a4
{ Obviously, White wants to stabilize his knight on c4, thus protecting the passed pawn. }
17... Ne6 18. a5 Nd4 19. Ne2
{ One of two goods things can happen. Either Black's most active piece gets exchanged or the knight will move on to g3, where it is better placed than on c3. }
19... Nb5
{ 19...Qe6  20.Be3!  Black is positionally lost, as he is unable to maintain his knight on d4.  20...Qxc4?  21.Nxd4  Qxb4  22.Nb3  22...Qxe4  23.d7+-  . }
20. Be3 Nf4 21. Ng3 Qd8 22. Bc5 { The d-pawn is safe. } *

