14... Ra8 15. a5
{ Played analogous to the main line and improving on  15.Bxf4  exf4  16.e5  , which was only clearly better for White in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Kiviaho, A @@StartBracket@@2242@@EndBracket@@-Behm, J @@StartBracket@@2132@@EndBracket@@ Finland 1999. }
15... Kh8 16. Ra3
{ By overprotecting the knight, White turns Bxf4 into a threat. } 16... fxe4
{ 16...h6?  17.Bxf4  exf4  18.e5+- } 17. Nxe4 b6
{ 17...Kg8  18.Rb3+-  Taking the sting out of ...b6 and binding the bishop to the defence of the b-pawn. After expelling the traveler from f4, White will push his c-pawn. }
18. g3 Nh3+ 19. Bxh3
{ There is no problem with giving up the light-squared bishop, as its counter part is already doomed. }
19... Bxh3 20. Nfg5 Bd7 21. Rf3
{ The Ra3 is not only watching the scene from a distance, often it will be switched to where the action is. }
21... Kg8
{ 21...Nf5  22.g4  Nd4  23.Nf7+  Rxf7  24.Rxf7  Kg8  25.Rxg7+  Kxg7  26.Bc3+-  Removing the knight means accessing Black's king. }
22. axb6 cxb6 23. Ne6 Bxe6 24. dxe6
{ Black's problem points are now f7 and d6. } 24... Qc8 25. Rxf8+ Bxf8 26. Qf3
Nf5 27. g4 Nd4 28. Qf7+ Kh8 29. Ng5 Bg7 30. Be3
{ 30.Be3  Nc2  31.Rc1  Nxe3  32.fxe3+- } *

