{ This break was coming sooner or later. Now, the c-file gets opened and Black's d-pawn is turned into a weakness. }
24... Nf6
{ This looks like another good opportunity to activate the offside knight, doesn't it? As it turns out, appearances are deceptive. }
25. Ngxf6+ Bxf6 26. Nxf6+
{ Giving up the strong knight for the bad King's Indian bishop?! What follows is a good example of the defensive or prophylactic properties of so-called bad pieces. }
26... Qxf6 27. Rf3 { White prepares the exchange of yet another defender. }
27... Qe7 28. cxd6 cxd6 29. g4 Nd4 30. Rxf7+ Qxf7 31. f4
{ That's the point. Now, that the bishop is gone, White simply changes the structure. Black's king will dearly miss his personal bodyguard. }
*

