27. Rb3
{ That's a strong exchange sacrifice. If you don't feel like sacrificing material, the game continuation  27.Bf1  Ra7  28.Ne3  Nd4  29.a6+-  from 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Galytskyi, V @@StartBracket@@2318@@EndBracket@@ -Staf, G @@StartBracket@@2120@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2011 is fully sufficient. }
27... Nd4 28. Rb2 Ne2+ 29. Kh2 Nxc1 30. Qxc1
{ The threat is to take on h6 and then further on g7, in order to penetrate on h6 with the queen. }
30... Rc7 { 30...Qf8  31.axb6  Bxd5  32.Bxh6+- } 31. Qb1 Bc8
{ 31...Bxd5  is tactically refuted:  32.axb6  Rb7  33.Qd3  33...Raxb6  34.Rxb6  Rxb6  35.Qxd5+-  Black suffers from three weak pawns and two weak minor pieces. }
32. Rxb6 Rxb6 33. Qxb6 Rd7 34. Qb4
{ The combination of Black's passive pieces, his weak d-pawn, unsafe king and, most importantly, White's passed a-pawn, makes this position an easy win for White. }
