10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... Nf4
{ Consistent play, but bad. On f4 the knight is more liability than an asset. }
11. Bf1
{ I always loved the harmony of this particular rook-bishop constellation, which can be found in many different openings. Black can now choose between  11...f5?  ,  11...h6?  ,  11...a5  , and  11...Bg4  . }
11... a5 12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. a4 c5
{ Black wants to stop the advance c4-c5 once and for all. } 14. Ra3 h6
{ Black wants to fortify the knight on f4 with the g-pawn followed by a standard ...f5 break. }
15. Nb5 g5
{ As we will see, this idea turns out to be flawed on different levels.   15...Ra6  16.Bd2!  leads to the mainline. }
16. g3
{ The alternative  16.h4  also wins, which is explained in the main line. }
16... Nfg6 17. Nd2
{ Black is already lost, as he handed over the light squares by playing g5. If he now stays put, White will occupy the light squares according to the arrows. When this is done, the position is ripe for h2-h4 at some stage. }
17... f5
{ Black doesn't want to go under without a fight. However, donating the square e4 to White's knight can hardly be advisable. }
18. exf5 Bxf5 19. Ne4 Nc8
{ 19...Bxe4  20.Rxe4+-  After resigning on the light squares, Black still felt like continuing to play on the dark squares for a while. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Lupor,A @@StartBracket@@2281@@EndBracket@@-Thakoerdien,J @@StartBracket@@2115@@EndBracket@@ Leiden 2014. }
20. Qh5 Nge7 21. Bh3 { Removing the guardian of the light squares. } 21... Qd7
22. Bxf5 Nxf5 23. h4 { The time for the battering ram has come. } 23... gxh4
24. g4 Nd4 25. Nxd4 cxd4 26. Bxh6
{ Black will lose the h-pawn, but is also positionally lost on top of this. } *

