{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... f5 { Apparently, this move is better than  10...Nf4  . } 11. a4
{ That's a good example of what I call an 'undervalued sideline'. As it happens, our line here complies with the laws of risk management. Let's have a look at all these principles:  1. Economy:  11.a4  is ranking 5th in terms of frequency and was played less than 100 times, as opposed to 5,  000  games with  11.Ng5  . In all likelihood, studying  11.a4  is far less work-intensive.   2. Information Warfare: Everyone wants to surprise his opponent and throw him out of his book knowledge. Obviously, sidelines come with a higher chance for success in this respect.   3. Risk Management: I will sum up some of the rules and then explain how they relate to this position.   a@@EndBracket@@ If you have a clear advantage, avoid risk, as you have more to lose compared to a situation of parity.   b@@EndBracket@@ Dynamic play is inherently more risky than static play, as it bears the risk of miscalculations.   c@@EndBracket@@ If you suffer from a static disadvantage, you are in a downtrend. Normally, every move that passes leads you further down this slope and it will become more and more difficult to break out. Hence, you have to try to break this trend with dynamic play as early as possible. No time for caution!   d@@EndBracket@@ If you have a dynamic advantage, you have to play dynamically, as otherwise your dynamic advantage might evaporate.   e@@EndBracket@@ If you have a static advantage, play statically, as you are in an uptrend and normal play will enhance and fortify your advantage. Your major goal is to prevent your opponent from breaking the trend by dynamic play, i.e counterplay. Hence, you ought to play in prophylactic fashion.   Conclusion: White not only has a large overall advantage, already. His advantage is also static in nature. Hence, it appears recommendable to stay away from the sharp play initiated by 11.Ng5, intending Ne6, if a calmer alternative is available.   Let's now discuss the positive intentions of 11.a4:  1. White gains space in a general sense. His idea is to continue with a4-a5.  2. The rook receives the fantastic square a3, from where it will influence the entire 3rd rank and might help to defend the kingside.   3. The bishop could now be placed on a3, in order to pressurize the pawn on d6, without blocking the a-pawn. }
11... Nf4
{ Let's start with the positive aspect. We are dealing here with an improved version of the line @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Re1  Nf4  11.Bf1  f5  .  As the bishop is still on e2, White cannot answer  with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1n1bp/3p2p1/3Ppp2/PPP1Pn2/2N2N2/4BPPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bxf4  exf4  13.e5  . However,  this doesn't wipe away the fact, that the knight is misplaced on f4, as shown by the following analysis. }
12. Bf1 h6 { This is refuted by methods, we are already acquainted with. } 13.
Bxf4 fxe4
{ 13...exf4  14.e5  g5  15.Rc1  g4  16.exd6  cxd6  17.Nd4+-  1-0 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Hetzer,V @@StartBracket@@2137@@EndBracket@@-Kiefer,D @@StartBracket@@2239@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2004. }
14. Bxe5 exf3 15. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Suba,M @@StartBracket@@2502@@EndBracket@@-Ruano Marco,J @@StartBracket@@2177@@EndBracket@@ Alcala de Henares 2007. }
16. g3
{ This is better than the game continuation  16.Qd4+  , as now the queen stays in touch with Black's weak-f-pawn. }
*

