10... f5 11. a4 Nf6
{ That's much better than  11...Nf4?  .  From f6, the knight really contributes to the position by fighting for the key square e4. }
12. a5
{ As Black's last move didn't contain a threat, White simply claims more space. Amongst others, the advance a5-a6 is now to be reckoned with, undermining the square c6 and consequently establishing an outpost for the knight on b5. There is also a prophylactic aspect to 12.a5!, as it prevents Black from playing ...a7-a5. Thus, White has secured his control over the key square c5.   Now, Black has many options, which can be grouped as follows:  1. Black relieves the tension with  12...Nxe4  or  12...fxe4  .  2. Black maintains the tension.  3. Black increases the tension with  12...c6  . }
