{ This is clearly the most frequent continuation. Black creates space for the activation of his pieces. }
13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Ng5 e3
{ This desperado is necessary, in order to activate the king's indian bishop. }
15. Bxe3 Nf5 16. Bd2 Bh6
{ Now, White has to be careful not to play  17.Ne4?  Bxd2  18.Qxd2  Nd4  , letting Black exchange his bad bishop and establish a strong knight in the center. }
17. Qc1
{ As White doesn't want to exchange bishops, supporting the knight on its influential outpost is the right thing to do. Alternatively, White could think about the liquidation  17.Ne6  Bxe6  18.Bxh6  Nxh6  19.dxe6  Qe7  20.c5  , which is interesting, but more chaotic. }
17... Nd4 18. Bd1
{ White had to cover the square b3, so dropping the bishop back to f1 was not an option. At first glance it may appear artificial to place the bishop on d1, as it interferes with the coordination of the major pieces. This however, is an illusion, as the natural square for the queen's rook is a3. On d1 the bishop radiates towards both wings and has a lot of options, once Black's knight has disappeared. }
18... Rb8 19. Ra3 b6
{ 19...b5  20.cxb5  Rxb5  21.Nf3  ,  reducing dynamic complexity in positions with static advantage is the standard procedure.  21...Bxd2  22.Qxd2  Nxf3+  23.Bxf3+-  It is difficult to save a position with three weaknesses. }
20. a6
{ Before moving the rook to the kingside, the tension has to be resolved. In the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@74@@EndBracket@@ Gonzaga Grego, L @@StartBracket@@2403@@EndBracket@@-Verhaeren, G @@StartBracket@@2359@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018, White let Black equalize after  20.Rg3?  bxa5  21.b5  a6  . }
20... b5
{ Black's rook insists in participating, allowing White access to the c-pawn. }
21. h4 bxc4 22. Qxc4 Qd7 23. f4
{ A good example for duality. Being actively placed, Black's knight definitively is an asset. On the flipside, it is also a liability, as it binds the e-pawn, which is now under attack. }
23... Bxg5 { 23...Bg7  24.Ne6  Nxe6  25.dxe6  Qxe6  26.Qxc7+- } 24. hxg5 Qf7
25. Be3 Nb5 26. Ra2 exf4 27. Bc1 Bd7 28. Rf2
{ White threatens to bring his powerful bishops into position, and takes a peek at Black's king. }
28... Rbe8 29. Re6 c6
{ Black has to undermine the outpost e6, but now the position opens up even more for the bishops. }
30. Rxe8 Rxe8 31. Bf3
{ White's powerful pieces are not short of targets, as the knight won't stay on b5 forever. 1-0  @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Esposito,L @@StartBracket@@2443@@EndBracket@@-De Bari,V @@StartBracket@@2440@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017. }
