10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... f5 11. a4 Nf6
{ That's much better than  11...Nf4?  .  From f6, the knight really contributes to the position by fighting for the key square e4. }
12. a5
{ As Black's last move didn't contain a threat, White simply claims more space. Amongst others, the advance a5-a6 is now to be reckoned with, undermining the square c6 and consequently establishing an outpost for the knight on b5. There is also a prophylactic aspect to 12.a5!, as it prevents Black from playing a7-a5. Thus, White has secured his control over the key square c5. Now, Black has many options, which can be grouped as follows:   1. Black relieves the tension with 12...Nxe4 or 12...fxe4,   2. Black maintains the tension   3. Black increases the tension with 12...c6. }
12... Nxe4
{ This is clearly the most frequent continuation. Black creates space for the activation of his pieces. }
13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Ng5 e3
{ This desperado is necessary, in order to activate the king's indian bishop. }
15. Bxe3 Nf5 16. Bd2 Bh6
{ Now, White has to be careful not to play  17.Ne4?  Bxd2  18.Qxd2  Nd4  , letting Black exchange his bad bishop and establish a strong knight in the center. }
17. Qc1
{ As White doesn't want to exchange bishops, supporting the knight on its influential outpost is the right thing to do. Alternatively, White could think about the liquidation  17.Ne6  Bxe6  18.Bxh6  Nxh6  19.dxe6  Qe7  20.c5  , which is interesting, but more chaotic. }
17... Nd4 18. Bd1
{ White had to cover the square b3, so dropping the bishop back to f1 was not an option. At first glance it may appear artificial to place the bishop on d1, as it interferes with the coordination of the major pieces. This however, is an illusion, as the natural square for the queen's rook is a3. On d1 the bishop radiates towards both wings and has a lot of options, once Black's knight has disappeared. }
18... Qe7
{ In two other games, Black became active with the b-pawn in search for counterplay. As this method creates a weakness on c7, it can hardly be called an improvement, though. }
19. Ra3 Bd7 20. a6 { 20.c5  Rae8  21.Rc3  is a good alternative. } 20... b6 21.
Rd3 Rf5
{ It's never easy to criticize strong email players, but apparently, the rook is too exposed on that square. }
22. h4 Qg7 23. Be3
{ 23.b5  happened in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Gonzaga Grego, L @@StartBracket@@2403@@EndBracket@@-Pellen, M @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018, after which White is clearly better, due to his attacking chances on the kingside. }
23... Rff8
{ 23...Raf8?  Playing for tactics doesn't work:  24.Qd2  Now, we threaten to win material.  24...R5f6  25.Ne4  Bxe3  26.fxe3+-  . }
24. f4 Rae8 25. fxe5 dxe5 26. c5
{ White is winning, as he has more space, the more active pieces and the better king. The knight on g5 is difficult to tolerate. But if it is taken, Black's king will be even more exposed.   26.c5  Bb5  27.Rc3  Qf6  28.d6  Qd8   28...cxd6?  would grant White a dangerous passed pawn plus invasion.  29.cxb6  axb6  30.a7+-  .  29.dxc7  Qxc7  30.Qb2+-  Black's biggest problem is his exposed king. }
*

