1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... f5 11. a4 Nf6 12. a5 Kh8
{ By removing the king from the a2-g8 diagonal, Black is preventing c5. At the same time, the square g8 is cleared for the knight on e7. }
13. Bf1
{ 13.c5?  would allow Black to bail out into an unclear position after  13...dxc5  14.bxc5  fxe4  15.Ng5  Nexd5  . }
13... Neg8 14. c5
{ As Black's knight has left e7, this is possible, now. Another option was to further improve the position with  14.Ra3  . }
14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Ng5 Nf6 17. cxd6
{ In the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Kuybokarov, T @@StartBracket@@2519@@EndBracket@@-G, A @@StartBracket@@2411@@EndBracket@@ Dubai 2019, White could have instead played  17.a6?  , Black could have defended dynamically with  17...bxa6  18.Bxa6  dxc5  19.Bxc8  Qxc8  20.bxc5  Qd7  with pressure against the d-pawn. }
17... cxd6 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Rxe4 Bf5 20. Rc4
{ Yet another position for my 'camouflaged +- collection'. To be honest, I wouldn't have guessed that this one is already won for White before performing the analysis. So, how can this possibly be the case? Let me sum up the ingredients:   1@@EndBracket@@ The black king is lacking good pawn protection.   2@@EndBracket@@ The bishop on g7 is passive; playing e4 would weaken the e-pawn.   3@@EndBracket@@ The bishop on f5 is susceptible to being expelled by g2-g4.  4@@EndBracket@@ Black's queenside is threatened by an invasion on c7.  5@@EndBracket@@ Black will be forced to concede the square b6 to the bishop, once his a-pawn is under attack by Be3 or even earlier. Obviously, this will facilitate the invasion on c7.  6@@EndBracket@@ Black's queenside pawns can easily become a target for White's bishops, once they are fixed.   7@@EndBracket@@ Let's not forget Black's permanent weakness on d6.   I will now try to prove this evaluation, but cannot be completely exhaustive, as this is beyond the scope of an opening course. Hence, some of the lines will be of exemplary nature.   20.Rc4  a6  This time, Black doesn't want his a-pawn getting fixed on the 7th rank.   20...Rc8  21.Rxc8  Qxc8  22.a6!  b6  Now, the a-pawn is a serious weakness.   22...bxa6?  23.Rxa6+-  23.Bg5  Rf7   23...Bf6  Black doesn't want to tolerate the bishop on g5, as it is a threat to all of the queenside pawns.  24.Bh6  Bg7  25.Rc1  Qd8  26.Be3  h5   26...Bd7  27.Qc2+-  followed by Qc7.  27.Rc6  Rf7  28.Qc1  As White seized control over the c-file, Black will have to permanently watch the squares c7 and c8.  28...Kh7  29.h3  Bf6  30.Be2  The threat is to drive the bishop away from f5, after which the invasion of White's rook cannot be prevented anymore.  30...e4   30...Qd7  31.b5  Kg7  32.Qa3  This is an example for how White can leverage the weakness of the d-pawn.  32...Be7  33.Bxb6!  axb6  34.a7+-   30...Kg7  31.g4  hxg4  32.hxg4  Bd7  33.g5  Be7  34.Rc7+-  31.Bf1  Be5  32.g3  The move 30.. e4 gave Black's bishop more freedom, but now the advanced e-pawn becomes a problem.  32...Qd7  33.h4  Bg4  34.Qc2  Bf3  35.Rc8+-   23...h6  24.Rc1  Qd7  25.Be3  Rc8  Opposing White's rook doesn't solve the problem.  26.b5  26...Rxc1  27.Qxc1  Kh7  28.Qc6+-  24.Rc1  Rc7   24...Qf8  25.g4  Bd7  26.Rc7  Bc8  27.Qc1!  The g-pawn is not relevant, as 'passed pawns' is the name of the game.  27...Bxg4  28.h3  Bf5  29.Qc6  Kg8  30.Rxf7  Qxf7  31.Qxd6+-  Black cannot prevent both, the a-pawn being captured or White's d-pawn running.  25.Rxc7  Qxc7  26.Qa4  Bd7  27.b5  Bf8  28.Qc4  Fixed pawns on the 7th rank make simple solutions possible.  28...Qxc4  This is easy now for White, but the position was lost anyways.   28...Qb8  29.Be2+-  followed by 30.Bg4.  29.Bxc4  Bc8  30.Bd8  Kg8  31.Bc7  Kf7  32.Bb8+-  21.Be3  Rc8  One more try. Now Black exchanges a pair of rooks.   21...h5  22.Rac1  Rf7  23.h3  White wants to play g4 in the right moment.  23...Bf6  24.Qd2  Kg7   24...Qd7  25.Rc7!  Qxc7  26.Rxc7  Rxc7  The general rule for assessing the position 'queen versus 2 rooks' is that the queen is superior to the rooks in dynamic positions, while in static positions it is the other way round. This position is dynamic, as there are many weaknesses for the queen to attack. I marked the weak pawns and the king, but you also have to take into account that Black's pieces appear to be loose, as they lack secure outposts.  27.b5  axb5  28.Qb4  Be7  29.g4  hxg4  30.hxg4  Bd7  31.f4+-  Black is unable to coordinate his forces in a way that everything can be protected from the queen. The main problem is the exposed king, of course.  25.g4  hxg4  26.hxg4  Bd7  27.g5  Be7  28.Rc7  This penetration is a bad sign for Black.  28...Rb8  29.f4  Now, the royal castle is under attack.  29...Bf5  30.Qh2  Kg8  31.Bh3!  Rh7  32.Bxf5  Rxh2  33.Be6+  Kg7  34.Kxh2+-  Black is completely paralyzed and White is about to double rooks on the 7th rank.  22.Rac1  Rxc4  23.Rxc4  Rf7  24.h3  Kg8  25.g4!  The bishop is expelled from its perfect position and will now be impeding the rook.  25...Bd7  26.Qc1  h5  Black tries to defend more actively.   26...Bf8  27.Rc7  Bb5  In order to prevent disaster on the 7th rank, Black has to abandon the 8th rank.  28.Rc8  Qd7  29.Bg2  h5  Otherwise Black will be completely tied up.   29...Ba4  30.Bh6  Qe7  31.Bg5  Qd7  32.Be4  Bb5  33.Rb8  Ba4  34.Bh6  Bb5  35.Qc8  This is a simple way of winning the d-pawn.  35...Qxc8  36.Rxc8  Bd7  37.Rb8  Bb5  38.Kg2  As Black cannot do anything, White first improves his position.  38...Bc4  39.f3  Bb5  40.h4  Bc4  41.Kg3  Bb5  42.Rd8  Be2  43.Bxf8  Rxf8  44.Rxd6+-  30.Qc2  hxg4   30...Kg7  31.gxh5  gxh5  32.Rc3+-  with the idea of 33.Bg5 and 34.Rg3.  31.Qxg6+!  Liquidating into an easily won ending.  31...Rg7  32.Rxf8+  Kxf8  33.Bh6  gxh3  34.Bxh3  Qf7  35.Qxg7+  Qxg7+  36.Bxg7+  Kxg7  37.Bc8+-  A different pawn, the same concept. Now, it is not the a-pawn but the b-pawn, which is fixed on the 7th rank.  27.gxh5  gxh5  28.Be2  Bxh3  29.Bxh5  Rf8  30.Bg5  Qd7   30...Bf6?  This would leave the king unprotected.  31.Bh6  Bg7  32.Bxg7  Kxg7  33.Rc7+  Kg8  34.Rc3+-  , winning in the attack.  31.Qe3  Bf5   31...Bf6?  would allow another liquidation into a trivial ending.  32.Bxf6  Rxf6  33.Qg5+  Qg7  34.Qxg7+  Kxg7  35.Rc7+  Kh6  36.Be2+-  32.Qg3  The position is won because White's pieces are more active and Black's king, as well as two of his pawns, is vulnerable. While you might face technical difficulties in a practical game, the engine sees White already more than 4 pawn units ahead. I will give you one very long disaster line, in order to show, how this might play out.  32...Rc8  33.Rh4  Kf8  34.Kg2  Rc7  35.Qf3  Kg8  36.Be8  Exchanging an important defender.  36...Qxe8  37.Qxf5  Qf7  38.Qh7+  Kf8  39.Qd3  Qe8  40.Qf5+  Qf7  41.Qe4  Ke8  42.Rh7  Kf8  43.Rh3  Ke8  44.b5!  This square will be needed for the queen later.  44...axb5  45.Rf3  Qh5  46.Qf5  Qf7  47.Qd3  Qh5  48.Qxb5+  There we go!  48...Rd7  49.Rg3  Qg6  50.Qc4  Bf6  51.Bxf6  Qxf6  52.Qc8+  Ke7  53.Qg8  Mission accomplished. }
*

