17... Nf5 18. Ng3 Qd7 19. Nxf5 Bxf5 20. Nb5
{ This knight is nothing but a plague for the black player. } 20... Bg6 21. Be3
Kh8 { Waiting is all Black can do. } 22. Bd3
{ Now, each of the following choices has its specific downside. } 22... Be8
{ Avoiding the exchange of the important light-squared bishop, but leaving the diagonal b1-h7 to White.   22...e4  23.Bb1+-  Black's last move has given White plenty of new ideas:   Occupying e6 with the knight.  Using the pawn lever f3.  Exerting pressure on the e-pawn with Bd4.    22...Bxd3  23.Qxd3  Kg8  24.Rc1+-  The weak queenside pawns together with Black's bad bishop decide the outcome. White's prime idea is c4-c5, but he is not forced to rush in. He might also consider placing his queen on g6 or to open the kingside with h4. }
23. Nc3
{ The knight would soon be under attack by the bishop. Hence, it moves to a square, from where it can reach both e4 and b5, as well as enable the advance c4-c5 by supporting the d-pawn. }
23... Nh5 24. c5 Nf4 25. Be4
{ Also the bishop makes a 'bella figura' on this square. } 25... Qf7 26. c6
{ This is a remarkable way of dealing with the position. Instead of trying to play against the weak d-pawn or to penetrate on the 7th rank, White closes the queenside, the wing where he is supposed to win the game. As a matter of fact, White indeed is winning the game on the queenside, but indirectly.  With his last move, the knight is allowed to return to b5, where it will exert decisive influence, by binding the rook to the defense of the a-pawn and the queen to the defense of the c-pawn. When the position will finally open up on the kingside, the rook cannot participate and the queen's participation is severely restricted @@StartBracket@@the exchange of queen's wont be possible, for instance@@EndBracket@@. That's an enormous energy drain!   26.c6!  Nh5  27.f3  Qe7  28.Qd3  Black's knight has to make a decision: f6 or f4?  28...Bf7   28...Nf4  29.Qf1  Bf6  30.g3  Nh5  31.Nb5  There it is.  31...Qg7  32.g4  Nf4  33.Bxf4  gxf4   33...exf4  34.Bf5  Be5  This won't be a fortress, as White will gladly sacrifice the exchange against Black's only decent piece. As we are already deep in the analysis, I will present only one exemplary line.  35.Qd3  Rf7  36.Rae2  Re7  37.Rxe5!  Sacrifices like this come much more naturally, when you think in terms of the relative value of the pieces. In that sense, White already has a significant material advantage, so he can sacrifice something and still remain way ahead. If you have problems understanding this, just look at the knight on b5 and the rook on a8. Which piece, do you think, is more valuable?  37...Rxe5  38.Rxe5  dxe5  39.Qe4  Rd8  40.d6  Now you see, that the exchange sacrifice also added a lot of value to the c-pawn, by introducing this break-through option.  40...Rxd6  41.Nxd6  cxd6  42.Qc4+-  If Black's queen blocks the c-pawn @@StartBracket@@a terrible blunder, according to Nimzowitsch@@EndBracket@@, White's queen will invade with deadly consequences.  34.g5!  When the time is ripe, pieces decide the game, not pawns. White's rooks need open files and they will get them.  34...Bxg5   34...hxg5  35.Qh3+  Kg8  36.Qe6+  Kh8  37.Rg2+-  followed by h4, Kh1 and Reg1.  35.Qh3  Rf7  36.Rg2  Qf6  37.Kh1  Rg7  38.Reg1  Thanks to the knight on b5, the rook g7 is overloaded.  38...Kg8  39.Qe6+!  The only thing White has to do is, to remove the defenders of the vulnerable c-pawn.  39...Qxe6  40.dxe6  Kh8  41.h4  Bf6  42.Rxg7  Bxg7  43.Nxc7+-  29.g3  Nf6  30.Rf2  Bg8  31.Kg2  White steadily improves his pieces. The main idea is to open the position with h4 in a suitable moment.  31...Bf7  32.Qd2  Nxe4  Black cannot stay idle and let White realize his plan. With this move he wants to release some pressure by exchanging a pair of rooks.   32...Bg8  33.Rh1+-  followed by h4.  33.fxe4  Bg6  This is the second idea linked to 32...Nxe4. White's e-pawn is now a target and will bind a defender.  34.Ref1  Rxf2+  35.Rxf2  Obviously, Black's remaining rook is not allowed to play in the f-file, as it is occupied with babysitting.  35...Bf6  36.Kg1  In some lines, Black might be allowed to grab the e-pawn.  36...Kg7  37.Qe2  Qe8  38.Nb5  Bd8  39.h4  Kg8   39...Bxe4  40.Bxg5  Qg6  41.Nxc7!  The knight is omnipresent.  41...Bxc7  42.Rf6+-  40.hxg5  h5  Why are we still around after move 40? Isn't this an opening course? It is, but in order to evaluate 26.c6!, we have to find out whether Black can establish a fortress or not.  41.Qf3  Qf7  42.Qh1  Qg7  43.Nc3  It's not beneath the knight to do a defensive job for a change and allow the queen to become active. It's also worth mentioning that the move 26.c6! took the square d7 away from Black's pieces.  43...Be7  44.Qh3  Bd8  45.g4  h4   45...hxg4?!  allows White's queen to occupy a dominant location on g4, amongst others liberating the knight from its defensive duties.  46.Qxg4  Qe7  47.Nb5  Qg7  48.Rh2  Be8  49.Rh6  Bg6  50.Qe6+  Bf7  51.Qf5  Be8  52.g6+-  46.Qxh4  Be7  47.Qh6  Bd8  48.Kf1!  Never forget to activate your king in the endgame!  48...Be7  49.Ke2  Bd8  50.Kd3  Now, the knight is free to go.  50...Rb8  51.Nb5  Ra8  52.Rf1  Zugzwang!  52...Bf7   52...Rc8  53.Nxa7  Ra8  54.Bxb6  cxb6  55.Nb5  Rxa6  56.Nxd6+-  , when White's connected passed pawns decide the game.  53.g6!  That pawn was restricting the bishop on e3.  53...Bxg6  54.Qh3  Bf7  55.Bh6  Qh7   55...Qg6  56.Qh5+-  White's rook is poised to invade the 8th rank.  56.Qf3  Qg6  57.Qf5+-  57 moves might be a record for a Chessable opening course! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 9.b4 Nh5 10.Re1 f5 11.a4  − 11th Moves"]
[Black "11.a4 Nf6 12.a5 c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... f5 11. a4 Nf6 12. a5 c6
{ Instead of relieving or maintaining the tension, Black increases it even further. The idea is to prevent White from playing c4-c5 or, more aggressively, to win the d-pawn, which is already undermined. This all sounds good in theory, but can be considered refuted thanks to a very direct and brutal approach. }
13. dxc6
{ This is more ambitious than the quieter  13.Nd2  , which is good enough for a clear advantage. }
13... bxc6
{ This allows White to start the invasion by opening up the position with } 14.
c5 d5 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Qb3 { Less strong is  16.Nxe5  Ne4  . } 16... e4
{ 16...Ne4  is losing by force:  17.Nxd5!  Nxd5  18.Bc4  Be6  19.Rd1  Nef6  20.Ng5+-  . }
17. Nd4 a6 18. Rd1
{ All of White's pieces are directed to the queenside, where they will support the passed pawns. }
*

