10... f5 11. a4 Nf6 12. a5 c6
{ Instead of relieving or maintaining the tension, Black increases it even further. The idea is to prevent White from playing c4-c5 or, more aggressively, to win the d-pawn, which is already undermined. This all sounds good in theory, but can be considered refuted thanks to a very direct and brutal approach. }
13. dxc6
{ This is more ambitious than the quieter  13.Nd2  , which is good enough for a clear advantage. }
13... Nxc6 14. Bg5
{ This evaluation is not yet visible to the naked eye. Nevertheless, it already exists as underlying information, waiting to be brought to light by analytical effort. Black suffers from a bad pawn structure and a vulnerable king. In order to score the full point, White has to play in dynamic fashion and mustn't shy away from temporarily sacrificing material. }
14... Be6 15. a6 b6 16. Qa4 Rc8 17. Rad1
{ The pressure against d6 is annoying for Black. } 17... h6
{ 17...Qd7  18.exf5  gxf5   18...Bxf5?  19.Nb5+-  19.c5  bxc5  20.bxc5  Nd4  21.Nxd4  exd4  22.Bb5!  The non-sacrifice 22.Rxd4 is inferior and only yields a clear advantage.  22...Qf7  23.Rxe6!  Qxe6  24.Bxf6  Qxf6  25.Nd5  Qe5  26.f4  Qe6  27.c6+-  The passed pawn is very dangerous. }
18. exf5 gxf5 19. Bh4 e4 20. Nb5
{ Play has a forced character, now.  20.c5!  is also possible, as well as  20.Bf1  for the faint of heart. }
20... exf3 21. Bxf3 Bxc4 22. Nxd6 b5 23. Qc2 Nxb4 24. Qxf5 Bb3
{ 24...Nd3  25.Rxd3  Bxd3  26.Qxd3  The combination of a monster knight, a strong bishop pair and a vulnerable black king makes this an easy win. }
25. Qb1 Bxd1 26. Rxd1 Qe7
{ 26...Nc6  27.Bd5+!  Creating a potential discovered check.  27...Kh8  28.Bxc6+- }
27. Qxb4 Rcd8 28. Bc6 Kh8 29. Bxb5
{ White is already better by nominal standards alone. } *

