exf5
{ This is a better practical approach than  14.Bd2  , which was played in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Gonzaga Grego, L @@StartBracket@@2402@@EndBracket@@-Zugrav, W @@StartBracket@@2577@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017. The game continued  14...h6  15.Ne6  Bxe6  16.dxe6  fxe4  , when things can become very complicated, with Black targeting the f-pawn. }
14... Nxf5
{ This is more solid than  14...gxf5  , but at the same time pretty lame. Black's structure simply lack's dynamic potential. }
15. Bd3 b6 16. Bd2 Ra8
{ 16...h6  would allow White to liquidate into a better ending.  17.Ne6  Bxe6  18.dxe6  Qe7  19.Bxf5  gxf5  20.Nd5  Nxd5  21.Bxa5  Nf4  22.Bc3  Nxe6  23.a5± }
17. Ra3 Nd4 18. Nb5 Nxb5 19. cxb5
{ is the losing structure, we already met above. } 19... Kh8 20. Bc2
{ Clearing the 3rd rank for the rook. } 20... Qe7 { 20...Nxd5  21.Be4+- } 21.
Rg3
{ Now that the rook has moved along the third rank, the bishop can be placed on b3, which is its ideal square. }
21... Bd7 22. Qc1 { Queen's love to be effective from a secure location. }
22... Rac8 23. Bb3
{ From here, the bishop protects the two weak pawns and facilitates a future Ne6. Additionally, it doesn't obstruct the queen in the c-file and can be switched to c2, in case Black weakens his structure with h6. }
23... Nh5 24. Rc3 Bh6 25. Re4 Nf6 { 25...Rf5  26.h4+- } 26. Rb4
{ Every white piece is placed highly effectively. I like, how the rooks are making good use of the ranks in this position. }
