18... Kh7 19. Rh3
{ White focuses on the barely protected black king. The threat is Bxh6 followed by Qd2, attacking both, bishop and rook. }
19... b6 { Defending against this threat. } 20. Be3
{ Discouraging a potential ...c7-c6, by casting an eye on the b-pawn. } 20...
Ra8 { Preparing ...c6, as with the rook on a5, Bxb6 would be annoying. } 21.
Bd3
{ Now, the entire royal protection shield is targeted. By pinning the f-pawn, Qd2 has become a dangerous threat. Black has to act immediately. }
21... c6 22. Qd2 cxb5
{ 22...Nfg8  23.Nxd6  Qxe6  24.Bc2  Rad8  25.c5  is obviously lost, as White is better in all areas: pawn structure, piece activity and king safety. }
23. Bxh6 Qxe6
{ 23...Nfg8  loses by force:  24.Bg5+  Kg6  25.Rg3  Kh7  26.Bxe7  Nxe7  27.Qg5  Rg8  28.Rh3++- }
24. Qg5 Ng6 25. Bxg7+ Kxg7 26. Bxf5 Qf7 27. Qh6+ Kg8 28. Be6
{ A lovely finish... } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 9.b4 Nh5 10.Re1 f5 11.a4 a5"]
[Black "11.a4 a5 12.bxa5 Rxa5 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... f5 11. a4 a5
{ We have already encountered this logical idea of weakening White's control of the square c5. An important idea to keep in mind in this structure. }
12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. Ng5 { 13.exf5  is an equivalent alternative. } 13... Nf6 14.
exf5
{ This is a better practical approach than  14.Bd2  , which was played in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Gonzaga Grego, L @@StartBracket@@2402@@EndBracket@@-Zugrav, W @@StartBracket@@2577@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017. The game continued  14...h6  15.Ne6  Bxe6  16.dxe6  fxe4  , when things can become very complicated, with Black targeting the f-pawn. }
14... gxf5
{ I made this move the main line, not for its quality, but for its complexity. In this structure, play generally becomes rather dynamic, as White will jump with his knight to e6 in most cases. I know, some players would fear to lose the pawn, that will land on e6 after the bishop takes the knight. Those players prefer the kind of static battle, which arises when a piece recaptures on f. There, they can try to slowly squeeze the opponent in a controlled manner. That's also my general preference, but we have to acknowledge that sometimes such options don't exist.   Even if the general game plan is static and solid, there are always islands of chaos, which can appear as the result of our opponent's choice. In that case, we have to be objective and rise to the occasion. Our ideal should be the universal player, who always acts according to the demands of the position. The good news is, that this position is objectively very promising for White, actually close to winning. Even if you play incorrectly, you might end up having the advantage. And don't forget, that your opponent is a fallible human and not a machine. }
15. Nb5
{ This is a Prokofiev-moment. The knights are knocking at the gates of Black's fortress and herald White's readiness for the fight. From Black's perspective, the situation looks gloomy and his sentiment could be fittingly represented by the great Russian's piece 'Dance of the knights'. }
15... h6
{ Black forces a change of the structure, in order to reduce White's options and to clarify the situation for himself. Let's also have a look at the alternatives. }
16. Ne6 Bxe6 17. dxe6
{ That's a good example of a binary situation, as the pawn is either weak or strong. In the context of this repertoire @@StartBracket@@opposed to less convincing lines with this structure, e.g. after 9.Nd2@@EndBracket@@, it will be strong every single time, though. That's why I call it the master pawn. It even has a personal bodyguard, standing on b5, which is tying the black queen to the defense of the pawn c7. If Black wants to get rid of the master pawn, the price he has to pay will be high. }
17... Kh8
{ The king withdraws from the a2-g8 diagonal, which could become dangerous in case of c4-c5 by White or ...d6-d5 by Black. }
18. Ra3 d5
{ 18...Ne4  allows the bishop to connect with the master pawn.  19.Bh5+-  . }
19. cxd5 Nfxd5
{ 19...Nexd5  leaves Black weak on the long diagonal.  20.Bb2  e4  21.Qd2!  Ra8  22.Rh3  22...Kh7  23.Rd1!  White threatens 24.Qg5, when 24...Ne7 is impossible.  23...Qe7  24.Nd4  Ne8  25.Rh5!  Nd6  26.Nxf5  Nxf5  27.Qxd5+-  . }
20. Bc4 c6 21. Bxd5 Nxd5 22. Rh3 Kh7
{ 22...Qf6  would invite the knight for a little dance.  23.Nd6  Qxe6  24.Nc4  Raa8  25.Nxe5+- }
23. Ba3 Nf4 { 23...Re8  24.Nd6  Rxe6  25.Nxb7+- } 24. e7 Qxd1 25. exf8=N+
{ I think, every good opening course should contain at least one position, where an underpromotion is necessary ;-@@EndBracket@@ }
25... Bxf8 26. Rxd1 Nxh3+ 27. gxh3 cxb5 28. Bxf8
{ As the dust settles White has excellent winning chances. } *

