18. Ra3 Ra6
{ Black intends to take care of the e-pawn by ...d5, followed by ...Rxe6. } 19.
Nc3 { Plan prevented. Now, c5 is a threat. } 19... Ra5 20. Bd2
{ Targeting the rook and thus preparing Nd5. } 20... b6
{ 20...Ra8  21.a5!  White is playing on the entire board and doesn't neglect the queenside. Now the b-pawn is kind of restricted, as ...b7-b6 could be answered by a5-a6. The direct idea is to play Nd5. If Black should happen to take twice on d5, White will answer with Bxh6, destroying Black's last protection pawn. }
21. g4
{ White already has the active pieces. All he needs is a breach in Black's position. }
21... fxg4 22. Ne4 Nxe4 { 22...Ra7  23.Bxg4+- } 23. Bd3 Kh8 24. Bxe4 Rc5 25.
Qxg4 Rxc4 26. Qh3 Ng8 27. Rg3 Qf6 28. Kh1
{ Virtually all of White's forces are included in the final battle. } 28...
Qxf2 29. Rxg7 Kxg7 30. Rg1+ *

