10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... f5 11. a4 a5 12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. Ng5 Nf4 14. Bf1 h6
{ Now, the knight is forced to retreat to a modest location and cannot be installed on e4, as after  14...Ra8  . }
15. Nf3 g5
{ This advance is double-edged, as it weakens the light squares.   15...fxe4  16.Nxe4  b6  17.Ra3±  White will chase Black's knight away with h3, Nh2 and g3, when ....Nxh3+ / Bxh3 Bxh3 / g4 would lose a piece. The next step would be to push the a-pawn. }
16. Nd2 c5
{ Black managed to stabilize the queenside for the time being, but he is now sitting on two long-term weaknesses. This is more than he can bear, as his kingside is weak, as well. White will win by combining activities on both wings. Black has to seek active piece play instead. }
17. Nb5 Ra6 18. g3
{ It's logical to drive Black's knight to the joyless square g6 as soon as possible, exploiting the move ...g5 on move fifteen. In the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Werle, J @@StartBracket@@2541@@EndBracket@@-Jones, G @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ Caleta 2019, White played  18.Ra3  , instead. }
18... Nfg6 19. exf5 Nxf5
{ 19...Bxf5?!  would leave both knights miserable.  20.Ra3+-  White will follow-up with Bg2, Ne4, Bd2 and a5. }
20. Qh5
{ Obviously, this option is a consequence of Black's ambitious pawn advance on move 15. }
20... Nge7 21. Ne4
{ White combines the pressure against the d-pawn with his control of the light squares . Black's queen cannot easily oppose the white queen, as it is occupied with guarding the points d6 and c7. The knight on b5 is really doing a formidable job. White's long-term plan is to improve his pieces and then pry open the kingside with h2-h4. }
21... Bd7 22. Bd2 Be8 23. Qg4 Bg6
{ Black is unable to get rid of the queen.   23...Bd7  24.Bh3+-  threatening Nbxd6. }
24. a5 { Dismissing the rook from its service and preparing Rab1. } 24... Qc8
{ 24...Nd4  Opening up the position doesn't only help the black pieces.  25.Nxd4  exd4  26.Qe6+  Bf7  27.Qh3  Ng6   27...Bg6  28.Rab1+-  28.f4+- }
25. Qh3
{ Moving the queen to a protected square, thus parrying the threat of  25...Nd4  . }
25... Qd7
{ 25...g4  26.Qg2  Nd4  If Black doesn't continue actively, White will use the pawn g4 as a hook.   26...Qd7  27.h3  h5  28.Qh1+-  27.Nxd4  exd4  28.Nxd6  Rxd6  29.Rxe7  Bf6  30.Re6!  White is winning, according to my analysis. }
26. Be2 Nc8 27. Bh5 Bxh5
{ 27...Bh7  28.Bg4+-  White will improve his rooks by Reb1, Ra3-b3 or Ra3-f3. }
28. Qxh5 Qf7
{ White was already threatening h4. If I want to prove my evaluation from move 21, I have to demonstrate how White can win the ending. }
29. Qxf7+ Rxf7 30. Reb1
{ Black might be able to cope with his two weak pawns, but not with the additional threat that White will open the kingside with f2-f4 or h2-h4 at a suitable moment.   30.Reb1  Nd4  31.Kg2  Nf3  32.Be3  Kh7  33.h3  Kg6  34.Nc7  Rxc7  35.Kxf3  Bf8  36.Ke2  Be7   36...b6  Getting rid of the weak b-pawn is a principal choice of Black, we have to examine.  37.axb6  Rxa1  38.Rxa1  Nxb6  39.Kd3  Rf7  40.Ra6  That's the problem with this strategy. White's rook is given too much freedom.  40...Rb7  41.Bd2  The king has to leave the 6th rank.  41...Kh7  42.Ba5  Na4   42...Nc8  43.Ra8+-  43.Nxd6  Nb2+  44.Ke4  Bxd6  45.Rxd6  Nxc4  46.Ra6  The passed d-pawn in combination with White's active king is decisive.  37.Kd3  Bf8  38.Rb5  Rf7  39.Bd2  White has two principal winning plans: pushing the h-pawn or pushing the f-pawn. I will show both of them.  39...Na7   39...Ra8  40.Rab1  Rb8  41.Rg1!  An elegant move, preparing the f4-break.  41...Kg7   41...Kh7  42.Bxg5+-   41...b6  42.f4+-   41...Rf3+  42.Ke2  Ra3  43.Rgb1+-  42.f4+-  40.Rb2  Nc8  41.Rab1  b6   41...Ra7  42.Ke2  Re7  43.Rb3  Rf7  44.f3  Rc7  45.h4+-  42.Rb5  Rb7  43.f3  Be7  As Black is tied up on the queenside, it's time for the h4-break.  44.h4!  gxh4   44...Bd8  45.hxg5  hxg5  46.Rh1  Bf6   46...Rh7  47.Rxh7  Kxh7  48.axb6+-  47.Nxf6  Kxf6  48.Rh8  Rc7  49.Rb1+-  45.gxh4  Bxh4  46.Rh1  Bg5  47.Bxg5  hxg5  48.Rh8  Rc7   48...Ne7  49.Nxd6  Rd7  50.axb6+-  49.Rg8+  Kf7  50.Rxc8+-  If you look closely enough, you might see the horse on e4 grinning with pleasure. }
*

