10... f5 11. a4 a5 12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. Ng5 Nf4 14. Bf1 b6 15. Nb5
{ 15.Ra3  was also very good for White in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Gonzaga Grego, L @@StartBracket@@2403@@EndBracket@@-Genga, S @@StartBracket@@2423@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018. }
15... h6 16. Nf3 fxe4 17. Rxe4 Bf5
{ At first sight, it might appear that Black could exploit the lack of vigilance by White's knight with regard to the e4-square. As it turns out the f5-square is rarely a good place for the bishop. }
18. Re1
{ As the bishop interrupted the connection between the rook and the knight on f4, Black now has to cope with the threat of Bxf4 followed by Nfd4. }
18... Bg4
{ Not often does it occur, that Black has a threat in the Bayonet. In this case, even two at once. }
19. Ra3
{ Thanks to one of the Bayonet's super moves we are able to prevent both threats with a single move. }
19... Ra8 20. h3 { The bishop's glory days are finally over. } 20... Bd7 21.
Nh2
{ This is stronger than  21.Nd2  , which was played in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Hernandez, A @@StartBracket@@2389@@EndBracket@@-Puzone, M @@StartBracket@@2404@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017. There, Black missed the opportunity to remove the annoying knight with  21...Bxb5!  , as  22.cxb5  is not possible due to the hanging d-pawn. After  22.axb5  Rxa3  23.Bxa3  Qe8  24.Ne4  Qf7  25.Bc1  Nh5  26.Bd3  Nf6  27.Rf1  Nf5  28.Bd2  Ra8  Black has some counterplay in the a-file.   After our novelty 21.Nh2!, White is ready to chase Black's knight away with g3 or Ng4, followed by g3.  If we could move again, the strongest continuation would actually be 22.Rf3 with the idea to eliminate the important rook on f8. It would then be awkward for Black, not to be able to recapture with the queen, due to his weak c-pawn. Anyways, White would follow up with Ng4, asking Black what to do with the pawn h6. }
21... Qc8 22. Ng4
{ That's generally a good square for the knight, as it influences the important points f6 and h6. The latter is currently under attack. Obviously, it also does a good job shielding the h-pawn, which is a useful mechanism to expel the knight on f4. }
22... Kh7 23. g3 Nh5 24. Bg2 Nf6 25. Nxf6+ Bxf6 26. Bd2
{ White will follow up with a4-a5, setting his sight on Black's weak c-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 9.b4 Nh5 10.Re1 f5 11.a4 a5"]
[Black "11.a4 a5 12.bxa5 Rxa5 #28"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... f5 11. a4 a5 12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. Ng5 Nf4 14. Bf1 Ra8 15. exf5 Nxf5 16. Nge4
{ Now Black has to be careful, because his knights moved into a dangerous tactical constellation. The motif g3 Nh5 / g4 is hanging in the air. }
16... Nd4 17. Nb5
{ You should remember this method to deal with a knight on d4. } 17... Nxb5
{ 17...Qh4  This is best, but also not satisfactory.  18.Nxd4   18.Nxc7??  Bg4  19.Qd2  Nh3+  -+  18...exd4  19.Ra3±  White will target the pawn d4 by Bb2. }
18. cxb5
{ This structure is basically lost for Black, as the c-pawn is exposed to White's heavy pieces. The immediate threat is a5, followed by a6 at some stage. }
18... b6 19. Ra3 Qe7 20. g3
{ There hardly is a position, where this knight cannot be expelled one way or the other. }
20... Nh5 21. Bg2 Bf5 22. Ng5 Nf6 23. h3 Bh6
{ That is not much of a plan, but the situation was hopeless, anyways. } 24.
Rc3 Bg7 25. g4 Bc8
{ If everything is lost, such moves have the advantage of already setting up the starting position for a new game. }
26. f4 h6 27. fxe5
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Gonzaga Grego, L @@StartBracket@@2403@@EndBracket@@-Esquivel Leon, J @@StartBracket@@2174@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018. Black didn't resign too early:  27...Nxg4  28.hxg4  hxg5  29.Rce3!  Bxe5  30.Rxe5  dxe5  31.d6+-  . }
*

