10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... f5 11. a4 a5 12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. Ng5 Nf4 14. Bf1 Ra8 15. exf5 Nxf5 16. Nge4
{ Now Black has to be careful, because his knights moved into a dangerous tactical constellation. The motive g3 Nh5 / g4 is hanging in the air. }
16... b6 17. Nb5
{ As the d4-square is covered, g3 has become a threat.   17.g3!?  Nh5  18.g4?  Nd4  would be premature. }
17... Nh6 { The knight had to retreat. } 18. a5
{ Dynamic play. Of course, it is easier to perform it in an email game than over the board. The conservative  18.Bd2  , however, is also very good for White. }
18... bxa5 19. c5 dxc5
{ 19...Nf7  20.c6+-  This is even stronger than 20.Ba3. White is further restricting his opponent and marks the pawn c7 as a target. It can be attacked by a rook from the side, and by a bishop and queen from a5 and b8. }
20. d6 c6 { 20...cxd6?  21.Bxf4  exf4  22.Qd5++- } 21. Nc7 Rb8 22. Nxc5
{ White is winning, due to his active pieces and dominating passed pawn. } *

