11. Nd2
{ If White plays the c4-c5 advance too early, Black will get a playable position by applying pressure on White's central pawns:  11.c5?  f5  12.Nd2  Nf6  13.a4  Kh7  14.Bc4  The d5-pawn needed protection. Now, Black switches to his standard attacking plan with  14...f4  , as White's knight cannot directly access  the square c4. I don't say that this position is fantastic for Black, but at least he has something to play for. }
11... Nf4
{ As the knight on d2 blocks the bishop, this plunge is less risky, now. No Bxf4 to be feared. }
12. Bf1 c6 13. Nb3 { Preventing ...a7-a5. } 13... cxd5 14. exd5
{ This is more ambitious than  14.cxd5  , which also promises a large advantage. }
14... Nh5
{ 14...f5?  15.Bxf4  exf4  16.Rc1+-  intending c5 and then Nb5 on the following move. White is not only having a de facto extra pawn, but a very vivid one. }
15. f3
{ 15.c5  was played in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@74@@EndBracket@@ Chuchelov, V @@StartBracket@@2490@@EndBracket@@-Iordachescu, V @@StartBracket@@2460@@EndBracket@@ Dresden 1996 and is also not bad. But it is more sophisticated to improve the position  first with moves such as Be3 and a4-a5, as Black has no active ideas at his disposal. The text move provides the bishop with a refuge on f2. }
15... Nf4
{ 15...Nf6  16.Be3  b6  17.a4  Re8  18.a5  Rb8  19.b5  Nf5  20.Bf2  h5  21.Bd3+-  White has many ideas, such as invading on the 7th rank and attacking Black's b-pawn. The most potent one, however, is the installation of a knight on c6. }
16. Be3 g5 17. Bf2 h5 18. Rc1 g4 { Black is trying his best. } 19. g3 Nh3+ 20.
Bxh3 gxh3 { A mate on g2 is nothing but a faint hope. } 21. c5
{ The majority begins to march. } 21... dxc5 { 21...Nf5  22.Ne4+- } 22. bxc5
Bf5 23. Qd2 Qd7 24. d6 Nc6 25. Nd5
{ White's spatial dominance makes a survival for Black very unlikely. } *

