17... Nf6 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 19. Ne4 Qd8 20. Rc1 Nf5 21. h3
{ There is no need to remove the bishop, as it happened in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Hrubaru, M @@StartBracket@@2074@@EndBracket@@-Figura, A @@StartBracket@@2087@@EndBracket@@ LSS email 2009 where White played  21.Bd2?  . On the contrary, we wouldn't mind to force this exchange, as the knight is Black's most active piece and also protects the d-pawn. }
21... Bd7 22. g4 Nxe3 23. Rxe3
{ Black owns the square f4, but he has no use for it. } 23... Be8 24. cxd6 cxd6
25. Rec3
{ The invasion cannot be prevented anymore. I will present some exemplary lines. }
25... Bf6 26. Rc7 Rf7 27. Rxf7 Bxf7 28. Qd2 Bg7
{ 28...Kg7  29.Nxf6  Qxf6  30.Rc7+- } 29. Rc3 Rb8 30. Qc2 Kh8 31. b5 Bxd5
{ 31...Be8  Let's see what happens, if Black pursues a sit-and-wait-strategy.  32.a4  Bf7  33.Bf3  Ra8  34.Kg2  Rb8  35.Qc1  Ra8  36.g5!  The participation of White's bishop will be decisive.  36...h5  37.h4  Rb8  38.Qc2  Ra8  39.Kg1  Rb8  40.Rc7  Qf8   40...Bxd5  41.Nf6  Bxf3  42.Qxg6+-  41.Bg2  Kg8  42.Bh3  42...Kh8  43.Nf6  Bxf6  44.gxf6  Qg8  45.Be6  Rf8  46.Qc1+- }
32. Rd3 Bg8 33. Nxd6 Qa5 34. Rd2
{ White's active pieces are poised to attack Black's kingside.   34.Rd2  Qa3  35.Rd1   35.Qxg6??  Qc1+  35...Qxa2   35...Kh7  36.Be4  Qxh3  37.Bxg6+  Kh8  38.Qe4+-  36.Qxg6  Qe6  37.Qd3  Qb3  38.Qf1  The queen is still needed for the attack.  38...b6?!  39.Nf5  Black is unable to repulse the attack. }
