{ This move looks natural, but White has ways and means to make progress. } 21.
h3 a6 22. a4 Rf7 23. Nd2 Kh7 24. Nb3 { Exchanging Black's only active piece. }
24... Qf6 25. Rc4 Nxb3 26. Qxb3
{ White's space advantage on the queenside is already decisive. } 26... Raf8
{ 26...h5  Exchanging the bad bishop is generally a good idea, but here it doesn't help anymore.  27.a5  Bh6  28.Bxh6  Kxh6  29.Qe3+  Kg7  30.c6  bxc6  31.Rxc6+-  That's one weakness too much for Black. }
27. b5 axb5 28. axb5 h5
{ 28...dxc5  29.Bxc5  Rd8  30.g4  Bd7  31.Be3+-  Black suffers from three major weaknesses. }
29. g4 Bd7 30. g5 { Encaging the dark-squared bishop. } 30... Qd8 31. cxd6 cxd6
32. b6
{ The invasion will most probably take place on the square c7.   32.b6  Bf5  33.h4  Re8  34.Rec1  Ree7  35.Qa3  Bh8  36.Qa7  Bg7  37.Bf1!  Qe8  38.Rc7  Rxc7  39.bxc7  Bc8  40.Qa3  Qd7  41.Qb4  White will further tie Black down with Qe4 and Bd3. Depending on the course of the game, White's rook might appear on a8, at some point. }
