14... fxe4 15. Ng5
{ 15.Nxe4?  Rxa2  16.Nfg5  Nf6  was only slightly better for White in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Shadrin, A @@StartBracket@@2123@@EndBracket@@-Seia, J @@StartBracket@@2200@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2006. }
15... Nf5 16. Ncxe4 { 16.g4??  loses to  16...e3  . } 16... Nf6 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6
{ As both, knight and a-pawn are under attack, the game takes a dynamic turn.   17...Qxf6  18.Ne4  Qf7  19.a4  Nd4  20.Bc4±  As usual, White's knight is exerting strong pressure on Black's d-pawn. }
18. Ne6 Bxe6 19. dxe6 Qe7 20. Bc4 Nd4
{ 20...Rc8  21.Qd2  Rac5  22.Bd5  Bg5  Black has to get rid of the bishop on d5.  23.Qxg5  Qxg5  24.Bxg5  Rxd5  25.Rxb7  Re8  26.Reb1  Ng7  27.Ra7  Nxe6  28.Bh6±  The outside passed pawn and Black's vulnerable king give White a clear advantage. }
21. Be3 d5
{ 21...Rc8  22.Qd2  Rac5  23.Bd3  Nc2  24.Bxc2  Rxc2  25.Qd5  Re8  26.a4  Qxe6  27.Qxb7±  Again, White has practical winning chances by pushing his passer. }
22. Bxd4 exd4
{ 22...dxc4?  23.Bc3  Rd8  24.Bxa5  Rxd1  25.Rexd1  Qxe6  26.Rxb7+-  Black's king is lethally exposed. }
23. Bb3 Rd8 24. g3 Rd6 25. Qe2
{ White's passed pawn and better king are problematic for Black. } *

