10... a5 11. bxa5 f5
{ Black immediately takes actions on the kingside, banking on the fact that White cannot protect his extra pawn. While this is true, it gives him the opportunity to play in dynamic fashion. }
12. c5
{ This move is like a Trojan Horse, offering Black something he rather wouldn't like to have: 'negative flexibility'. He has a lot of options, but most of them are bad. This concept is important when it comes to the construction of your opening repertoire.   Let's say, you play the French Defense. You give White the choice between the two good moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  and  3.Nd2  , which are both complementary in terms of style, and the decent continuation  3.e5  . Then there is also the drawish option  3.exd5  , which would annoy me very much as Black. Actually, I only see positive flexibility for White in the French.  Things look different, however, when it comes to the Sicilian Defense. Look at all these feeble sidelines, which perform below 50%. White definitely has a lot of negative flexibility in the Sicilian, which makes it a very strong metagame weapon for Black. After digressing a bit, let's quickly return to the bad choices Black can make in this position. }
12... fxe4
{ This will lead to an inferior version of the main line - same structure, better piece placement for White. }
13. Nxe4 Rxa5 14. Bd2 Ra8 15. Qb3
{ That's a really good square for the queen. It is effective along the a2-g8 diagonal and exerts pressure on the b-pawn. Later it may seek contact with Black's d-pawn or move to b6 @@StartBracket@@after cxd6 cxd6@@EndBracket@@, helping the rook to penetrate on c7. }
15... Nf4 16. Bc4 Nf5 17. Rac1
{ All of White's pieces are on active squares. By removing the rook from the long diagonal, White threatens to take on f4 and invade with his knight on e6. }
17... h6 { 17...Kh8?  18.Bxf4  exf4  19.cxd6  cxd6  20.Neg5+- } 18. a4 g5
{ There is nothing Black can do, but become active on the kingside. White doesn't have to be afraid, though, as his king is surrounded by defenders. }
19. h3 { ...g4 had to be prevented. } 19... Qe8 20. a5 Qg6 21. Bxf4 exf4 22.
cxd6 Nxd6 23. Nxd6 Qxd6
{ 23...cxd6  24.Re6!   24.Bd3  also works.  24...Bxe6  25.dxe6  25...Kh8  26.e7  Rfe8  27.Bf7  Qe4  28.Bxe8  Rxe8  29.Re1  Qg6  30.Qxb7+- }
24. Re6 Bxe6
{ 24...Qc5  25.Re7!  Kh8  26.Ne5!  White wins attacking, e.g.  26...Bf5  27.Nf7+  Kh7  28.Qd3!  Bxd3  29.Bxd3+  Kg8  30.Nxh6+  Bxh6  31.Rxc5+-  . }
25. dxe6 Kh8 26. Rd1 Qc5 27. Rd5 Qc6 28. e7 Rfe8 29. Ne5 Bxe5 30. Rxe5
{ The emperor wears no clothes! } *

