{ 15...Nf6?  That mistake illustrates the queen's power in a straight-forward way.  16.cxd6  cxd6  17.Nxd6!  Qxd6  18.Bb4+-  . }
16. Bg5
{ 16.g4?  doesn't work because of  16...Nf6  17.Nxf6  Bxf6  18.gxf5  e4  . }
16... Nf6 17. a4
{ By delaying the capture on d6, White prevents Qa5. Apart from that, there are four ideas linked to this advance, which may be realized according to the circumstances:   1@@EndBracket@@ The pawn is supposed to be pushed to a5 at some stage, enabling the queen to move to b6.  2@@EndBracket@@ In some lines, White wants to play Qb4 and Rac1. No hanging pawn on a2 anymore.   3@@EndBracket@@ The bishop receives a secure outpost on b5.  4@@EndBracket@@ If the b7 pawn falls, a far advanced a-pawn would be an immediate danger for Black. }
17... Kh8 18. Bf1 h6
{ 18...dxc5  19.Nxc5  Qxd5  20.Bxf6  Qxc5  21.Bxe5  Bxe5  22.Nxe5+-  Black's miserable king safety is a gigantic energy leak. }
19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. cxd6 cxd6 { 20...Nxd6  21.Nxf6  Qxf6  22.Qe3+- } 21. Qb4
{ Binding Black's forces to the defense of the d-pawn and preparing a5. } 21...
Be7
{ 21...Qa5  This doesn't reduce the pressure, as the queen was an important defender of weak spots such as d6 and c7,  22.Qxa5  Rxa5  23.Bb5+-  .  Dominating rook and bishop and preparing Nfd2-c4. }
22. a5 Rf7 23. Ra3 Kg8 24. h3
{ This provides the king with air and gives more power to a potential g2-g4. Whenever you have the position under control, don't forget to do these small improvements. }
24... Ng7 25. Nfd2 { It's a good time for this, as Nd4 is no longer possible. }
25... Bf5 26. Nc4 h5 27. Nb6
{ White has to watch out for his sore spot:  27.Qxb7?  Bxe4  28.Rxe4  Bh4  , attacking queen and f-pawn. }
27... Rb8 28. Rb1 Qf8 29. Rab3
{ White may improve his pieces as follows: Bd3, Qe1 and Nc4, exposing the weaknesses on b7 and d6. The lever a5-a6 is always an option. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 9.b4 Nh5 10.Re1 a5"]
[Black "11.bxa5 f5 12.c5 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... a5 11. bxa5 f5
{ Black immediately takes actions on the kingside, banking on the fact that White cannot protect his extra pawn. While this is true, it gives him the opportunity to play in dynamic fashion. }
12. c5
{ This move is like a Trojan Horse, offering Black something he rather wouldn't like to have: 'negative flexibility'. He has a lot of options, but most of them are bad. This concept is important when it comes to the construction of your opening repertoire.   Let's say, you play the French Defense. You give White the choice between the two good moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  and  3.Nd2  , which are both complementary in terms of style, and the decent continuation  3.e5  . Then there is also the drawish option  3.exd5  , which would annoy me very much as Black. Actually, I only see positive flexibility for White in the French.  Things look different, however, when it comes to the Sicilian Defense. Look at all these feeble sidelines, which perform below 50%. White definitely has a lot of negative flexibility in the Sicilian, which makes it a very strong metagame weapon for Black. After digressing a bit, let's quickly return to the bad choices Black can make in this position. }
12... Nf6 13. a6 bxa6
{ The 6th rank is an El Dorado for White, with two potentially weak pawns and three potentially weak squares. }
14. Nd2 fxe4 15. Ncxe4 Nxe4 { 15...Nexd5?  16.cxd6  cxd6  17.Ba3+- } 16. Nxe4
Bf5 17. f3 dxc5
{ Black is more or less forced to isolate his pawns, in order to activate his problem knight and to get rid of his weak d-pawn. }
18. Bc4 Kh8 19. Be3 Bxe4 20. fxe4 Nc8 21. Bxc5 Nd6 22. Rc1 *

