17. exf5
{ This is better than  17.Ng5  , which would have allowed Black to diminish White's advantage by  17...f4  in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Romizin, N @@StartBracket@@2223@@EndBracket@@-Kozlov, V @@StartBracket@@2345@@EndBracket@@ RCCA email 2003. }
17... gxf5
{ 17...Bxf5?  The bishop is not very useful there and gets in the way of the knight.  18.Qc1  Bd7  19.Ng5+-  . }
18. Ng5
{ White's pieces are in a state of harmony, as no one is in the way of someone else. The knight's form an impressive vanguard; the bishops radiate in both directions. The queen's rook is the master of the 3rd rank and the king's rook can be placed on the b-file. }
18... Ng6
{ 18...e4  19.f3  Black's pawn is used as a hook, to open the position up for White's hungry pieces.  19...Ng6  Even the famous sealer-sweeper, as in Kotov-Gligoric, Zurich 1953, cannot turn the tide anymore.  20.fxe4  f4  21.Ne6  Bxe6  22.dxe6  Be5  23.Rf1  Rc6  24.Bg4+-  . }
19. Rh3 { Cleaning the 3rd rank of any possible dust particle there was. }
19... Nf6 20. Ne6 Bxe6 21. dxe6 e4
{ 21...Ne4  22.Be3  22...Ng5  23.Bxg5  Qxg5  24.Rh5  Drawing a nice geometrical pattern.  24...Qf6  25.g4!  fxg4  26.Bd3+-  Black is busted on the light squares. }
22. Bg5 Qe7
{ 22...Re8  23.g4+-  There hardly is a line in the Bayonet, where Black is allowed to collect the e-pawn just like this.   22...Rc6  23.g4  h6  24.gxf5  hxg5  25.fxg6  Qe8  26.Rg3  Qxe6  27.Bf3  White will penetrate Black's position after winning the e-pawn  27...Re8  28.Bg2  g4  29.Rge3  Qf5  30.Nc3-+  . }
23. f3 h6 { 23...Qxe6  24.Nc7+- } 24. Bxh6 Bxh6 25. Rxh6 Nf4 26. Qd2 N6h5 27.
Qc3 { Black's king is too exposed. } *

