1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... a5 11. bxa5 Rxa5 12. a4
{ I consider this stronger than the more frequent  12.Nd2  . Leaving the knight  as long as possible on f3, appears like a good general guideline to me. }
12... c5
{ Black's position is very passive and White has a clear plan to make progress. }
13. Ra3 Nf6 { The knight was exposed on h5 and returns to safety. } 14. Bd2
{ That's the best place for the bishop in so many lines. } 14... Ra6 15. Qc2
Ne8 16. Nb5
{ I will now distinguish between three different plans:    Black plays ...f5 at some stage.  Black stays completely passive. Black stays passive and plays ...b6. }
16... Kh8
{ This line is more important than the lines with ...f5, as it became clear that White's pieces could profit more from the open kingside than Black's. The really interesting question is: What does White do, if Black is simply biding his time? Advancing pawns on the kingside is possible, but not trivial. A move like f2-f4 needs good preparation, as it would activate the King's Indian bishop. Luckily, there is a more elegant plan. White is able to systematically make progress on the queenside. }
17. a5 Kg8 18. Rb1 Kh8 19. h3
{ As the plan is to transfer the light-squared bishop, we don't want to be molested by a possible ...Bg4, later on. }
19... Kg8 20. Qc1 Kh8 21. Bd1 Kg8 22. Bc2
{ This is the perfect interim set-up. The king's rook performed a 'castling' with the queen and can now rule the b-file. The light-squared bishop radiates in two directions and leaves the queen's rook free sight on the 3rd rank. The queen and the dark-squared bishop control an interesting diagonal. Once more, we have maximized harmony. }
22... Kh8 23. Nc3 { Now the second part of the plan begins: penetration. }
23... Nf6
{ The knight hurries, to neutralize his white counterpart.   23...Rxa5  24.Rxa5  Qxa5  25.Na4  Qc7  26.Nb6  Black cannot save his b-pawn, as its defender is about to be exchanged.  26...Nf6  27.Qb2  Kg8  28.Nxc8  Rxc8  29.Qxb7+-  White enjoys more space, the two bishops, play against the weak d-pawn and has penetrated Black's territory. }
24. Na4 Nd7 25. Rab3 Kg8 26. Nb6
{ The square b6 has to be cleared for the rook. } 26... Nxb6 27. Rxb6 Rxb6 28.
Rxb6 Kh8 29. Bg5 Qc7 30. Qb1 h6 31. Bd2 Kg8
{ Did you spot the ideal square for White's knight? } 32. Ne1
{ It might be a7, after all. That's why exchanging Black's rook was that strong. Now, Black cannot sit tight anymore. }
32... f5 33. Bd3 fxe4 34. Bxe4 Nf5 35. Nc2 Qd8 36. Na3 Rf7 37. Nb5 Bf8 38. Na7
{ There it is! } 38... h5 39. Bc3 Kh7 40. Qd3
{ Black suffers from 3 weaknesses and has to reckon with g2-g4.   40.Qd3  Qd7   40...Kh6  41.Nxc8  Qxc8  42.Bxf5  Rxf5  43.Qb1  Rf7  44.Bxe5  41.Qd1  Qc7  42.Qb1  Qd7  43.Bxf5  Qxf5   43...gxf5  44.f4  e4  45.Qd1  Kh6  46.Be5+-  44.Nxc8  Qxc8  45.Bxe5+-  Actually, White's rook was secretly in touch with all of Black's three weak pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 9.b4 Nh5 10.Re1 a5"]
[Black "11.bxa5 Rxa5 12.a4 c5 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... a5 11. bxa5 Rxa5 12. a4
{ I consider this stronger than the more frequent  12.Nd2  . Leaving the knight  as long as possible on f3, appears like a good general guideline to me. }
12... c5
{ Black's position is very passive and White has a clear plan to make progress. }
13. Ra3 Nf6 { The knight was exposed on h5 and returns to safety. } 14. Bd2
{ That's the best place for the bishop in so many lines. } 14... Ra6 15. Qc2
Ne8 16. Nb5
{ I will now distinguish between three different plans:    Black plays ...f5 at some stage.  Black stays completely passive. Black stays passive and plays ...b6. }
16... Kh8
{ This line is more important than the lines with ...f5, as it became clear that White's pieces could profit more from the open kingside than Black's. The really interesting question is: What does White do, if Black is simply biding his time? Advancing pawns on the kingside is possible, but not trivial. A move like f2-f4 needs good preparation, as it would activate the king's indian bishop. Luckily, there is a more elegant plan. White is able to systematically make progress on the queenside. }
17. a5 Kg8 18. Rb1 Kh8 19. h3
{ As the plan is to transfer the light-squared bishop, we don't want to be molested by a possible ...Bg4, later on. }
19... Kg8 20. Qc1 Kh8 21. Bd1 Kg8 22. Bc2
{ That's the perfect interim setup. The king's rook performed a 'castling' with the queen and can now rule the b-file. The light-squared bishop radiates in two directions and leaves the queen's rook free sight on the 3rd rank. The queen and the dark-squared bishop control an interesting diagonal. Once more, we have maximized harmony. }
22... Kh8 23. Nc3 { Now the second part of the plan begins: penetration. }
23... Nf6
{ The knight hurries, to neutralize his white counterpart.   23...Rxa5  24.Rxa5  Qxa5  25.Na4  Qc7  26.Nb6  Black cannot safe his b-pawn, as its defender is about to be exchanged.  26...Nf6  27.Qb2  Kg8  28.Nxc8  Rxc8  29.Qxb7+-  White enjoys more space, the two bishops, play against the weak d-pawn and has penetrated Black's territory. }
24. Na4 Nd7 25. Rab3 Kg8 26. Nb6
{ The square b6 has to be cleared for the rook. } 26... Nxb6 27. Rxb6 Ra7 28.
Qb2 h6 29. a6 { That's our motif. } 29... bxa6
{ 29...Rxa6  30.Rxa6  bxa6  31.Qb8+-  Invasion time. } 30. Ba5 Bd7 31. Qa3 *

