12... c5
{ Black's position is very passive and White has a clear plan to make progress. }
13. Ra3 Nf6 { The knight was exposed on h5 and returns to safety. } 14. Bd2
{ That's the best place for the bishop in so many lines. } 14... Ra6 15. Qc2
Ne8 16. Nb5
{ I will now distinguish between three different plans:    Black plays ...f5 at some stage.  Black stays completely passive. Black stays passive and plays ...b6. }
16... h6 17. Bd3 f5
{ Here, Black has prevented the knight sortie to g5. However, by shutting one door, another one is opened. }
18. exf5 Bxf5 19. h3
{ This move is linked to two ideas: Nh2-g4 and g2-g4, to attack a knight on f5. }
19... Qd7 { 19...Bxh3?  20.Nh4  Bf5  21.Nxg6+-  The power of the x-ray! } 20.
Nh2
{ Parrying Bxh3 and setting up the counter threat of g4! which will lead to the e7-knight running out of decent squares. }
20... Bxd3 21. Qxd3 Nf5 22. Rb1 Nf6 23. Ng4
{ This is an indirect way to fight for the square e4. } 23... h5 24. Nxf6+ Bxf6
25. Nc3 Bd8 26. Ne4
{ This square is better for the knight than b5. On e4 it doesn't jam the b-file and is also keeping an eye on g5. }
26... b6 27. a5
{ White is not forced to do this, but it shows the dynamic potential he has. }
27... bxa5 28. g4 Nd4 29. Bh6 Rf3 { 29...Re8  30.Rb8+- } 30. Qxf3 Nxf3+ 31.
Rxf3
{ With a crushing attack:  31...hxg4  32.Rf8+  Kh7  33.Bg5  gxh3  34.Kh2  Bxg5  35.Nxg5+  Kh6  36.Ne6+-  . }
