[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... a5 11. bxa5 Rxa5 12. a4 f5 13. exf5
{ The most popular move is  13.Nd2  , but after  13...Nf6  Black gets away with +=. }
13... gxf5 14. Ra3
{ The rook escapes the influence of the King's Indian bishop and can later be engaged on the 3rd rank. Less accurate is  14.Ng5  Nf4  15.Bxf4  exf4  +=. Now,  there is the tactical threat of Nxe5, as the knight on c3 is protected. }
14... Nf6 15. Ng5
{ The knight is targeting the well-known weak spot in the heart of Black's position. }
15... h6
{ 15...b6  16.Nb5  Ra8  17.Rh3  transposes to the position that we've examined thoroughlyhere in chapter  3. }
16. Ne6 Bxe6 17. dxe6
{ As usual, the pawn is relatively safe on e6. Conquering it, will always come with a price. }
17... Kh7
{ 17...Qc8  18.Nb5  Kh7  19.Rh3+-   17...c6  18.Rb3  If you play through the lines of this course, you will witness this rook stepping on every single square on the third rank. For me it resembles the eye of Sauron @@StartBracket@@maybe that's a good name for the rook, once it appears on a3@@EndBracket@@, which turns its sight to wherever the action is. Right now, its attention has shifted to the b-file, as the square b6 has just been weakened.  18...b6  19.Be3  Nc8  20.Qd2  f4   20...Qe7  21.Bxb6  Ra8  22.Be3  Provoking f4.  22...f4  23.Bb6  Qxe6  24.a5+-  Black's central structure is fragile, while White's passed pawn will bind a good part of Black's forces.  21.Bxb6!  Nxb6  22.e7  The e-pawn is a constant source of chaos for Black. Here, it is used as a deflection device.  22...Qxe7  23.Rxb6  Rc5   23...Qd7  24.Rd1  Rd8  25.Ne4  25...Rxa4  26.Nxd6+-  24.Bf3  Qd7  25.Rd1  Rxc4   25...Rd8  26.a5!  Rxa5  27.Bxc6  Qf7  28.Ne4+-  White will be winning the d-pawn one way or another, for instance by playing c4-c5.  26.Qa2  Qf7  27.Rxc6  Rxc6  28.Bxc6  Qxa2  29.Nxa2  Rc8  30.Rc1  30...Rc7  31.Nb4+-  This endgame is a nice example for the power of the outside passed pawn and opposite colored bishops of different value. }
18. Bd2 Ra8
{ 18...b6  19.g4!  Chiseling away light-squared obstacles is nothing new for us. But rest assured. You don't have to find such moves OTB, as there are normally more conventional alternatives at hand. Here, 19.Nd5 is also a good option.  19...fxg4   19...e4  20.Nb5  Ra8  21.Rh3+-  when Black's h-pawn is under severe attack.  20.Ne4!  Ra7   20...Nxe4  21.Bd3  Kh8  22.Bxe4+-  21.Nxf6+  What follows is a good example for piece improvement.  21...Rxf6  22.Rg3  Rxe6  23.Bd3+  Kh8  24.Qxg4  Qg8  25.Kh1  Rxa4  26.Reg1+- }
19. a5 c6 20. Qc2 d5
{ Black gets his center rolling, but with no great effect, as White's pieces are operating from a safe distance. }
21. Na4 d4
{ 21...e4  22.Nb6  Rb8   22...Ra7  23.cxd5  cxd5  24.Qc5  Nc6  25.Bb5  Re8  26.Nd7  26...Ra8  27.a6+-  This line is a good example for the ineffectiveness of a broad pawn center, once the opponent has conquered a vast amount of space on a wing. White simply avoided the center and was comfortable, playing on the left side of the board.  23.cxd5  Nexd5   23...cxd5  24.Bf4+-  24.Rb3  Nxb6  25.Rxb6  Nd5  26.Rb3  Black's active minor pieces cannot compensate for the fact, that Black's pawn structure is fragile. There is no way to swallow White's e-pawn in peace.  26...Qe7   26...Re8  27.Reb1  Qc8  28.g4!  Once more, softening up the light-squares is the key to success.  28...Rxe6  29.gxf5  Re7  30.f3+-  27.Reb1  Be5   27...Qxe6  28.Rxb7+-  28.a6  bxa6  29.Qxc6+-  White's e-pawn is still alive. }
22. Rb1 Ra7
{ 22...e4  23.Rxb7  d3  Finally, Black has gotten somewhere with his pawn roller. However, White also made progress in the meanwhile, which allows him to simply remove the spear head.  24.Bxd3!  exd3  25.Rxd3  Qe8  26.Nc5+-  Black is completely lost, as his pieces are very passive. }
23. Nc5 e4 24. Qc1 Qd6
{ 24...d3  25.Bxd3!  exd3  26.Rxd3  Qc7  27.Nd7  White has penetrated Black's position and is ready to start the final assault.  27...Rfa8  28.Bxh6  Bxh6  29.Nxf6+  Kg6  30.Qc3+- }
25. Rh3 Neg8
{ 25...Qxc5  26.Bxh6  Ng4  27.Bxg7+  Kxg7  28.Qg5+  Ng6  29.Bxg4+-  intending Rh6 and Bh5. }
26. Bb4 Qe5 27. Qg5
{ White is threatening f4, which would force Black to abandon his impressive center. }
27... d3 28. Nxd3 exd3 29. Bxd3 Ne4 30. Bxe4 Qxe4 31. Re1 Qg4 32. Qd2 Re8 33.
Rg3 Qd4 34. Qc2
{ At the end of this pretty forced line, White is again standing at the gates of Black's palace. }
*

