13... Nxf5 14. Bg5 { Accepting the offer to play a move free of charge. } 14...
Nf6
{ 14...Qd7  15.Bd2  The bishop returns to its favored square, after having misplaced the queen.  15...Ra8  16.Ra3  Nf6  17.Bd3  Nd4  18.Ng5±  Now challenging the d4-knight with Nb5 would give the king's knight access to e6.   14...Qe8  This is not a good place for the queen, due to its opposition to White's rook and the unprotected c-pawn  @@StartBracket@@fueling Nb5@@EndBracket@@.  15.Ra3±  Now, Black faces the threat of 16.g4, as 16...e4 no longer has to be feared. }
15. Bd3 b6 { 15...Bh6??  16.Bxf5  Bxg5  17.Bxc8+- } 16. h3
{ Introducing g4 as a future option, in order to challenge the knight on f5. }
16... Bd7 17. Ra3 Ra8 18. Bc2
{ Overprotecting the a-pawn and clearing the 3rd rank for the rook. } 18... Qc8
19. Bc1
{ The idea is to play Ng5 after the reply Nd4 has been ruled out. This can be achieved by g4. Note, that chasing the annoying knight away from g5 with h6 always weakens the g6-pawn. }
