1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nh5
{ Depending on your perspective, this could be considered the critical variation. Obviously, Black not only makes way for the f-pawn but also prepares to jump to f4 with his knight. This visually attractive move resulted in a high degree of popularity. With near 10,  000  games,  9...Nh5  clearly takes the lead in front of  9...a5  with only 4,  000  games.  That said, the leader of the ranks is not seen too often in top-level chess anymore. As we go along with our analyses, it will become clear why this is the case. In order to sharpen your awareness, I will now summarize the reasons upfront:   1@@EndBracket@@ On h5, the knight is a tactical liability. If White's king's knight moves, it will be under attack. In case of the sequence ...f5 /exf5 gxf5, the knight will be altogether unprotected.   2@@EndBracket@@ In case of ...f5/exf5 Nxf5, there is the fork g2-g4 available for White. With a pawn on h3, this will also be the case when the bishop takes on f5.  3@@EndBracket@@ If the knight jumps to f4, it might be taken under favorable circumstances. How this could lead to disaster will be shown in the very first two chapters.   4@@EndBracket@@ In most cases, White will retreat with the bishop to f1 and render the knight pretty harmless on f4. Note, that from f4 the knight cannot help Black to fight for the important square e4 anymore.   5@@EndBracket@@ With the knight sitting on f4, the pawn storm starting with ...f5-f4 is not working anymore. It's not even possible with the knight on h5, as ...g6-g5 doesn't work with that loose knight. Moreover, the move ...h7-h5, supporting ...g5-g4 is impossible.   6@@EndBracket@@ Often, Black faces the positional threat, that the knight is being dislodged by g3 when it would have to retreat to a problematic position on h5 or g6. }
10. Re1
{ The alternative is  10.g3  with the idea to play  10...f5  11.Ng5  ,  followed by Ne6. This plan in itself is dangerous for Black and we will use it in some of our lines. That said, I feel reluctant to taint our perfect castle, with the pawns still on h2, g2, and f2, in order to prevent Black from doing something, which is most probably bad for him. The knight on f4 is exposed and much more of a concern for Black, than for us.   There is no need to engage in the potentially sharp lines after 10.g3 when our variation leads to a huge advantage without any kind of trouble. For me, this is a clear case, where prophylaxis is stronger than restriction. Black now has the following options: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1npbp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf4  ,  10...f5  ,  10...a5  , and  10...h6  , which will be covered throughout the rest of this course. }
10... a5 11. bxa5 Rxa5 12. a4 f5 13. exf5
{ The most popular move is  13.Nd2  , but after  13...Nf6  Black gets away with +=. }
13... Bxf5
{ The bishop is rarely well placed on f5, as it creates a conflict with the knight on e7. }
14. Ra3 Nf6 15. Nb5
{ As we already know, this move is often a prelude for the e6-jump, as it will indirectly protect the e-pawn against the attack by the queen. }
15... h6 16. h3 { 16.Nh4  looks also reasonable. } 16... g5
{ 16...b6  17.Bd2  Ra8  18.a5± } 17. c5
{ Dynamically attacking Black's structure is justified by White's space advantage and better king safety. }
17... Kh8 18. Bb2 { Frustrating a possible ...dxc5. } 18... Qd7
{ After  18...Nfxd5?  19.cxd6  cxd6  20.Bc4  Be6  21.Rd3+-  Black's center will fall apart. }
19. Nd2 Nfxd5 20. Nc4 Ra6 21. Bf1
{ White has all the time in the world, as Black is frozen in the center. Now Rf3, threatening g4 would be a good follow up idea. }
21... Bh7 { 21...Rc6  22.cxd6  cxd6  23.Rf3+- } 22. Ra2 Bg8 23. Ba3
{ Now, Black's center will blow up, with bad consequences for the king. } 23...
dxc5 24. Nxe5 Qc8 25. Bxc5
{ If you dare to loosen your fortress with g6 and f5, you better make sure that the d6-e5-barrier endures. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 9.b4 a5 10.bxa5 Rxa5 11.a4 Nd7 − 13th Moves"]
[Black "12.Ba3 Ra8 13.Bb4 Kh8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ This is the second most frequent continuation. By challenging White's b-pawn, Black starts a fight over the critical c5-square.   We have already seen this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8+=  . In our variations, the knight will appear on  d7  , which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the square c5. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one. However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as ...Ne8 would do. }
12. Ba3
{ I first analyzed the alternative  12.Nd2  , with the idea to influence  the dark squares on the queenside by Nb3. At the beginning, that looked very promising. But after many days of work, I finally found a way for Black to achieve a position with roughly half a pawn unit disadvantage and no winning chances whatsoever. Even with pincers, I wouldn't touch this with Black.  For most White repertoires, such a line would have been perfectly okay, but it would have forced me to abandon the '+/- - paradigm'. Hence, I decided to look at the text move, and fortunately, I liked what I saw. }
12... Ra8
{ Black has a large variety of alternatives, but after all of them there follows Bb4 Ra8. In order to unify the material, I decided to execute both moves at the beginning, thus establishing the tabiya after Bb4. }
13. Bb4 Kh8
{ Before becoming active with f5, Black removes his king from the potentially dangerous a2-g8 diagonal. At the same time, he creates a square for the problem knight, which now could be activated via g8 to f6. This maneuver would also increase the scope of the queen. }
14. a5
{ Gaining space in the usual manner and nailing the b-pawn to its post. } 14...
f5 15. Nd2
{ Black's idea is to answer  15.Bd3  with  15...Nc5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r1k/1ppnn1bp/3p2p1/P2Ppp2/1BP1P3/2N2N2/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Ng5  with  15...Nb8  16.c5  Nec6!  17.dxc6  Nxc6  .  For this to work, the king had to leave g8. I found a novelty in this line, which makes Black's position difficult to play. Nevertheless, I made Nd2 the main line, as it is objectively the best move. }
15... Rf7 16. Qc2
{ In the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Tauber, H @@StartBracket@@2539@@EndBracket@@-Sikorsky, H @@StartBracket@@2521@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017 there followed  16.Na4?  Nf6+=  , when the pressure on White's central pawns didn't allow  17.c5  . }
16... Nf6 { 16...Ng8  17.Na4± } 17. c5 dxc5 18. Bxc5 fxe4 19. Ndxe4 Nexd5 20.
Ng5 Rd7 21. Ne6 Qg8 22. Nxg7
{ Without his personal body guard, the king is even more exposed than before. }
*

