{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8+=  . In our variations, the knight will appear on  d7  , which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the square c5. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one. However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as ...Ne8 would do. }
12. Ba3
{ I first analyzed the alternative  12.Nd2  , with the idea to influence  the dark squares on the queenside by Nb3. At the beginning, that looked very promising. But after many days of work, I finally found a way for Black to achieve a position with roughly half a pawn unit disadvantage and no winning chances whatsoever. Even with pincers, I wouldn't touch this with Black.  For most White repertoires, such a line would have been perfectly okay, but it would have forced me to abandon the '+/- - paradigm'. Hence, I decided to look at the text move, and fortunately, I liked what I saw. }
12... Ra8
{ Black has a large variety of alternatives, but after all of them there follows Bb4 Ra8. In order to unify the material, I decided to execute both moves at the beginning, thus establishing the tabiya after Bb4. }
13. Bb4 Kh8
{ Before becoming active with f5, Black removes his king from the potentially dangerous a2-g8 diagonal. At the same time, he creates a square for the problem knight, which now could be activated via g8 to f6. This maneuver would also increase the scope of the queen. }
14. a5
{ Gaining space in the usual manner and nailing the b-pawn to its post. } 14...
f5 15. Nd2
{ Black's idea is to answer  15.Bd3  with  15...Nc5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r1k/1ppnn1bp/3p2p1/P2Ppp2/1BP1P3/2N2N2/4BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Ng5  with  15...Nb8  16.c5  Nec6!  17.dxc6  Nxc6  .  For this to work, the king had to leave g8. I found a novelty in this line, which makes Black's position difficult to play. Nevertheless, I made Nd2 the main line, as it is objectively the best move. }
15... Bh6
{ Exerting pressure on the knight is logical and appears to be stronger than the ...Ng8 idea. }
16. Re1
{ White has many options and most of them yield positions ranging somewhere between a slight and a clear advantage. This novelty might be the only move which concludes with a definitive +/-. The idea is to reinforce the control of the important e4-square, which was already challenged by Black's last move. }
16... Ng8
{ Black uses his queen's knight @@StartBracket@@don't confuse the knights, here@@EndBracket@@ to fight for the e4-square, in order to keep c5 under control. }
17. Na4 { This square was given the knight by the strong move a5. } 17... Ngf6
18. Bd3 Ng4
{ By tactical means, Black lures the knight away from controlling the square e4. }
19. Nf3 { White had to address the threats of Qh4 and Nf2. } 19... Ndf6 20. Nc3
{ The kingside had to be stabilized. Bad would be  20.exf5?  gxf5  21.h3  Nxf2  22.Kxf2  e4=  . }
20... fxe4 21. Nxe4
{ The alternative  21.Bxe4  Nxe4  22.Nxe4  Nf6  23.Ng3!  @@StartBracket@@preventing the light-squared bishop from participating@@EndBracket@@ also promises White a distinct advantage. }
21... Nxe4 22. Bxe4 Nf6 23. Bc2
{ Analysis has shown, that this move is better than Nd2 and Bd3. } 23... Bf5
{ If Black doesn't play actively, White would continue with c5. } 24. h3
{ Getting the square g4 under control and providing the king with air makes this a good semi-waiting move. Black cannot use the extra tempo for much and many moves would indeed deteriorate his position. }
24... Ra6
{ Black plans to play b6 at some point. However, by weakening the 8th rank, this move allows White to perform a favorable transformation.   24...Kg8?!  25.c5  Bxc2  26.Qxc2±  Nxd5?  27.Qb3  Actually, White needed the king on g8 to play c5.  27...c6  28.cxd6+- }
25. Bxf5 gxf5 26. Nxe5 dxe5 27. Bxf8 Qxf8 { 27...Bxf8?  28.Rxe5+- } 28. Qb3 Qc8
29. Rxe5 Bg7 { 29...Ne4?  30.Qf3+- } 30. Re6 Ne4
{ 30...Ra8?  31.Rae1  Ne4  32.Qe3  32...Rxa5  33.f3  Nf6  34.Re8++-   30...Rxe6?  31.dxe6  Qxe6  32.Qxb7+- }
31. Rxa6 bxa6 32. Rb1 Bd4 33. Qb8 Qxb8 34. Rxb8+ Kg7 35. Ra8 Nc5 36. g3
{ White has good chances to create a passed pawn on the kingside. } *

