{ Black's intention is to exchange a pawn on the queenside, in order to get rid of one potential weakness. This idea is based on sound logic, but there is also a downside to it. The additional open file will give White more space for his pieces. }
14. a5 bxa5 { This is the only reasonable move. } 15. Bxa5
{ I like this move a bit better than  15...Rxa5  , but both options are of approximately the same strength. }
15... Nc5 { There is no genuine alternative. } 16. Bb4 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 Na6
{ 18.Bxc5 was the threat. } 18. Ba3
{ Obviously, Black has a weak pawn on c7. If White manages to enforce c4-c5, the point d6 will be targeted as well. }
18... c5
{ That's the principal alternative. Now, White's dark-squared bishop is confined and the threat of c4-c5 has been stopped. On the flipside, Black's d-pawn has turned into a serious weakness. }
19. Rb1 f5 20. Qb2 Qa5
{ 20...fxe4?  Granting White's pieces access to the key square e4 is hardly recommendable, e.g.  21.Nxe4  Nc7  22.Qb6  Bf5  23.Bd3  Qd7  24.Qb7  Bxe4  25.Bxe4  Nf5  26.Bc1  Nd4  27.Bd2+-  White has already invaded Black's half of the board and is in full control. }
21. Ra1 Nc7
{ 21...Nb4?  22.Bxb4  Qxb4  23.Rb1  Qa5  Exchanging queens would allow White's rook to move to b6.  24.Ng5  Bf6  25.Ne6  Bxe6  26.dxe6+-  . }
22. Ra2 Ne8 23. Nd2 Bh6 24. Qc2 Nf6 25. Bc1 Qb6 26. Bd3
{ White has disentangled his pieces on the queenside and is now ready to start the invasion. }
26... Bd7 27. Nf3 Bxc1
{ Exchanging the 'bad bishop' looks like the better choice, but the classification in good and bad is not always as straight-forward as it seems. Just think of the low life White's light-squared bishop sometimes has to endure in the Stonewall Dutch. Here, White's dark-squared bishop is restricted by Blacks pawn triangle, whereas Black's counterpart is able to defend the king and the pawn on d6, which is the Achilles' heel of the position.   27...Bg7  28.Ng5  f4  29.Qd1  Rb8  30.g3±  with play on both sides of the board. }
28. Qxc1 Qb8
{ 28...fxe4  29.Bxe4  Kg7  30.Qa1  Rb8  31.Bd3  White's position is close to winning, given the loose black structure and White's ability to play on both wings. The threat is Ng5. }
29. Ng5 f4 30. Nb5 { Those two Bayonet knights again. } 30... Nc8 31. Qa1 h6
32. Ra8 Qb7 33. Nf3 { There is no obligation to do the e6-jump. } 33... Bxb5
34. cxb5 Nb6 35. Ra7 Qb8 36. Nd2 Rc8 37. Bc4 { Blocking Black's c-pawn. } 37...
Rc7 38. Ra6 Kg7 39. g3
{ The tension on the kingside will pose Black some serious problems. In case he plays  39...g5  ,  White will exchange the blockading knight on b6 by moving his knight to c4. If Black replaces the blockader by his king's knight, the g4-square might serve White's pieces for invading the kingside. }
