{ Black's intention is to exchange a pawn on the queenside, in order to get rid of one potential weakness. This idea is based on sound logic, but there is also a downside to it. The additional open file will give White more space for his pieces. }
14. a5 bxa5 { This is the only reasonable move. } 15. Bxa5
{ I like this move a bit better than  15...Rxa5  , but both options are of approximately the same strength. }
15... Nc5 { There is no genuine alternative. } 16. Bb4 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 Na6
{ Bxc5 was the threat. } 18. Ba3
{ Obviously, Black has a weak pawn on c7. If White manages to enforce c4-c5, the point d6 will be targeted as well. }
18... f5
{ ½-½ @@StartBracket@@17@@EndBracket@@ Flumbort,A @@StartBracket@@2355@@EndBracket@@-Hazai,L @@StartBracket@@2440@@EndBracket@@ Hungary 2000. This is how the only game continued and ended, as the weaker player accepted the draw offer in this clearly better position. Let's see how the game may have unfolded. }
19. Rd1
{ This is not only a prophylaxis against the ...c7-c5 advance. White also stabilizes the d-pawn in view of a later c4-c5. }
19... Kh8 20. Ng5 Ng8
{ 20...fxe4  21.Ngxe4  Nf5  22.Nb5  Qh4  23.Bd3±  White can be very satisfied with the location of his knights and is close to winning. }
21. Ne6 Bxe6 22. dxe6
{ Here, the loose knight on a6 prevents Black from simply devouring the passed pawn. }
22... Qc8 23. Nb5 Rd8 24. g3
{ Useful air for the king, before the direct confrontation starts. Black is void of good moves. }
24... h6
{ 24...fxe4  25.Bg4+-   24...Ne7  25.Bxd6  cxd6  26.Nxd6  Rxd6  27.Rxd6  Nc5  28.Qa7+-  Intending Qb6. Black won't be able to deal with White's passed pawns. }
25. exf5 gxf5 26. Bh5 Qxe6 27. Bxd6 cxd6 28. Qxa6 Qxc4 29. Qb6 Rf8 30. Nxd6 Qc2
31. Re1 { Black will lose on the light squares. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 9.b4 a5 10.bxa5 Rxa5 11.a4 Nd7 − 13th Moves"]
[Black "12.Ba3 Ra8 13.Bb4 b6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ This is the second most frequent continuation. By challenging White's b-pawn, Black starts a fight over the critical c5-square.   We have already seen this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8+=  . In our variations, the knight will appear on  d7  , which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the square c5. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one. However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as ...Ne8 would do. }
12. Ba3
{ I first analyzed the alternative  12.Nd2  , with the idea to influence  the dark squares on the queenside by Nb3. At the beginning, that looked very promising. But after many days of work, I finally found a way for Black to achieve a position with roughly half a pawn unit disadvantage and no winning chances whatsoever. Even with pincers, I wouldn't touch this with Black.  For most White repertoires, such a line would have been perfectly okay, but it would have forced me to abandon the '+/- - paradigm'. Hence, I decided to look at the text move, and fortunately, I liked what I saw. }
12... Ra8
{ Black has a large variety of alternatives, but after all of them there follows Bb4 Ra8. In order to unify the material, I decided to execute both moves at the beginning, thus establishing the tabiya after Bb4. }
13. Bb4 b6
{ Black's intention is to exchange a pawn on the queenside, in order to get rid of one potential weakness. This idea is based on sound logic, but there is also a downside to it. The additional open file will give White more space for his pieces. }
14. a5 Nc5 15. axb6 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 cxb6 17. Bxc5
{ Exchanging Black's only active piece and at the same time exposing the weak d-pawn. }
17... bxc5 { The pawn can now be attacked from the side. } 18. Rb1
{ This is slightly stronger than  18.Qa7  , which has been played in a couple of games. Obviously, Black is unable to stop White from invading the queenside, which makes defending the d-pawn a difficult task. }
18... Qc7
{ 18...Bg4  19.h3  Bxf3  20.Bxf3+-  Black's d-pawn is undefendable in the long run. }
19. Qb2 Bg4 20. Qb6 Qxb6 21. Rxb6
{ Exchanging queens didn't relieve the pressure, as black's queen was defending important points. }
21... Ra8
{ Black has to activate his rook, if he doesn’t want to be completely helpless.   21...Nc8?  22.Rb7  Rd8  23.Nd2  Bxe2  24.Nxe2  Bf8  25.Rb8+-  'Knightmare' ahead! }
22. h3 Bxf3 23. Bxf3 Bf8 24. Nb5 Nc8 25. Rb7 Ra6
{ Preparing 26...Nb6 and binding White's bishop to the defense of the c-pawn for the time being.   25...h5  This would only help White's bishop to enter the battle immediately.  26.g4  hxg4  27.Bxg4  Ne7  28.Bd7  Rd8  29.h4  Nc8  30.Bh3  30...Ne7  31.Na7  Kg7  32.Nc6  Re8  33.Ra7  As the rook is short of squares, Black will lose the exchange. }
26. Be2 Nb6 27. Bf1 Na4
{ As this position is won for White, it isn't worth being thoroughly analyzed. I just give one representative line: }
28. h4 h5 29. Rb8 Kg7 30. g3 Be7 31. Re8 Bf8 32. f4
{ White will be able to create a passed pawn.   32.f4  Nb6   32...f6?  33.Nc7  33.fxe5  dxe5  34.d6  Ra1  35.Kf2  Ra2+  36.Ke3  Rb2  37.Rd8  Rb3+  38.Kf2  Rb2+  39.Be2  .  The idea is to play Nc3, followed by d7 and Rxf8. If Black places the rook on d2, White will shield the pawn with Nd5. }
