Re8
{ 24...Nxe4?  25.Bd3   That banal solution is not the only reasonable continuation. Even donating the exchange with  25.Bf1  Kg7  26.Raxe4!  fxe4  27.Rxe4  +- comes into consideration.  As the pawn on a6 devalues Black's rooks through its presence, you can be very liberal with small sacrifices.  25...Nd6  26.Nxe5+- }
25. Bd3 Kh8 26. Qb2 Qf7 27. Qe2 Raa8 28. h4
{ The idea is to play h5 at some point. If Black stops it with h5, that pawn becomes a target. There are some chances that this position is won. Instead of performing a deep analysis in order to arrive at a clear verdict, I would rather invest the time somewhere else in this project. If you are afraid that this here might be a fortress, there are some alternatives to resort to, for instance, the move 17.Qa3. }
