1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ This is the second most frequent continuation. By challenging White's b-pawn, Black starts a fight over the critical c5-square.   We have already seen this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8+=  . In our variations, the knight will appear on  d7  , which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4
{ Now, Black has many different options. We will have a look at  11...Nd7  ,  11...c5  ,  11...b6  , and  11...Ne8  . }
11... Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the square c5. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one. However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as ...Ne8 would do. }
12. Ba3
{ I first analyzed the alternative  12.Nd2  , with the idea to influence  the dark squares on the queenside by Nb3. At the beginning, that looked very promising. But after many days of work, I finally found a way for Black to achieve a position with roughly half a pawn unit disadvantage and no winning chances whatsoever. Even with pincers, I wouldn't touch this with Black.  For most White repertoires, such a line would have been perfectly okay, but it would have forced me to abandon the '+/- - paradigm'. Hence, I decided to look at the text move, and fortunately, I liked what I saw. }
12... Ra8
{ Black has a large variety of alternatives, but after all of them there follows Bb4 Ra8. In order to unify the material, I decided to execute both moves at the beginning, thus establishing the tabiya after Bb4. }
13. Bb4
{ Now, we find the following structure:  13...f5  ,  13...Bh6  ,  13...h6  ,  13...Kh8  ,  13...b6  , and  13...Nc5  . As logic demands, I start with the most direct approach. }
13... f5 14. Ng5
{ That's one of the reasons why we like to leave the knight on f3. Black's weak spot e6 is easily accessible. }
14... Nc5
{ This will lead to a disrupted structure, but it is still better than allowing White to open the position as after ...Nf6. }
15. Bxc5 dxc5
{ White gave up his bishop pair, but received many assets in return:   a@@EndBracket@@ Black's structure lost its flexibility.   b@@EndBracket@@ We see an isolated e-pawn and a slightly exposed pawn on c5.   c@@EndBracket@@ From a more dynamic perspective we observe the potential of the newly liberated d-pawn, which can either advance or turn into a passed pawn after the sequence Ne6 Bxe6 / dxe6. The involved opening of the d-file gives this option additional punch. }
16. a5
{ The rationale behind the text move is to prevent a fortification of Black's structure by b6, giving support to the somewhat fragile pawn on c5 and also placing the b-pawn on a protected square. As the c5-pawn is now isolated from the b-pawn, it can be attacked by Na4 or the queen from various squares. If Black defends the pawn with b6, we would see a further change of structure after axb6 cxb6. Now, White would attack the weak pawn on b6 or use the square b5 for his knight. Moreover, the pawn d5 would turn into a passed pawn. }
16... Bh6 17. Ne6
{ 17.Nf3  , which happened in the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Dziadyk, P @@StartBracket@@2198@@EndBracket@@-Kruglyakov, P @@StartBracket@@2043@@EndBracket@@ Kiev 2002 is clearly inferior, albeit still very favorable for White.   A good alternative, however, is  17.h4! }
17... Bxe6 18. dxe6
{ The vanguard pawn opens the possibility for White to use the square d7 for the invasion. }
18... Bd2
{ Black exploits his superiority on the dark squares to win a pawn by a nice geometrical maneuver. But will he be happy with it? }
19. Nd5 { 19.Qc2?  Bxc3  20.Qxc3  Qd6  would allow Black to equalize. } 19...
Bxa5 { This bishop is offside now and will be missing on the kingside. } 20.
Ra3 c6 21. Nxe7+ Qxe7 22. Qa1 b6 23. exf5 Rxf5 24. Rd1 e4
