15... fxe4 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. Ncxe4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Rf4
{ This is a pseudo-active move, which fails to solve the problems with the d-pawn conveniently. The position, however, was not enviable, anyways.   18...Nf5  19.Rb1Ν  Rf7  20.h3  Bf8  21.Bc3+-  Black has too many weaknesses. He has to worry about Ng5-e6 and the siege of his d-pawn. White might place the pawn on a5, the rook on b6 and the bishop on b4. Finally, Black's knight could by questioned by g4 or Bg4. }
19. Bf3 Bf5
{ 19...Ra6?!  20.g3  Rxf3   After  20...Rf8  21.Be2  +- Black will lose his d-pawn.  21.Qxf3+-  1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Seitner,R @@StartBracket@@2015@@EndBracket@@-Stoffel,M @@StartBracket@@1987@@EndBracket@@ Bayern 2016. }
20. Qd3
{ This is much more active than  20.Re1  , which has been played in a couple of games.  It is understandable, that a player is reluctant to create a self-pinning situation, but if it cannot be exploited, there is nothing wrong with it, objectively. White's idea is to play 21.a5 and deploy the king's rook actively on b1, pressing against the b-pawn. Black will have to exchange his bishop on e4, after which White's bishop on e4 will be directed towards Black's kingside. A plan such as g3 and h4-h5 will complement the queenside pressure. }
