[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ This is the second most frequent continuation. By challenging White's b-pawn, Black starts a fight over the critical c5-square.   We have already seen this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8+=  . In our variations, the knight will appear on  d7  , which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the square c5. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one. However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as ...Ne8 would do. }
12. Ba3
{ I first analyzed the alternative  12.Nd2  , with the idea to influence  the dark squares on the queenside by Nb3. At the beginning, that looked very promising. But after many days of work, I finally found a way for Black to achieve a position with roughly half a pawn unit disadvantage and no winning chances whatsoever. Even with pincers, I wouldn't touch this with Black.  For most White repertoires, such a line would have been perfectly okay, but it would have forced me to abandon the '+/- - paradigm'. Hence, I decided to look at the text move, and fortunately, I liked what I saw. }
12... Ra8
{ Black has a large variety of alternatives, but after all of them there follows Bb4 Ra8. In order to unify the material, I decided to execute both moves at the beginning, thus establishing the tabiya after Bb4. }
13. Bb4 Bh6
{ By covering the square g5, Black wants to avoid the problems he faces after ...f5 and Ng5. The bishop appears to be more active on h6, but in reality, it doesn't manage to influence White's further development much. Its absence from g7 will reduce Black's dynamic options. }
14. a5
{ We have seen this move many times before. By suppressing Black's b-pawn, White not only fixes it as a weakness, he also improves his chances in the fight for the key square c5. }
14... f5 15. Bd3
{ The bishop fortifies the point e4 and at the same time exerts pressure on Black's f-pawn. }
15... Kh8
{ The king is dodging potential problems on the a2-g8 diagonal and vacates the square g8 for the knight. }
16. Re1
{ One of the characteristics of the Bayonet Attack is the combination of central actions with play on the wings. The rook gives additional support to the key square e4, but is also setting his sight on Black's e-pawn. We mustn't forget, that the center right now is more dynamic than static, with the advance c4-c5 hanging in the air. }
16... Ng8
{ With this move, Black is liberating the queen and approximating the knight to the key square e4. As there is pressure on the f-pawn, Ngf6 will hardly be an option, though. Hence, the idea is to play the queen's knight to f6, exchange everything on e4 and then bring the reserve knight from g8 into play. Unfortunately for Black, the dynamics of the position don't allow this plan to work out. }
17. h3
{ White is so well centralized, that Black can hardly do anything constructive. Hence, slowly improving the position before taking visible actions is the right thing to do. The gratis move h3 may come in handy later, when the king needs air, the knight wants to go to h2 or when the advance g2-g4 becomes interesting. }
17... Ndf6
{ Black didn't want to sit still, which is no easy thing to do in chess, and continued with his plan to fight for the e4-square. But as Bobby said 'If you wanna get some @@StartBracket@@squares@@EndBracket@@, you gotta give some.' Now White has a free hand with his standard pawn-break. }
18. c5
{ Nothing spectacular has occurred. Black just allowed a losing structure to come into existence, where the fragility of the pawn d6 is more than the position can bear. White's simple plan is to transfer his knight to c4. }
18... fxe4 19. Bxe4
{ That's better than  19.Nxe4  . Now, Black can't alleviate the pressure  by taking on e4, as this would lead to a collapse of his pawn structure after Nxe4. }
19... Rf7 20. Bc2 Bf5 21. Bb3 Ne8 22. c6
{ Black managed to secure his d-pawn, by accepting a passive position. This allows white to execute the alternative plan of pushing the a-pawn. Good positions come with many options, as mentioned in the introduction. }
22... Qb8 23. Ra4
{ In the encounter 1-0 @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Smirnov, P @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@-Jenni, F @@StartBracket@@2517@@EndBracket@@ Istanbul 2004, there followed  23.g4?  bxc6  24.dxc6  Bc2!  , instead, and the game dragged on for 51 moves. The text move simply protects the bishop and leaves Black completely tied up. }
23... Re7 { 23...Ngf6  24.Ba3+- } 24. g4 Bc8 25. Bc4 Bf4
{ 25...bxc6  26.dxc6  This clears the square d5 for White's knight.  26...Ba6  27.Bb3  Bg7  28.Nd5  Bb5  29.Ra1  Rf7  30.Ng5  Rf8  31.Ne6  Rf7  32.Ndxc7!  Nxc7  33.Nxg7  Rxg7  34.Bxd6+-   25...Bg7  26.Qb3  Nef6  27.Ba3  27...bxc6  28.Qxb8  Rxb8  29.dxc6  Ra8  30.a6+-  The a-pawn is the decisive factor, of course. }
26. Qc2 Ngf6 { 26...g5  27.Rb1  h5  28.cxb7  Bxb7  29.a6+-  winning material. }
27. Ne2 g5 { 27...Bh6  28.g5+- } 28. Nxf4 gxf4 29. Bc3
{ White's superior piece activity allows him to think in terms of brute force. }
29... b5 30. axb6 Rxa4 31. Qxa4 Qxb6 32. Qa3
{ White is intending to play Nxe5 after every non-crazy move. } *

