21. Qc4
{ From c4 the queen controls many important squares, such as g4, e4, b5, and c6 @@StartBracket@@c5-c6 becomes an option@@EndBracket@@.   It prevents the idea ...g5-g4, as after  21...g5  there follows  22.Ne4  and Black  loses control over the square g4.   If Black just waits with a move such as  21...Kg8  , White will reinforce his position with  22.Rad1  and h3.   The move  21.Ne4  , which happened in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@ Vegjeleki, A @@StartBracket@@2288@@EndBracket@@-Rozanski, R @@StartBracket@@2081@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016, is less suitable, as Black can ease his defensive tasks by exchanging one pair of minor pieces. }
21... Bg7
{ If Black succeeds in playing ...h6 and ...Qf7, he would considerably improve his chances. }
22. Ng5 Nd4 23. Nce4 Nxe4 24. Nxe4 Qf7
{ That's a tactical idea to deal with the d6-problem, but it doesn't work. }
25. cxd6 c6 26. d7 cxd5 27. Qc7 Rfd8 { 27...dxe4?  28.Bxf8  Qxf8  29.Qxb7+- }
