10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8+=  . In our variations, the knight will appear on  d7  , which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4 Nd7
{ The knight clears the f-pawn and supports the control of the square c5. As hitting two birds with one stone is a very appealing concept, it doesn't surprise, that this option is the most frequent one. However, it is worth mentioning that the move also has its drawbacks. By hemming the bishop, the square e6 is weakened in case of ...f7-f5. Furthermore, the knight doesn't defend the sore points c7 and d6, as ...Ne8 would do. }
12. Ba3
{ I first analyzed the alternative  12.Nd2  , with the idea to influence  the dark squares on the queenside by Nb3. At the beginning, that looked very promising. But after many days of work, I finally found a way for Black to achieve a position with roughly half a pawn unit disadvantage and no winning chances whatsoever. Even with pincers, I wouldn't touch this with Black.  For most White repertoires, such a line would have been perfectly okay, but it would have forced me to abandon the '+/- - paradigm'. Hence, I decided to look at the text move, and fortunately, I liked what I saw. }
12... Ra8
{ Black has a large variety of alternatives, but after all of them there follows Bb4 Ra8. In order to unify the material, I decided to execute both moves at the beginning, thus establishing the tabiya after Bb4. }
13. Bb4 Bh6
{ By covering the square g5, Black wants to avoid the problems he faces after ...f5 and Ng5. The bishop appears to be more active on h6, but in reality, it doesn't manage to influence White's further development much. Its absence from g7 will reduce Black's dynamic options. }
14. a5
{ We have seen this move many times before. By suppressing Black's b-pawn, White not only fixes it as a weakness, he also improves his chances in the fight for the key square c5. }
14... f5 15. Bd3
{ The bishop fortifies the point e4 and at the same time exerts pressure on Black's f-pawn. }
15... Kh8
{ The king is dodging potential problems on the a2-g8 diagonal and vacates the square g8 for the knight. }
16. Re1
{ One of the characteristics of the Bayonet Attack is the combination of central actions with play on the wings. The rook gives additional support to the key square e4, but is also setting his sight on Black's e-pawn. We mustn't forget, that the center right now is more dynamic than static, with the advance c4-c5 hanging in the air. }
16... Nf6 { This is similar to 15. ..Nf6. } 17. c5 fxe4 18. Bxe4 Bg4
{ The bishop will be challenged here by the h-pawn. If it retreats, the extra move h2-h3 will be in White's favor. }
19. cxd6 cxd6 20. h3 Nxe4
{ 20...Bf5  21.Nd2  Rc8  22.Bf3  Qd7  23.Ra2  Bd3  24.Rb2  Nf5  This is a remarkable position. It looks like Black is getting his fair share with his pieces pretty actively placed. But appearances are deceptive. In reality, they don't have a lot of impact and what remains are weak pawns on b7 and d6 plus a vulnerable king.  25.Nde4  Bxe4  26.Nxe4  Nxe4  27.Bxe4  Nd4  28.Qd3  Black is probably losing, here. }
21. hxg4 Nxc3 22. Bxc3 Rc8 23. Qb3 Rf4
{ 23...Nxd5  Opening the d-file isn't very attractive for Black, as it exposes both, Black's king and queen.  24.Bb2  Rc5   24...Nf4  25.Rad1  25...Bg7  26.Nxe5+-  25.Red1  Nf4  26.Qxb7+- }
24. a6 bxa6 25. Rxa6 Bg7 26. Ng5
{ 0-1 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Pavlov, O-Kurbanov,R RCCA corr 2002. } *

