{ 18.Ra3  happened in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@63@@EndBracket@@ Atalik, S @@StartBracket@@2607@@EndBracket@@ -Erdogdu, M @@StartBracket@@2448@@EndBracket@@ Kalamaria 2010. }
18... fxe4
{ 18...Ndf6  19.c5!  fxe4  20.Bxe4  Nxe4  21.Rxe4  Nf6  Black won the battle for the square e4. But one square is not enough to win a game of chess.  22.Rh4!  Bf8  23.cxd6  cxd6  24.Ng5  Rg7  25.Qf3  Bf5  26.Rc4+-  followed by Rac1 and Ne6. }
19. Bxe4 Ngf6 { The problem is that White's bishop doesn't have to move. } 20.
c5
{ It's always the same. Black might get away with his vulnerable king and passive pieces as long as the position is closed. Hence, ripping it open is always worth a pawn, and a doubled pawn even more so. }
20... dxc5 21. Bd2 Bxd2 22. Qxd2 Rf8 23. Ng5 Nxe4
