[White "8) 9.b4 a5 10.bxa5 Rxa5 11.a4 Sidelines"]
[Black "11.a4 c5 12.Ra3 Kh8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ This is the second most frequent continuation. By challenging White's b-pawn, Black starts a fight over the critical c5-square.   We have already seen this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8+=  . In our variations, the knight will appear on  d7  , which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4
{ Now, Black has many different options. We will have a look at  11...Nd7  ,  11...c5  ,  11...b6  , and  11...Ne8  . }
11... c5
{ This structure was already covered two times in the 9.b4 Nh5 move order, one time with Black playing the knight to f4 and one time with the knight staying on h5.   The present version can be considered slightly better for Black in comparison, as the knight tends to be misplaced on the axis h5-f4. My recommendation in those previous chapters was to retreat with the knight to e8, all the way from f4, if necessary.   Now, the question is, whether the extra tempi Black enjoys in this very situation are of great value to him. Let me give the answer right at the beginning. I don't see many benefits for Black as the only active idea is to play ...f7-f5. This idea is, however, flawed, as it opens up the position in a sector, where White has considerably more firepower. }
12. Ra3 Kh8
{ The idea of playing ...Nfg8 and ...Bh6 offers Black a chance to avoid getting trapped in endings with a bad King's Indian bishop.   Then again, this bishop will often be a useful defender, be it for the king or for the weak d-pawn. As I am not one hundred percent sure what to think of this exchange, I would choose a pragmatic approach and stick to the rule: 'Never change a winning team!' Hence, I would simply prevent this exchange, in order to obtain a position, which I already know is good for me. }
13. Bd2
{ 13.Re1  was played in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@ Kalod, R @@StartBracket@@2490@@EndBracket@@-Lanka, Z @@StartBracket@@2507@@EndBracket@@ Czechia 2001. }
13... Nfg8 14. Nb5 Ra6 15. Qc1 { No ...Bh6 in the near future. } 15... f5 16.
exf5 gxf5
{ 16...Nxf5  17.Ng5  Nf6  18.Re1+-  is positionally lost, if you take into account piece activity, king safety and weaknesses.  After  18...h6?  White would answer  19.Ne6  and  probably exploit the weak pawns on h6 and g6. }
17. g3
{ The pawn is controlling two important squares and creates a hole for the light-squared bishop. }
17... f4 { That's a pawn sacrifice, in order to generate some activity. } 18.
gxf4 Ng6 19. fxe5 dxe5 20. Bg5 Qd7 21. Kh1
{ There is no real danger for the king, as there are six 'defenders' nearby. }
21... Nf6 { 21...Nf4  22.Bxf4  Rxf4  23.Ng5  Rg6  24.Rg3+- } 22. Qe1
{ Releasing the rook from its defensive duties.  22.Rg1?  would be met by  22...Ng4=  . }
22... Qf5 { 22...Ne4  23.Rg1  Qf7  24.Bd1  Bf5  25.Re3+- } 23. Rg1 Ng4 24. h3
Nh6 25. Bf1 { Black has no compensation for the pawn. } *

