12. Ra3 Ra6 { 12...Ne8  13.Bd2  Ra6  14.Nb5  transposes. } 13. Bd2
{ I stick to the same recipe as in the previous chapters with that structure. Every game, deviating from that master plan can be ignored. }
13... Kh8 14. Qc1
{ That stifles Black's idea outright. There is nothing wrong with  14.Re1  ,  in order to play Qc1 only after ...Bh6 has been prepared,  for instance by  14...Nfg8  . }
14... Nfg8 15. Re1
{ In the high class encounter ½-½ @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@-Grischuk, A @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@ chess. com INT 2020, the game continued  15.Kh1  h6  16.Ne1  , which was not the best setup for White, though. }
15... f5
{ 15...Bd7  If Black stays passive, White will improve his position in the first step.  16.Bd1  b6  17.Bc2  Ra8  18.Nb5  Nc8  19.h3  In the second step he will penetrate the queenside by executing a4-a5. }
16. exf5 Nxf5 17. Nb5 Nd4
{ 17...Bh6  18.Ng5+-  White doesn't let the exchange of bishops happen just like that. Now, the knight on g5 is very annoying for Black, as capturing it with the bishop would leave Black weak on the dark squares. }
18. Nbxd4 cxd4 19. Bd3
{ Amongst others, this freezes the h-pawn, so that Ng5 cannot be prevented. }
19... Ra8 { Anticipating c4-c5. } 20. a5
{ Black was prepared to play ...b6, to stop White from playing c5. } 20... Nf6
21. Ng5
{ White has two strong pawn breaks at his disposal: f2-f4 and c4-c5. If he was allowed to play some extra moves, he would probably play h3, Rb3-b6, and then strike with his pawns. }
