{ This structure was already covered two times in the 9.b4 Nh5 move order, one time with Black playing the knight to f4 and one time with the knight staying on h5.   The present version can be considered slightly better for Black in comparison, as the knight tends to be misplaced on the axis h5-f4. My recommendation in those previous chapters was to retreat with the knight to e8, all the way from f4, if necessary.   Now, the question is, whether the extra tempi Black enjoys in this very situation are of great value to him. Let me give the answer right at the beginning. I don't see many benefits for Black as the only active idea is to play ...f7-f5. This idea is, however, flawed, as it opens up the position in a sector, where White has considerably more firepower. }
12. Ra3 Ra6 { 12...Ne8  13.Bd2  Ra6  14.Nb5  transposes. } 13. Bd2
{ I stick to the same recipe as in the previous chapters with that structure. Every game, deviating from that master plan can be ignored. }
13... Ne8 14. Nb5 h6 15. Qc1
{ It appears logical to force the king to h7, as it could be exposed on the b1-h7 diagonal after a consecutive ...f7-f5. }
15... Kh7 16. Bd3 f5
{ It's now or never. Everything else would give White the opportunity to further improve his position. }
17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Be2
{ It may be a bit counter intuitive to abandon the diagonal, but there is no way for Black to maintain the bishop on f5. White will simply play Nh4 on most of Black's moves. }
18... Bd7
{ 18...e4  19.Nh4  Bd7  20.Qc2  Nf6  21.f3+-  Black clearly lacks space for defending his kingside and the queen's rook is out of play. }
19. Nh4
{ Even after the bishop withdrew to safety, the knight is moving to h4. Its mission is to unblock the f-pawn and to clear the 3rd rank for the rook. }
19... Nf5 20. Nxf5 gxf5 21. Kh1
{ White will soon be able to use both pawns, the f-pawn and the g-pawn as a battering ram, in order to increase the scope of his pieces.   It would be very time-consuming for me and confusing for you, if I would present a comprehensive analysis of this position. I deem it a good idea, however, to show some representative lines, instead. }
21... Qe7 22. a5 Ra8
{ Black can only wait, as every move of his pawn duo on the kingside would provide White with a hook to open up the position.   22...e4  23.f3  Ra8  24.fxe4  fxe4  25.Bf4+-  There are too many weaknesses in Black's position, including his majesty himself.   22...f4  23.Bd3+  Kh8  24.Rg1  Nf6  25.f3  Nh5  26.Be1+-  White will combine ideas like playing in the b-file, transferring the knight to e4 and pushing the g-pawn to realize his advantage. }
23. f3 Ra6 24. Rg1 h5
{ Black does his best to prevent White from playing g2-g4. } 25. f4 h4 26. Qe1
b6 { Counterplay is Black's only chance. } 27. Bd1 { Pinning the e-pawn. }
27... bxa5 28. g4
{ Time for action. White wants to continue with gxf5 Bxf5 on the subsequent move. }
28... fxg4 { 28...Kg8  29.gxf5  Bxf5  30.Re3  Kh7  31.Rg5+- } 29. Bxg4 Bxg4 30.
Rxg4 Kg8 31. Rg5
{ Controlling the square f5 and shielding Black's queen off from the h-pawn. }
31... a4 32. f5 Qd7 { 32...Ra8  33.Rh3+-  intending Qxh4 followed by Qh7. } 33.
Rf3 a3 { Black is looking for counterplay, as his kingside is undefendable. }
34. Nxa3 Qb7 35. Nb5 Ra2 36. Qxh4 { Not the only move, but the best. } 36...
Rxd2 37. Rh3
{ The main threat is  38.Qh8+  Kf7  39.Rxg7  Nxg7  40.Nxd6  with mate following soon. }
37... Rxd5 38. Qh7+ Kf7 39. Qg6+ Ke7 { 39...Kg8  40.Qe6+  Qf7  41.cxd5+- } 40.
Qe6+ Kd8 41. Qxd5
{ And White is clearly winning. Black is forced to exchange queens, after which White's two rooks will dominate the position. }
