[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ This is the second most frequent continuation. By challenging White's b-pawn, Black starts a fight over the critical c5-square.   We have already seen this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8+=  . In our variations, the knight will appear on  d7  , which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4
{ Now, Black has many different options. We will have a look at  11...Nd7  ,  11...c5  ,  11...b6  , and  11...Ne8  . }
11... b6
{ Given the experience we already accumulated, the move itself doesn't need any explanation. It should be noted that we can't force a transposition after  11...Nd7  12.Ba3  Ra8  13.Bb4  as Black can deviate from playing  b6  with many reasonable moves. }
12. Nd2 Ra8
{ Other moves generally transpose to the main line.   12...c5  13.dxc6  Nxc6  14.Nb3  Ra8  15.Be3  see main line.   12...Nd7  13.Nb3  Ra8  14.a5  see main line. }
13. Nb3 c5 { Black chooses to prevent a5. } 14. dxc6
{ You can make a mental note that  14.Bd2  , with the idea of Ra3, Qa1 and a5 is a decent plan B. However, I think it is less strong and we don't really need an alternative, here. }
14... Nxc6 15. Be3 Be6
{ Both parties have two weak pawns, but White is in a better position to exploit these deficiencies, as he commands more space. }
16. Qd2
{ In order to acknowledge this novelty, you must be aware of the following line:  16.f3?  Nd7!N  17.Qxd6?  @@StartBracket@@  17.Qd2  only gives White a slight edge.@@EndBracket@@  Nd4  18.Nxd4??  @@StartBracket@@  18.Bxd4  =@@EndBracket@@  18...exd4  19.Bxd4  Qb8!  20.Qxb8  Bxd4+  -+ This intermediate check was made possible by the flawed  16.f3  . }
16... Qe7 17. f3
{ Another subtle move is needed here, as after  17.Rfd1  Black defends actively with  17...Rfc8!  , leaving both pawns hanging. Now,  18.Bxb6  is answered by  18...Rab8  19.Qe3  Nb4  and on  18.Qxd6  , there follows  18....Qxd6  19.Rxd6  Bf8  20.Rd2  Nb4  , with a satisfactory position in both cases. By overprotecting the e-pawn, White prepares  18.Nd5  . }
17... Nd7 { 17...Rfc8?  18.Nd5  Bxd5  19.cxd5+- } 18. Nd5 Bxd5
{ Black sacrifices a pawn in order to liberate himself.   18...Qd8  19.Rfb1  f5  20.Bg5  Nf6  21.Bd3±  Obviously, White has the more active position and can be proud of his centralized knight. }
19. cxd5 Nd4 20. Nxd4 exd4 21. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 22. Qxd4 f5
{ White has to be careful not to end up with a weak extra pawn on e4 and a bad bishop. }
23. Bb5 Nc5 24. e5 { A beautifully dynamic move. } 24... Nb3
{ 24...dxe5  25.d6  Qe6  26.Qd2  Kg7  27.Rad1  Rfd8  28.d7+-  Black is paralyzed by White's passed pawn. }
25. Qb2 Nxa1 26. e6 { A silent intermediate move. } 26... Qg7
{ 26...Rfc8  27.Rxa1  Rc5  28.Bc6  Ra6  29.Re1+-  The winning plan is to open a second front with moves such as g3, Kf2, Re2, Qb4, h4 and h5, when Black's defenses will be overtaxed. }
27. Qxa1 Qxa1 28. Rxa1 Ra7
{ 28...Rfc8  The line  29.Re1  Kf8  30.e7+  Kf7  31.e8=Q++-  is leading to a won pawn ending. }
29. Re1
{ Deflecting the rook from the a-file, so that Bc4 would be possible at some stage, after the d-pawn has fallen. }
29... Re7 30. Rc1 Kg7 31. Rc6 { Taking another pawn. White is winning. } *

