{ Given the experience we already accumulated, the move itself doesn't need any explanation. It should be noted that we can't force a transposition after  11...Nd7  12.Ba3  Ra8  13.Bb4  as Black can deviate from playing  b6  with many reasonable moves. }
12. Nd2 Ra8
{ Other moves generally transpose to the main line.   12...c5  13.dxc6  Nxc6  14.Nb3  Ra8  15.Be3  see main line.   12...Nd7  13.Nb3  Ra8  14.a5  see main line. }
13. Nb3 Nd7 { That's the most frequent move, but apparently not the best. } 14.
a5 Ba6 15. axb6 cxb6 16. Be3
{ The unhappy bishop on a6 is not only out of play, but will sometimes make a nice target. }
16... f5 17. Qc2 { 17.f3 has been played, but that's not necessary. } 17...
fxe4 18. g4 { Restricting the knight on e7, as usual. } 18... Nf6 19. Nxe4 Nxe4
20. Qxe4 { Black has a majorminor piece problem ;-@@EndBracket@@ } 20... Bb7
21. Rxa8 Bxa8 22. Ra1 Kh8 23. Ra7 b5 { He's doing his best to solve it. } 24.
Nd2 bxc4 25. Bxc4 Ng8 26. h3 Nf6 27. Qd3 Qb8 28. Ba2 Bb7
{ This bishop can become a target in different ways.   28...Qb2?  29.g5  Nh5  30.Qa6+- }
29. g5
{ By driving the knight away from the center White liberates his queen from its defensive duties. }
29... Nh5 30. Qb1 Rf7
{ 30...Ba8  31.Qxb8  Now, Black's d-pawn becomes weak.  31...Rxb8  32.Rd7  Bf8  33.Ne4  Rb2  34.Nf6  Nxf6  35.gxf6  Rb8  36.f4  exf4  37.Bd4  With the big threat of  f7+  Black cannot prevent White's bishop from conquering the g-pawn. }
31. Ne4 Bf8 32. Bc4
{ White is netting material due to the cross-pin of Black's bishop. } 32... Qc8
33. Ba6 Bxa6 34. Rxf7
{ And although the position appears complex, White is clearly winning, Qb6 being the main threat. }
