1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 a5
{ This is the second most frequent continuation. By challenging White's b-pawn, Black starts a fight over the critical c5-square.   We have already seen this motive in different forms after  9...Nh5  . In my opinion, there is not much point in deferring this pawn-break. If Black wants to include it in his strategy, he should play it right now, on move  9. }
10. bxa5
{ The alternative  10.Ba3  has been played twice as often. However, White can only achieve a slight advantage, if Black continues in the most accurate fashion. One possible line would be  10...b6  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Bb4  Ra8  13.a4  Ne8+=  . In our variations, the knight will appear on  d7  , which is inferior from Black's point of view. }
10... Rxa5 11. a4
{ Now, Black has many different options. We will have a look at  11...Nd7  ,  11...c5  ,  11...b6  , and  11...Ne8  . }
11... b6
{ Given the experience we already accumulated, the move itself doesn't need any explanation. It should be noted that we can't force a transposition after  11...Nd7  12.Ba3  Ra8  13.Bb4  as Black can deviate from playing  b6  with many reasonable moves. }
12. Nd2 Ra8
{ Other moves generally transpose to the main line.   12...c5  13.dxc6  Nxc6  14.Nb3  Ra8  15.Be3  see main line.   12...Nd7  13.Nb3  Ra8  14.a5  see main line. }
13. Nb3 Nd7 { That's the most frequent move, but apparently not the best. } 14.
a5 Ba6 15. axb6 cxb6 16. Be3
{ The unhappy bishop on a6 is not only out of play, but will sometimes make a nice target. }
16... Qc7 17. Qc2
{ 17.Rxa6  Rxa6  18.c5  Raa8  19.c6  is also winning. But as a chess coach I know, that my students normally prefer conservative solutions. }
17... Nc5 18. Nxc5 bxc5 19. Ra4 Bb7 20. Nb5 Qd7 21. Rfa1 Rxa4 22. Rxa4
{ Black is lost in the long run. Trying to neutralize White's rook would lose outright: }
22... Ra8 23. Rxa8+ Bxa8 24. Qa2 Bb7 25. Qa7 Nc8 26. Qb8 Bf8 27. h3 h5 28. g4
{ Clearing the g4-square for the bishop. The immediate  28.Nc7  doesn't work, as Black can still play  28...Be7  29.Qxb7  Bd8  . }
28... hxg4 29. Nc7 Be7 30. Qxb7 Bd8 31. Bxg4 f5 32. exf5 gxf5 33. Bxf5 Qxf5 34.
Ne6
{ Not only threatening two minor pieces but also threatening checkmate on g7. Too many threats for Black to survive. }
