{ If you compare this move with  11...Nd7  , you easily recognize its pros and cons. Obviously, the drawback of this move is that it doesn't influence  the key c5-square. On the positive side we see the following aspects:   1@@EndBracket@@ The light-squared bishop is not hemmed. Amongst others, this affects the control of the square e6, which is relevant in positions, where White reacts to ...f7-f5 with the sortie Ng5-e6.  2@@EndBracket@@ The neuralgic points d6 and c7 are defended in case White plays c4-c5.  3@@EndBracket@@ The knight can be played to the strong square d6, after the sequence c4-c5 cxd5.   It looks like the upside is bigger than the downside, at least from a quantitative perspective. While this is true, this observation doesn't allow us an abstract judgement, as we have no idea of the qualitative side. Theoretically, one aspect @@StartBracket@@in this case the neglect of the square c5@@EndBracket@@ can outweigh several others, if it is more relevant. At the end of the day, you have to put in the hours and perform concrete analysis, in order to arrive at a clear result. After I did exactly that, I came to the following conclusion.  11...Ne8  is an interesting move, as it performs better after all continuations that have been tried in practice, compared to its sister move  11...Nd7  .  In all these lines, White achieves an advantage slightly above 0.5 pawn units, which means a slight advantage, bordering a large one. Not a bad result for a White repertoire, but alas, only subpar in the context of the Bayonet. So far, I succeeded with claiming a clear advantage in every line. Would  11...Ne8  turn out to be the Grinch, spoiling my +/- - paradigm? Luckily, I found a strong novelty in the very next move, allowing me to maintain my claim. }
12. Be3
{ We haven't seen this move in any previous line at such an early stage. The reason for this are many fold, depending on the concrete position. One reason is that it doesn't help to push a4-a5, which is necessary after Black played ...b6. The other reason is exposure. On e3 it is in the sphere of Black's f-pawn @@StartBracket@@...f5-f4 would be lethal with a White knight on d2@@EndBracket@@ and the knights @@StartBracket@@...Nf6-g4, ...Ne7-f5@@EndBracket@@. For me, this explains its novelty status. People simply don't take it into account. It's 'something you don't play in this position type'. But from a logical point of view, it does make sense, indeed. In contrast to other lines, Black neglected the square c5 and this is, where our move places its focus on.   Let me put a disclaimer right at the beginning. If you choose this move, you must be willing to engage in small material investments. No big deal in my view, but a potential issue for some. Therefore, I will briefly present alternatives, so nobody will be forced to leave his or her comfort zone.   12.Ba3  b6  13.Bb4  Ra8  14.h3  f5  15.a5  bxa5  16.Bxa5  Nf6  17.Bd3  fxe4  18.Nxe4  Nf5⩲  This position is acceptable for White, as he has potential play against Black's queenside structure.   12.Bd2!?  This was only played two times, but the idea of supporting the a-pawn is logical.  12...b6  13.Nb5  Ra8  14.a5  bxa5  15.Rxa5  Bd7  16.Rxa8  Qxa8  17.Qa1  Qd8  18.Nc3  f5  19.Rb1  Nf6  20.Bd3⩲  White again has chances to exploit Black's vulnerable queenside structure.   12.Nd2  f5  13.Nb3  Ra8  14.f3  fxe4Ν  If it wasn't for this novelty, White would end up clearly better.  15.fxe4  Rxf1+  16.Bxf1  b6  17.Be3⩲  Black cannot prevent White from playing a5 at some stage. But he has counterplay, based on the weakness of the pawn e4 and the square g4. }
12... c5 13. Bd2
{ I guess, it is the simplest solution to play the line 11.a4  c5  with a tempo down, as we already know, that this structure is very pleasant for White. The alternative  13.dxc6  bxc6  14.Nd2  Ra8  15.Nb3  also looks promising. }
13... Ra6 14. Ra3
{ If Black wants to exploit the extra tempo, he has to play a quick ...f7-f5. }
14... h6
{ 14...f5  15.Ng5±  leads to structures and motives, which have been examined before. }
15. Bd3 f5 16. exf5 { Otherwise, Black would continue with ...f4. } 16... Nxf5
{ Black misses the chance to challenge White's strong light-squared bishop after this capture. }
17. h3 Nf6
{ 17...Bd7  18.Qb3  b6  19.Ne4  Nf6  20.g4!  The knight has to be removed, in order to exploit the weak g-pawn.  20...Ne7  21.Nxf6+  Rxf6  22.Be4  The square e4 is not only attractive for a knight. This bishop is a mighty piece.  22...Rf8  23.Rfa1+-  As usual, Black's position is a conglomerate of weaknesses and passive pieces. }
18. g4 Ne7 19. Qe2 Bd7 20. Rb1 b6 21. Nh2 Kh8 22. Bc2
{ Clearing the 3rd rank for the rook. } 22... Be8 23. Nf1
{ White's pieces are extraordinarily active. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 9.b4 Ne8 10.a4 f5"]
[Black "11.a5 Nf6 12.Bg5 f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Ne8
{ This is one of the most aggressive variations against the Bayonet Attack. Black plans to unroll the typical King's Indian pawn storm by playing ...f7-f5-f4, followed by ...g6-g5-g4.   In contrast to  9...Nh5  , Black won't have any problems with an exposed knight. The downside is, however, that the text move doesn't come with a threat and allows White to unfold his own agenda without delay. }
10. a4
{ I decided to recommend this move instead of the mainline  10.c5  for reasons, related to the metagame. Our move is less sharp and doesn't involve so many sub-variations. Actually, it has only been played 281 times, opposed to the 1335 games with the database mainline. Instead of trying to directly attack Black's queenside and let him have his way on the kingside, we neutralize his kingside play and bank on our structural advantage. In the long-term, the position will play itself. }
10... f5
{ 10...a5  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Be3  transposes to a line we've seen before. } 11.
a5
{ Gaining space on the queenside is the basic idea of the Bayonet and needs no further explanation. }
11... Nf6 12. Bg5
{ If we learn a new opening, we try to observe where the pieces typically belong. At this point, through pattern recognition, we can apply the collected knowledge of lines we have learned previously. This in turn will help us to deduct the right moves in variations we still have to study.  In this position, honestly, I wouldn't have guessed the text move. Simply put, this is because I didn't see it in all the lines we have met so far. Furthermore, I am normally not inclined to put my precious dark-squared bishop at risk. There is logic behind this deviation from previous variations, the bishop is not needed anymore to make progress on the dark squares of the queenside.  Now, the focus must be on suppressing Black's ambitions on the kingside, and it is exactly this, what the move is supposed to achieve. If White would continue with the more common  12.Nd2  , Black would be able to equalize after  12...f4  13.c5  g5  14.f3  Ng6  15.Nc4  Rf7  16.Ba3  Bf8  17.b5  dxc5!  . }
12... f4
{ Insisting on the originally intended pawn storm is bound to fail, as the bishop on g5 prevents Black from getting the light squares under control. }
13. c5
{ This is more flexible than immediately deciding about the destination of the king's knight by playing  13.Nd2  , which happened in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Xiu, D @@StartBracket@@2532@@EndBracket@@-Mikes, J @@StartBracket@@2253@@EndBracket@@ Prague 2017. }
13... h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. h3 g5 16. Nh2
{ Obviously, our dark-squared bishop gave up its life for a good purpose. Black won't be able to overcome the light-squared barrier. }
