a5
{ Gaining space on the queenside is the basic idea of the Bayonet and needs no further explanation. }
11... Nf6 12. Bg5
{ If we learn a new opening, we try to observe where the pieces typically belong. At this point, through pattern recognition, we can apply the collected knowledge of lines we have learned previously. This in turn will help us to deduct the right moves in variations we still have to study.  In this position, honestly, I wouldn't have guessed the text move. Simply put, this is because I didn't see it in all the lines we have met so far. Furthermore, I am normally not inclined to put my precious dark-squared bishop at risk. There is logic behind this deviation from previous variations, the bishop is not needed anymore to make progress on the dark squares of the queenside.  Now, the focus must be on suppressing Black's ambitions on the kingside, and it is exactly this, what the move is supposed to achieve. If White would continue with the more common  12.Nd2  , Black would be able to equalize after  12...f4  13.c5  g5  14.f3  Ng6  15.Nc4  Rf7  16.Ba3  Bf8  17.b5  dxc5!  . }
12... h6 13. Bxf6 Rxf6 14. Nd2
{ The knight helps stabilizing the point e4, so that the queen's knight can keep on protecting the d-pawn after the advance c4-c5. }
14... fxe4
{ Strictly speaking the best Black can do is to maintain the tension in the center. Black should avoid inviting White's knight to occupy the key e4-square. In almost any case, White would continue with c5, claiming a clear advantage. }
15. Ndxe4 Rf7
{ 15...Rf8  16.c5  Bf5?  1-0 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Hollan,M @@StartBracket@@2210@@EndBracket@@-Rastocny,J @@StartBracket@@2098@@EndBracket@@ Kouty nad Desnou 2018  17.a6  b6  18.cxd6  cxd6  19.f3+-  .  The threat of 20.Nb5 is devastating,  as  19...Bxe4  ,  allowing White's bishop to g4, can hardly be called an option. }
16. c5 Nf5
{ Of course, ...fxe4 was played with the intention to activate the knight, which now has the square d4 within reach and also protects the d-pawn. However, evaluating both knights leads us to the conclusion that the e4-knight is stronger, as it influences more important squares and sits on an outpost, whereas Black's knight can be pushed away by g2-g4 in a suitable moment. }
17. a6
{ Securing the square b5 for the knight by blocking Black's a-pawn is a recurring motif. }
17... b6 18. Nb5 Bf8
{ 18...bxc5  19.bxc5  Kh7  20.Bc4Ν  .  In 1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Peigney,C @@StartBracket@@2325@@EndBracket@@-Larsen,A @@StartBracket@@2091@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2014, White closed the position with 20.c6, which was not necessary and hence less flexible.  20...Bf8  21.Qd2+-  Black suffers from passive pieces and weak spots, as usual. }
19. Bc4
{ I like this move better than  19.Bd3  , which was chosen in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@ Andriuschenko, N @@StartBracket@@2417@@EndBracket@@-Nekhaev, A @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015, as it doesn't give Black the opportunity to fish in muddy waters with  19...bxc5  20.bxc5  dxc5  . }
19... Kh8 20. Qd2 Bd7 21. c6 Bc8 22. Ra3
{ Black's position might be already lost, as the lack of space and the paralyzing knight on b5 diminish his defensive abilities on the kingside. }
