a5
{ Gaining space on the queenside is the basic idea of the Bayonet and needs no further explanation. }
11... Nf6 12. Bg5
{ If we learn a new opening, we try to observe where the pieces typically belong. At this point, through pattern recognition, we can apply the collected knowledge of lines we have learned previously. This in turn will help us to deduct the right moves in variations we still have to study.  In this position, honestly, I wouldn't have guessed the text move. Simply put, this is because I didn't see it in all the lines we have met so far. Furthermore, I am normally not inclined to put my precious dark-squared bishop at risk. There is logic behind this deviation from previous variations, the bishop is not needed anymore to make progress on the dark squares of the queenside.  Now, the focus must be on suppressing Black's ambitions on the kingside, and it is exactly this, what the move is supposed to achieve. If White would continue with the more common  12.Nd2  , Black would be able to equalize after  12...f4  13.c5  g5  14.f3  Ng6  15.Nc4  Rf7  16.Ba3  Bf8  17.b5  dxc5!  . }
12... Nh5
{ Obviously, the knight is heading towards f4. At the same time, there is the threat of ...h6, as exchanging the bishop for the passive knight on e7 is no attractive prospect. As the two best options for White are similar in value, I decided to present both of them. }
13. Qd2 { White prevents ...h6 and also clears the square d1 for the bishop. }
13... fxe4 { 13...Nf4  14.Bd1  most likely transposes. } 14. Nxe4 Nf4 15. Bd1
h6 16. Bxf4
{ Finally, the queen's bishop has to leave the board, but it does so, by exchanging Black's most active piece, which was charged with no less than five tempi. }
16... exf4
{ This way of recapturing liberates the bishop, but on the other hand, White receives good prospects on the e-file. Moreover, Black's f-pawn is exposed and if it is defended by ...g6-g5, more light squares will be weakened. }
17. Rc1 Nf5 18. c5 b6 19. Re1 bxc5 20. bxc5 Rb8
{ That's the most active setup for Black. } 21. Bc2 Rb2 22. h3 Qd7
{ 22...Kh7  23.Qd3+-  Black has many weaknesses and insufficient pawn protection for his king. White may continue with Qc4 and Bd3 in order to build up the pressure on the c-file. }
23. Nc3 Qf7 24. cxd6 cxd6 25. Rb1 Qb7 26. Ne2 g5 27. Nfd4
{ Black's kingside stands wide open. } *

