1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Nd7
{ This way of unblocking the f-pawn is less popular than  9...Ne8  . My explanation for this is that it has no advantages  in comparison, but provides White with more good options. The idea to prevent c4-c5 is only effective for one move.  Already after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppnnpbp/3p2p1/3Pp3/1PP1P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.a4  f5  , White can continue with  11.c5  which is quite attractive for White.   My recommendation against  9...Nd7  is straightforward and based on the laws of economics. As we are able to play the same variation as against  9...Ne8  , this is exactly what we are going to do. No time wasted. I will briefly present the alternatives for those, who are not happy with my recommendation against  9...Ne8  or who love to study the full spectrum of the Bayonet Attack. Apart from that, I will analyze the offbeat opportunities for Black to deviate, and then, I will call it a day. No need to give  9...Nd7  more attention than it deserves. }
10. a4 f5 11. a5 h6 12. Nd2 h5
{ Apparently, Black is engaging in the standard king's indian pawnstorm. His unusual move order derives from two assumptions, as it seems. First of all, he believes that leaving the knight on  d7  would deter White from playing c4-c5. Secondly, he appears to be afraid of  12...f4  13.Bg4  . }
13. c5
