1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 c6
{ This is a rather defensive approach. By establishing central tension, Black wants to prevent White from executing the standard c4-c5 advance. The game will most likely lead to a structure, which we already met in several sections and perceived as very favorable for White. }
10. a4
{ Another popular line is  10.dxc6  . Personally, I don't like the idea of granting Black more space, when the alternative is to simply maintain the status quo, in which his pieces are well confined by our pawns. After  10...Nxc6  11.Rb1  Bg4  12.Be3  Rc8  13.a4  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Nd4  15.Be2  a5  White has some advantage, but might be worried by the specter of the draw, manifested by Black's control of the dark squares. }
10... Bd7 11. Ra3
{ Prophylactic thinking. After  11.a5  cxd5  12.cxd5  Rc8  13.Bd2  Black obtains the chance to perform a prison break by sacrificing the exchange.  13...Rxc3  14.Bxc3  Nxe4  15.Bb2  Nf6  . This position is still favorable for White, but the increase of disorder has improved Black's practical chances. }
11... Rc8 12. Bd3
{ As the points c3 and e4 are well protected, now, Black's position will remain passive. }
*

