1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 c6
{ This is a rather defensive approach. By establishing central tension, Black wants to prevent White from executing the standard c4-c5 advance. The game will most likely lead to a structure, which we already met in several sections and perceived as very favorable for White. }
10. a4
{ Another popular line is  10.dxc6  . Personally, I don't like the idea of granting Black more space, when the alternative is to simply maintain the status quo, in which his pieces are well confined by our pawns. After  10...Nxc6  11.Rb1  Bg4  12.Be3  Rc8  13.a4  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Nd4  15.Be2  a5  White has some advantage, but might be worried by the specter of the draw, manifested by Black's control of the dark squares. }
10... a5 11. bxa5 Rxa5
{ This has only been played in a couple of games. The difference to main line is not significant. }
12. Ra3
{ As none of the game continuations appeared convincing to me, I propose a novelty right here. The square a3 has proved to be the rook's natural habitat in most of the lines we already dealt with. The key to this position is to play similar to the structure with Black's pawn on c5. As ...cxd5 is no sound option for Black, he will often have to continue with ...c6-c5 in order to stabilize his position. }
12... Ne8 13. Bd2 Ra8 14. Qb3
{ This is a prophylactic measure against Black's only active idea, which is ...f7-f5. It also invites the king's rook to participate, most likely by moving to b1. }
14... f5 15. Ng5
{ Now we see, why the queen is placed very effectively on b3. } 15... h6 16. c5
hxg5 17. dxc6+ d5 18. cxb7 Bxb7 19. Qxb7 Rb8
{ 19...fxe4  20.Nxe4!  dxe4  21.Bc4+  Rf7   21...Kh8?  22.Rh3  mate.  22.Rb1+-  Black's minor pieces are incapable to deal with White's passed pawns. }
20. Qa6 Rf6 21. Qd3 fxe4 22. Qc2
{ Black's center might look impressive at first glance, but is neither mobile nor effective. White will push the a-pawn or put pressure on Black's d-pawn by means of Qa2 and Rd1. }
