1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 c6
{ This is a rather defensive approach. By establishing central tension, Black wants to prevent White from executing the standard c4-c5 advance. The game will most likely lead to a structure, which we already met in several sections and perceived as very favorable for White. }
10. a4
{ Another popular line is  10.dxc6  . Personally, I don't like the idea of granting Black more space, when the alternative is to simply maintain the status quo, in which his pieces are well confined by our pawns. After  10...Nxc6  11.Rb1  Bg4  12.Be3  Rc8  13.a4  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Nd4  15.Be2  a5  White has some advantage, but might be worried by the specter of the draw, manifested by Black's control of the dark squares. }
10... a5 11. bxa5 Qxa5 12. Bd2 c5
{ This is the most frequent continuation. Of course, Black can also try to keep the structure fluid. }
13. Nb5
{ This structure was already covered in previous chapters and evaluated as very good for White. Theoretically, I could have stopped here, referring to these elaborations. But of course, that would have been unsatisfactory, as every single line deserves to be narrated comprehensively.  As this position is closed and more about general plans, it doesn't take us by surprise that White has many alternatives available, all potentially leading to the same recommended setup by transposition. To this end, White could also start with moves such as Ra3, Qc2, or Bd3, of which all have been actually tested. I decided to opt for the text move, simply because the following game was less flawed than all the rest. }
13... Qd8 14. Bd3 Nh5
{ Everybody who studied the previous material is hardly intimidated by this move. But it should have become clear, that a more restrained continuation such as  14...Ne8  also wouldn't manage to solve the problems of the position. }
15. Ra3
{ There is no need for  15.Re1  , as the bishop can simply drop back to c2 from where it stands. }
15... Ra6 16. Re1 f5
{ For the majority of chess players it is difficult to wait and do nothing. This is even more true for King's Indian player, who is biased towards active play. Pushing the f-pawn is what he has learned, pushing the f-pawn is what he will normally do. }
17. exf5 Nxf5 { 17...gxf5  18.Nxe5+- } 18. Ng5
{ Now, g4 is a threat, but  18.g4?  would have been strongly met by  18...Nh4  . }
18... Bf6
{ 18...Nf4?  19.Bxf4  exf4  20.Ne6  Bxe6  21.dxe6  Once more, this pawn will be the final nail in the coffin of Black's position.  21...Be5  22.Be4  22...Qe7  23.Qd5  Rb8  24.Bxf5  gxf5  25.g3+-  White will break through on the kingside. }
19. Ne6
{ White engages in a long-term pawn sacrifice, which can be classified under the no-brainer category. }
19... Bxe6 20. dxe6 Nhg7 21. Be4 Qe7 22. Qb1
{ Our super engine of today declares  22.Qf3  as stronger, but the text move is good enough. }
22... Nxe6 23. Nc3
{ I love this position. Black is a useless pawn up and very good at demonstrating that he is the rightful owner of the square d4. In terms of piece activity, however, he cannot compete. }
23... Nd8 24. Nd5 Qd7 { 24...Qf7?  25.Rf3+- } 25. Qb5 Rc6 26. Bxf5
{ White parts with his monster bishop, because harvest time has begun. } 26...
gxf5
{ 26...Qxf5  27.Bh6  Rf7  28.Rf3  Qe6  29.Ree3  Smells like zugzwang.  29...Bg7  30.Rxf7  Qxf7  31.Bg5  Ne6  32.Ne7++-  . }
27. Rg3+ Kh8 28. Bh6 Rf7 29. Nxf6 Rxf6 30. Bg7+
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@ Jenkins,R @@StartBracket@@2117@@EndBracket@@-Cunha,E @@StartBracket@@2217@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2013. }
