[Black "9.b4 Kh8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 Kh8
{ This move looks a bit artificial because it can't be said that Black is undertaking anything. On the other hand, closed positions allow for slow maneuvering and we already know, what this move is good for, namely clearing the square g8 for the knight e7 and dodging potential tricks on the a2-g8 diagonal. Apart from that, 9...Kh8 has waiting-move qualities and is good for collecting information. White now has the choice between two moves of roughly equal strength. }
10. a4 Neg8
{ Black follows through with his plan to improve his worst placed piece. Even though this is consistent and logical in itself, it can be criticized from a holistic perspective. The point is, that there were more urgent things to do. }
11. c5 Nh5 12. Re1 { This flexible move is useful against ...Nh5. } 12... f5
{ 12...Nf4?  13.Bf1  f5  0-1 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ Jacquet,F-Gicquel,F @@StartBracket@@2070@@EndBracket@@ Creon 1999,  14.exf5Ν  Bxf5  15.Bxf4  exf4  16.Rc1+-  Black's position is full of soft spots. }
13. exf5
{ Improving on the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Lalic, B @@StartBracket@@2575@@EndBracket@@-Hebden, M @@StartBracket@@2540@@EndBracket@@ Cambridge 1996, where the unnecessarily passive  13.Nd2  was played. }
13... Bxf5 14. a5
{ Once more, pushing the a-pawn is a useful tool. Black is in a dilemma and has to decide between two evils. }
14... a6
{ This stops the positional threat of 15.a6, but now, depending on the course of the game, either the square b6 will become weak or the a-pawn itself. }
15. Ra3 Nf4 16. Bf1 Nf6 17. Rb3
{ That's both, prophylaxis against ...dxc5 and preparation of b4-b5. } 17...
Bg4
{ 17...dxc5?  18.Rxe5+-   17...Qd7  18.h3+-  At some point, g2-g4 might be a threat. Right now, White would like to exchange Black's light-squared bishop. }
18. Bxf4 exf4
{ Obviously, the soft spot e6 is very exposed in this structure. } 19. h3 Bxf3
20. Qxf3 Nd7 21. Ne4 Qe7
{ 21...Ne5  22.Qd1+-  followed by b5 is similar to the main line. } 22. Rbb1
Ne5
{ This might be a good example of an optical illusion. Apparently, Black has solved most of his problems, by liberating his bishop and installing his knight in the center. Now, guess how Stockfish evaluates the situation? It sees White more than 2.5 pawn units ahead. The reason for this are Black's many weaknesses. We will have a look at these, when the tension has resolved. }
23. Qa3 Rfd8
{ 23...g5  24.b5  g4  25.bxa6  bxa6  26.hxg4  Qh4  This isn't much of an attack.  27.Rb7  Rae8  28.Rxc7  Nxg4  29.Qh3  Qxh3  30.gxh3  Nf6  31.Bd3  Nxd5  32.Rd7+-  White is winning material. }
24. cxd6 { 24.b5  also wins. } 24... cxd6 25. b5 axb5 26. Rxb5 Rd7 27. Rb6 Rad8
28. Qb4 h6 29. Rb1
{ Black can stay in the game with  29...Ra8  , but he still is lost in the long run.  White might put the rook from b1 to b5 or try to accomplish Nd2-b3-d4-e6. }
*

