10. a4 Nfg8 11. c5 f5 12. Nd2 Bh6
{ Exchanging the bad King's Indian bishop via h6 is a motif, we have seen several times in the previous chapters. When doing so, Black really has to pick his spots. As was already mentioned, the bishop fulfills an important prophylactic task, by defending the king and by making the pawn-break f2-f4 unattractive for White. }
13. Nc4 Bxc1 14. Rxc1 fxe4
{ For the sake of preventing f4, Black invites the knight to e4, with bad consequences for the pawn d6.   14...Nf6  15.f4+-   14...f4  This is what you normally want to play after the exchange. The problem is, that White is in a position to directly attack the c7-d6 structure.  15.Nb5!  Rf6  16.Nxc7!  This is the most straight-forward line.  16...Qxc7  17.cxd6  Rxd6  18.Nxe5  Qb8  19.Nf7+  Kg7  20.Nxd6  Qxd6  21.Qd4+  Kf8  22.Rfd1+-  Black cannot prevent the pawns from rolling. }
15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Nxe4 Nf5 { 16...Nf6  17.Nexd6  Nexd5  18.Bf3  Be6  19.Re1+- }
17. Bg4 Ngh6
{ Trying to hold on to the d-pawn a bit longer, compared to the game.   17...Nd4  18.Bxc8  Rxc8  19.Nexd6+-  1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Polgar,J @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@-Kurpiewski,S @@StartBracket@@2164@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2011. }
18. Bxf5 Nxf5 19. f4 exf4 20. Rxf4 Qe7 21. g4
{ After the d-pawn is captured, Black's king will become the next target. } *

