[Black "9.b4 h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5
Ne7 9. b4 h6
{ This move looks a bit slow, like other non-critical move nine options. In reality, it is hardly worse than any other move and is likely to transpose to lines we have already covered. Black prevents Bg5 and especially Ng5 for good, which constitutes a problem after Black plays ...f7-f5. Additionally, he could now push his g-pawn, if necessary, or use the vacant square h7 for his king or knight.   The biggest motivation to play the text move might be a little trap.  10.c5?  would now be countered by  10...c6!  , when White can only claim a slight advantage. }
10. a4 { 10.Nd2  is an equivalent alternative. } 10... Ne8 11. c5 a5
{ This just helps White to bring his dark-squared bishop into play. } 12. Ba3
axb4 13. Bxb4 f5 14. Nd2 fxe4
{ Black tries to activates his pieces, but has to surrender the square e4 to that end.   14...Kh7  15.a5  Ng8  16.Nc4  Ngf6  17.exf5  Bxf5  18.Qb3+-  White may continue with Rad1, followed by cxd6 cxd6 and Nb5. }
15. Ndxe4 Nf5 16. Bd3 Nd4 17. cxd6 Nxd6
{ 17...cxd6  18.a5  Bf5  19.Rb1  Kh7  20.f3   Black passive position makes the engine suggest the exchange sacrifice  20...Rxa5  , which however, cannot save the draw. If Black stays put, White will continue with  Nb6  and  Nc4  , enhancing the pressure on the d-pawn.  20...Rf7  21.Na4+- }
18. Nxd6 cxd6 19. Ne4 Nf5 20. a5
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Aalders, P-Van Ginkel,H Leiden 2009. White played a flawless game so far, which is remarkable for a player of his category. For me this is an indication for the logical and straight-forward nature of the Bayonet Attack. The next step could be to transfer the rook to b6. Later the bishop might reappear on b4, while the queen could contribute from a3. }
