17... cxd6 18. a5
{ Black's minor pieces are extremely restricted in this structure. } 18... Ng8
{ 18...fxe4  19.Nxe4  Ra6  20.Rb1+-  As usual, Black's position is a mixture of weak pawns and passive pieces. }
19. Qb3 Nf6 { 19...fxe4  20.Qb6  Nf6  21.Rfb1+-  Black is losing his d-pawn. }
20. Qb4 Ne8 21. Nb5 Ra6
{ That's objectively not the best move, but the only one holding on to the pawn d6. }
22. Nb6 fxe4 23. Nc3 Ra7 24. Nxc8 Qxc8 25. Nxe4
{ Black's position lacks both, integrity and activity. } 25... Qd8 26. Rfd1 Rg8
{ Clearing the square f8 for the bishop, so that the knight can move. } 27. g3
Nf6 28. h4 { Not  28.Nxd6?  Bf8  . } 28... Nxe4 29. Qxe4 Rxa5 30. Rxa5 Qxa5
{ Even after this liberating sequence, Black is dead lost, because his king is not safe. }
31. Bd3 Bf6 32. Qf3 Qd8 33. h5 Kh8 34. Bxg6
{ White will finally attack on the light squares, where he possesses an extra piece. }
