9... a6
{ I would say, this is the best of the rest. Black combines some kind of accelerated prophylaxis against the push a2-a4-a5-a6 and against Nb5 ideas with a little trap.   After  10.c5?  c6  he would have accomplished near-equality. }
10. a4
{ Funnily enough, after  10...a5!  @@StartBracket@@I know, nobody would play that@@EndBracket@@  11.bxa5  Rxa5  12.Ba3   Instead of  Ba3  , White could make a counter-semi-waiting move by playing the useful  12.h3!?  , preparing a potential Be3.  12...b6  ,  Black still has a playable position. The reason for this is, that the Ba3-b4 setup is especially strong with Black's knight on d7. So here White is a tempo up, but Black can put his knight on a better square. }
10... Nh5 11. Re1 f5
